Winner 36% Yes, of Course.... Wait wait there were multiple options for no.... Alright (looks carefully at notes) 40% Combined No, Missouri is Clearly part of the South/Missouri is Part of the Ozarks a Smaller yet Proud Region! (21%/19%) While in the end the votes cast No, the fact that it was all so close really epitomizes how odd American Cultures, Politics and States can be. Missouri has always been the odd one. In the Midwest the Great Plains states of the Dakotas, Nebraska and Kansas have always been more akin to being Great Plains and merely adjacent to the Midwest. Accepted as part of the "Inland Empire" as it is sometimes affectionately called but all vastly different from the Great Lake States and the two primarily Mississippian states of Iowa & Missouri. While there is rarely contention over Iowa being midwestern even though much of its western half is part of the Great Plains to some extent, the same cannot be said for Missouri where Ozark culture, Southern accents and it's status as a border state in the Civil War have given it a unique feel in comparison to the other Midwestern states that border it. On top of all this Missouri has a complex mixture of history from the Missouri Rhineland in its central riverlands and vineyards to various famous cowboys who found their way there. The state is a mixture of beautiful forests, farm fields and riverlands. Though Missouri is also arguably the most indicative of the "Redneck Riviera" those cultures that persist along the Mississippi and who hold great stock and pride in themselves, for good reason. As someone from the Midwest (Iowa) who has lived in two other states, I will say Missouri always felt like the odd one out. You felt like you were in a completely different country going there, though the same couldn't be said of Illinois or Wisconsin. Which felt more like a regional shift in the Midwest at least outside of Chicago or the Superior Separatist Movement regions. Overall No State truly fits its macro-group. But whether Missouri is more Dixie or Ozark, Redneck Riviera or Middle America I suppose comes down to personal interpretation. To me it will always seem more a part of Dixie than the Midwest, a definitively Ozark state. An Island of their own. I suppose time will tell if this is just the unique state that Missouri is or if one of those cultural trends will win out on the National stage. But for now Missouri is definitely Missouri.

Mountain Goat Nanny This female mountain goat (also called a doe or nanny) was found and photographed just under the top of Hurricane Ridge on the Washington's Olympic Penisula. Too busy eating to worry about a human nearby, she did keep an eye on me and her youngster (also called a kid) who was learning which plants to eat by copying its mother. See more at: www.richleighton.com

Bird's Nest Fungi These fascinating bird's nest fungi found near the base of a huge waterfall in Oregon's Marion County, just east of Salem are one of the many natural curiosities found in the Pacific Northwest. While it may not look like it, these are actually an unusual type of mushroom, rather than a type of lichen. These still have their spores (they look like eggs in a nest) but will expel them with raindrops during a rainstorm, spreading their DNA on the forest floor for the next generation to spread and prosper. See more at: www.richleighton.com

Lichen Agaric This common mushroom is usually found growing with or among lichens on rotting logs, decaying wood, or in organically-rich soil. While regularly seen across most of the northern hemisphere, it is found most frequently closer to the Arctic. This one was found on West Tiger Mountain in Washington State. See more at: www.richleighton.com

But the way I could put it in as American terms as possible is that one may be Rocky Road and another Moose Tracks but its all Ice Cream. This compounded by the fact sometimes whole towns or regions would be emptied out of Europe. Irish Clans that are no longer in Ireland, The Hesse who are no longer in Hesse. America may not be our cradle but it shall be our descendants, for us this is still a Spiritual Frontier, a homestead somewhere between the Wise River Rat, Hardened Mountain Man and Magical Hobo. Having a Bison for a neighbor and a Bear to play Euchre with. Simultaneously too Feral and too American for Europe to deal with on mass. Halloween Rewind I love Halloween. I love the Halloween season. I've loved it when I was a kid going as a Werewolf, Pirate Ghost and Post-Apocalyptic Raider house to house Trick R' Treating. It has been my favorite Holiday since I can remember and to be honest it's never been about the candy. It was about the feel of Halloween, while I was young I didn't quite understand it, we've all heard the "Halloween was Invented by the Candy Companies" line at some point, but that is a lie. Halloween is a very, very old Holiday. Last year we posted many times on the Lore and History of Halloween and its customs, rather than rehash the same ideas by rote I thought I'd just collect them for ease of access. 2021 Halloween Posts Trick R' Treating Spirit Animals Witch Gods The Eternal Hunter Masking Ghosts Goblins The Grim Reaper Veles & The Dead Will-O-The-Wisp Chernobog Black Dogs The Wild Huntress Vampires Goddesses of Death Food of the Dead Samhain & The Bear King Booo! Fairy Godmothers Graveyard Picnics Fear The God of Gallows Fairy Toadstool Freak Shows Liminal Spaces La Castanyada Halloween Apples Halloween Around the World I Love Halloween Scarecrows Halloween, like the various other Holidays for the Dead found across our lands, is a season. It is not a single day. None of our ancient holidays are bound by calendar dates, you can feel it in the air! Right beside the crisp fall breeze. You can feel something more in the air when the Ghosts & Banshees, Gnomes & Goblins are all ready to revel alongside us! Despite all the pushback Halloween has received from the powers that be it is still to this day a Holiday that is beloved and treasured. I hope that all of us enjoy it to the fullest extent that we are able, both the living and the dead. Sincerely I.M.Knosp & J.A. Coburn of Hyperborean Radio (Uncensored)

Pikes Peak, America's Mountain Pike's Peak has largely faded from the larger consciousness of America, but it was once a central part of our folklore and legends. After Columbia was given Uncle Sam as a "Brother" Uncle Sam was said to use Pike's Peak as his throne through which he could look out across America. Today Pike's Peak is largely forgotten, but it still is rife with lore of Cryptids, Wildmen, Miracles, Aliens, and Giant Man Eating rats. A strange "Byway of the Bizarre" of the American West.

cleaned_message: Northern Cardinals The Cardinal is one of the most popular birds of North America named after the Cardinals of the Catholic Church due to their red coloration, which also leads to their other less common name of "Redbird". Northern Cardinals are also often used as Yuletide decorations and symbols likely due to their overwintering and red coloration upon white snow. They have a distinct Whistling Song that is hard to mistake for another birds and have beautiful woven nests with speckled eggs. They are the State Bird of: Illinois, Indiana, Kentucky, North Carolina, Ohio, Virginia and West Virginia. They are also the namesake of several sports teams including the St. Louis Cardinals (MLB) and the Arizona Cardinals (NFL) The Cardinal was once prized as a pet bird but it was rendered illegal to keep them as pets in 1918. The Northern Cardinal carries the nickname of America's Favorite Backyard Bird and enjoy Sunflower and Safflower Seeds in bird feeders.

California Mussels These common native mussels are found along the North America's West Coast from Alaska to Baja California in Mexico, and are found in massive colonies on the rocky coastline, often easily seen at low tide above the waterline. Archeological evidence shows these edible mollusks have been an important food source to humans for the past 12,000 years or more. These barnacle-covered mussels were found at low tide on Crescent Beach on Northern Oregon's Pacific Coast. See more at: www.richleighton.com

cleaned_message: Black-crowned Night Heron The black-crowned night heron is one of the most elusive species of heron in North America, and can be found throughout most of the world on every continent except Australia and Antarctica. Active primarily at night and nearly invisible during the day, these ambush hunters fish the water's edge for fish, reptiles, insects, crustaceans, mussels, clams, small rodents and anything else they can overpower. This one was found stalking its prey in the early evening in Fort Myers, Florida. See more at: www.richleighton.com

Maple Syrup & America Our people have been making Tree syrup for a very long time, but the most quintessential Tree Syrup of North America is Maple Syrup, it went on Paul Bunyan's Flapjacks, its the pride of Vermont and much of the Northeastern United States. We began tapping American Sugar Maple Trees way back in the 1500's and the rest is history. Each region thinks it has the best Maple Syrup, with Vermont and Canada being the most fervent in their Maple Syrup adoration. Syrup producing areas will often use Maple Syrup as their only sweetener, with the production, Maple Forests, and use of the syrup taking on near spiritual components. Personally I think the Maple Syrup from my Home State of Iowa is the best. The Syrup can be further processed into an amber like substance that can be made into "Maple Sugar". P.S.- The Amerindians did not have Syrup they had the Sap, but the making of it into Syrup was a Hyperborean addition much like we already did with other trees such as Birch.

Watershed Democracy: The Plan of John Wesley Powell John Wesley Powell was an American Veteran, Scientist, Ethnologist and Passionate Advocate of Ecology. Whose experiences exploring the mostly unexplored Western USA along the Green and Colorado Rivers would radically change him, inspiring him of the necessity of what came to be called "Watershed Democracy" yet what is that and who is this bearded bestial looking man anyway? Born in Mount Morris, New York in the Spring of 1834 Powell went on to fight in the Civil War where he lost most of his right arm from a Mini√© ball at the Battle of Shiloh, forever leaving him with but a stump where his arm used to be. Not long after he would lead several expeditions to chart the West, though they were perilous, one he undertook with ten men and several rowboats down the Green and Colorado Rivers. Only to come out in the end with 6 half naked men and a few pounds of moldy flour between them. He'd become an American Hero but was forever changed by his experiences. After his expeditions, he advocated that America must carefully settle the West as unlike the bounty of the Mississippi and Great Lakes that the East has, most of the West was a Desert. Using a combination of Mountains, Forests and Rivers of the Land he and his team charted the Western Watersheds and advocated State and Country Boundaries to be based around these natural land marks to avoid conflict and the destruction of the Land. However between his stubborn, wild and passionate demeanor and the fact he was going against the Narrative of the Time of the endless bounties of the West and of Gods divine intent for America his ideas were rejected and most senators of the time ended up detesting Powell and his ideas. Yet one wonders what may have happened had his idea been heeded, how different the map would be? Would the Dust Bowl Never happen? Would the Colorado River still charge forth into Mexico? No one can deny, his prediction of the conflict wrought by the scarce water of the West was all too prophetic.

Thimbleberries The thimbleberry is one of those often overlooked, highly under-appreciated wild berries that deserves a lot more credit than it gets. Found in all of the western states, and Canadian provinces and all around the Great Lakes, both in the United States and Canada the humble thimbleberry is considered by many to be superior than any raspberry. It is easily recognized in the wild by its large, papery maple-shaped leaves and completely thornless stalks. The tart, intensely fruity, high in Vitamin C berries are used to make some of the best jellies, and are often added to other berries such as blueberries, blackberries and raspberries to kick up the sweetness and flavor. These were found growing above Lake McDonald in Montana's Glacier National Park. See more at: www.richleighton.com

Barn Quilts If you've driven across Rural America you have probably seen a painted Barn Quilt. Hanging on the side of a house or barn these large square examples of Folk Art have a rich history stretching back to before the founding of the country. Similar in appearance to the Pennsylvania Dutch Hex Sign the Barn Quilt is less specific to an individual group and is practiced in Rural areas from the East Coast through to the Southwest. Though they are most well known from the Midwest where certain areas have a painted Quilt Square on pretty much every barn if not multiples. A Barn Quilt is rather simple in idea but immensely varied in design. As the Barn Quilt can be any pattern or shape but is most often painted with Quilt patterns and designs. Such as Corn and Beans, Jacob‚Äôs ladder, Compass Star and Carpenter‚Äôs Wheel, among many others. Many are based off patterns that have been passed down in family lines making the Barn Quilts a form of familial Heraldry. Other Barn Quilts will use regional, local or even historic patterns to paint their Barn Quilts. Many of the Barn Quilts are painted in honor of historic moments and even in memory of a loved one. Despite the iconic Folk Paintings they are today, the oldest Barn Quilts are thought to be pictures sewn into Quilts and Hung on the Side as a way to communicate who lived there or even occupation. They have since exploded in popularity since the turn of the millennia and become a popular tourist attraction with several Barn Quilt Trails popping up. (Some people who will not be named because I don't agree with disparaging the differently abled think they invented it in 2000) Do You Know of Any Barn Quilts? Do You Have Any Family or Local Patterns You'd Like to Make Into a Barn Quilt?

She'll Be Comin' Round The Mountain You've probably heard of the well known folk song "She'll be Comin' Round the Mountain" But did you know its origins? If one does a quick glance around the interwebs they will see claims it originated as a Christian Song specifically in Ameriblack Circles. Or that it started life as "When the Chariot Comes" that it was a reference to The Underground Railroad and later used for Mother Jones a Labor Activist... This is all complete and utter Sh*t. The Song is actually about what else, a prostitute. It was sung by workmen specifically miners and the like who would often look forward to the arrival of or traveling to "Entertainers" specifically of the female variety. Though in the modern day this may seem crude the reality is it was not uncommon outside of the heavily Puritanical areas of the United States Prostitutes' were common and might even have status. Folklore is replete with them such as the magical Brothels of Paul Bunyan Lore or the beloved Mate of Doc Holliday Big Nose Kate or even Pecos Bill's true love Slue Foot Sue. Like most of these elements of American Folklore repeated attempts have been made to clean up the Song rebranding it, changing history in order to fit the false idea of a heavily Christian and prudish nation (Prudish Nations Don't Make Cowboys). The Song despite being considered a Children's Folk Song is more of a Workmen's song expressing their excitement for the prostitutes and the lyrics are all thinly veiled references to the acts and joys the men would associate with these women. The Six White Horses are the Men Lining up to be "Ridden" while many of the other lyrics change too often and have been altered deliberately to reveal the songs original meaning. Don't let them Destroy Our Folklore and Our History.

cleaned_message: California Gull The California gull is a medium-sized, common migratory gull found across most of the western half of North America. Primarily feeding on fish, insects and eggs, it is a well-known scavenger of trash and garbage. It breeds far inland as far as Colorado north to Canada's Manitoba and the Northwest Territories, but it always returns to the Pacific Coast in the winter. This one was among many found in Los Angeles, California near Del Rey Lagoon on a warm, sunny springtime afternoon. See more at: www.richleighton.com

The Angel Oak The Angel Oak is a giant Southern Live Oak in Charleston, South Carolina. It is over 66 feet tall and 28 feet in circumference. It's longest branch measures over 180 feet long. The shade is produces cover over 17,000 square feet. The tree is so big that other plants such as ferns grow in its branches. The tree is said to be haunted with many spirits of the dead frequenting this sacred tree. It is around 400-500 years old about the age of the American people (not counting Vinland or Pre-Contact White Tribes).

The Battle For the American Spirit I don't need to tell you American history is complicated and has been deliberately misrepresented for decades if not centuries. There has been an ongoing battle, a war for the Soul of America, for "The American Spirit". I am not referring to the oft declared war between Good and Evil, or any machinations of the Devil. No this battle is much more shades of Green than black and white. The battle between the freedom to be as we may and that of a controlling overarching doctrine. One could call it the war of the Pagan vs the Puritan. Though it is more complicated than that. While we are often told of The Quakers and The Pilgrims, we are rarely told of the Mountain Folk or the "Werewolves and Witches" who escaped the flames of Europe and brought their Wild Hearts to American Shores. We are told of "In God We Trust" but rarely its precursors of "E Pluribus Unum" or "Mind Your Business". But if you dig a bit deeper you find centuries of warring ideas, the heathen-like Cedar cutters forced off their hard won homes by would be land barons, the Mountain Folk of Appalachia forcing away the IRS or National Guard. Stories of Old West Psychopomps that take the form of Undertakers, Forest God Lumberjacks, Giant Sailors Atop Clouds, or of the Fallen Warriors Who Dwell in the Meadows of Fiddlers Green, of a God of Liberty who came to Washington, Veneration of the Beloved God Columbia, of a Deified Pioneer or Mountain Men Hermits and Wild Berserkers, of River Gods and Freshwater Faeries, of Dogmen who fought in the civil war, of ancient blond and red haired bear men, of flying Yuletide Elves and Ghost Riders in the Sky. This is a land where Folk Songs challenged Jesus to a Fight and Bear Gods greet the Worthy, where Bees are kept in Mountain Kitchens and Bison come to tea. This is the land I value so, this is the land I live in, this is the side of the story I treasure.

Xenophilia: Salmon and Ravens I have seen many individuals (My younger self included) be enamored with the art of the Haida and other Pacific Northwest Injun tribes. Especially in regards to the Raven and Salmon aspect of their culture, to the point they adopt it. Which to me is rather silly, we have our own raven and salmon lore libraries of it, no need to adopt foreign symbols we have our own. Both of these animals are sacred to us as much or more so then the PNW Injuns. The Salmon of Knowledge, the Ravens of Apollo, Othin, and the Morrigan. Loki as a Salmon god, etc. No need to feel guilty at finding them important or even spiritual, and no need to adopt Haida symbols or get Haida tattoos, we have our own symbols, lore, and meaning with these animals whether in Europe or America. The Rivers of Ireland or of the Northwoods of Paul Bunyan's Domain. Remember that Hyperboreans. The North is our home.

Banjo Playing Frogs Banjo's are a staple of the American South (They are often attributed to African instruments..... you know all the famous African string instruments like ummm..... yeah that's bullshit) it is used in Cajun, Appalachian, Bluegrass, and even Dixie Music. It was invented likely by poor Southerners who could not afford professionally made instruments. Frogs are often depicted in folk art and folklore as playing the banjo (though it is a favorite instrument of many southern critters) likely due to the it sounding similar to their mating croaks. This innocuous imagery eventually made its way to the most famous American Frog. Kermit, the Frog of the Muppets who famously plays a Banjo in his swamp.

The Problem with American Nationalism There is no American DNA. Therefore there is no American Nation by the True Meaning of the Word. This may seem odd but I often find American Nationalism rather cringe. To be clear there are many many issues and the forced diversity, DEI and rampant immigration both legal and illegal are issues this country has but "Nationalism" in America is a confusing topic. Irish, Germans, Italians, Slavs that came over here weren't exactly welcome. There have been constant failed attempts to homogenize American Culture and on top of that by allowing all the Not-Us into the country in droves we gave up our ancestral claim to the land by right of conquest and now simply live here. A Hoosier is not a Tar Heel is not a Cajun is not a Yankee. There are many subgroups in America that up until now had at least some reason to have a shared identity or purpose but that is no longer the case. The reason "American Identity" is something that seems so quickly to become generic and downright saccharine is because trying to figure out how people from Rural West Virginia and the Mormons of Salt Lake City are the Same People is a fools errand. They aren't. We know they aren't. They are "American" in the same way Europeans are "European" the core difference being they don't even have the genetic lineage to claim that most groups in America are "Immigrants" or more accurately "Conquerors" since many groups that came here during our history actively aided in some fashion of the conquest of the American Empire. Now what America has is a free for all. We are defined as a whole by Geography and nothing more. The land of Cascadia and the Land of New England do not even have enough shared history to bother calling them the same country besides legalities. If we wish to defend this land, to reconquer it and claim it as ours than the first thing we need to do is acknowledge these sub-groups because "American" is generic, but the smaller Sub-Groups of loosely confederated tribes are what made us strong and what make up what we call America. If you have to whittle the entire country down to Flags, Beer, Guns and Pick Up Trucks. Or some Melting Pot Nation of Immigrants BS than we've already lost. There are rich "Cultures" here, PLURAL. But pretending what the founding documents say is somehow the reality is like claiming anything written into Law is reality and not wishful thinking. "One Nation Under God" was Wishful thinking. American's are not a Nation nor under One God, we are a Confederation for better or worse. If we don't acknowledge this we will lose.

Why the Underwear on the Outside? If you've ever seen the original designs for Superheroes especially those like Superman you have had the urge to or made the joke about him wearing his underwear on the outside. While this is a head scratcher in the modern day it actually makes total sense when the comics first appeared. As the strongmen acts of the time that populated boardwalks and carnivals often featured scantily clad Adonis' with nothing but boots and a pair of "Trunks" or as we would call them today "Speedos" the incorporation of this imagery into the costumes of Superheroes was meant to show their massive strength and power. As the culture shifted we lost context and it became point of mockery for the Superhero Genre.

An Enormous Pyramid where a large amount of trees grow. By the time Paul and his camp reached the top the bottom had regrown. The Chuck Wagon Quintessentially American, The Chuck Wagon was used on Cattle Drives (mostly in Texas) as a means of keeping up morale with good food and as a means to attract the best of the Cowboys to run the cattle drive. The Chuck Wagon often used easy to preserve items such as Beans, Salted Meats (Especially Beef), Coffee, Onions, Potatoes, Lard and Flour. The Chuck Wagon was often manned by a talented cook who was typically ill tempered due to lack of sleep and long hours. He was second only to the trail boss and had many nicknames including Cookie, Coosie, Sourdough, Puncher, Greasy Belly, Dough Boxer, Old Lady, etc. While the Chuck Wagon fell out of fashion after the 1880's it eventually gave way to both the American Diner and the Modern Food Truck. It's culinary mainstays and adaptable nature of its cooks fed into much of modern American cuisine. It's Name of the "Chuck" wagon can be traced to either a slang word for food or its supposed inventor Charles "Chuck" Goodnight.

What Do These Gods Have In Common? After many claims concerning "But I'm -???- and I can't find any information." Let us begin with the obvious for America. The Bear: As America was settled we returned to our wild natures and with it came to recognize once more our Forest Cousin. We again learned and lived alongside the most beloved of animals The Bear, The Face of Gods. Columbia: American War Goddess and Alma Mater. She who nourishes the ideals of Life, Liberty and the Pursuit of Happiness. She who joins us when we are led astray. So beloved songs were sung to her, giant idols carved, people once even called America Columbia. Paul Bunyan: Born of trees and mountains, his axe crafted by dwarves and whose mighty crew molded the nations landscape reminding man how to live with nature. When his lessons were scorned Paul took his leave to the North Pole where he and babe now create the Northern Lights. Kris Kringle: Santa Claus, the God of Christmas, Children, Hope and Winter Storms, The King of the North and Beloved Dead who gives gifts to the noblest of children and punishes the worst. Embodying the Spirit of Giving and Communal bonds. Joe Magarac: The Spirit of American Steel and God of crafting, Industrious and Hard Work, Born of Storms and Mountain Ore. He so loved his people that he melted his metal flesh into the steel itself so that they may work and flourish. Lady Luck: The most fickle of Gods, credited with the Revolutionary Victory that created America, today her shrine can be found, it is known as Las Vegas. Where the Lucky and Unlucky alike court her favor. Honorable Mentions: Lady Liberty, Old Man of the Mountain, Johhny Appleseed, Wildmen, Ghosts, Dogmen, Pecos Bill, Washington, Green Man, Thor, Holda, Groundhog, Stag, Dwarves, Davy Jones, Davy Crockett, Puck, Trolls, Elves, Faerie, Grim Reaper, Wolf, Bobcat, Undertaker, Saint of Killers, Bison, Fox, Raccoon, Raven, Hunter, The Morrigan, Mothman, The Dagda, Robin, Owl, Salmon, The Sandman, Easter, Hermes, Crow, Othin, Neptune, Jersey Devil...

The Origin of Paul Bunyan's Ax One of the most iconic tools of any being or hero of folklore is the ax of Paul Bunyan. Now there are many tales told of how Paul came by his signature ax, the most common is that he made it himself pulling a whole towering pine tree up out of the ground to form the handle, yet perhaps my favorite has much more of that mythic nature to it that exists in many American myths but is so often buried by what sells at roadside attractions or Kids films. That he was given it by the spirits of the earth. Now see just like the Ax Paul himself has many origins from flocks of storks, to arriving washed up by the sea to being born of old trees and becoming a sort of forest god, but this one seems to follow the vein of Paul's origins that has him akin to Joe Magarac in that he was born of the mountains themselves. Molten ore flows through Paul's veins as much as steel forms the flesh of Joe. Born of the Earth it stands to reason he would pal around with spirits of the earth. Sometimes its dwarves, others gnomes, and some others are more generic in their earth spirits. But this story holds that Paul received his Ax as a gift from the Spirits of the Earth (Dwarves) and it was because he chose to leave his mountain home and go amongst man to show them how to live with nature. This was Paul's noble goal and his gift to his camp followers. It also shows why when people put profits before nature he fled North away from those who broke his heart. Either way Paul's Ax is an iconic image and is even a Trophy between two rival football teams.

The Mothman Mothman is a Cryptid or Spirit from Point Pleasant, West Virginia. He appeared during the time span of 1966-1967. He is described as having large wings and glowing red eyes. He is often thought to be a Sandhill crane or other bird. However, aside from the usual legends of flying over cars and scaring a passerby the Mothman is also connected to the deaths of 46 people as he was spotted and connected to the Silver Bridge Collapse in 1967. After this the Mothman became more associated with being an omen of destruction or misfortune, perhaps a spirit who feasts on fear?! In typical American Fashion the Mothman is often considered either a Nuclear Mutant or an Alien. As such the Men in Black ended up being mixed into the story somehow.

When Other Countries Have American Themed Restaurants Have you ever wondered if other Countries have American themed restaurants? Well turns out they do! The results are hilarious and amazing! Popular themes include 50's Diners, Cowboys, Steakhouse, Texan, BBQ, Burgers, Midwest or Sports Bar. Though Amerindian, Surfer and well known city dishes also happen. Japan has several including Bronco BIlly's serving famous American dishes like ‚ÄúI stewed the Bronco hamburger and beef muscle meat of collagen plentiful.‚Äù & who can forget traditional American Bacon boiled and served in the water it was boiled in just like Mom's. There is Indiana Caf√© in Paris which serves Traditional Hoosier Cuisine or Tex-Mex, order classic items like Nachos Indiana if you're feeling homesick. There are also chains such as Ireland's Eddie Rocket's which serves 50's Diner fare though if you want extra cheese you'll need to use the American phrase of "Pimped-Up" to let them know. Quite possibly one of the most beloved institutions and birthday party destination is Spur Steak Ranch with an Amerindian theme whose menu includes varieties of traditional American Schnitzel with Mushroom Soup atop it, Spur is beloved across South Africa. There's Old Wild West in Italy a bizarro Olive Garden. Moscow has Beverly Hills Diner complete with a Pulp fiction dance performed by staff to really make you feel American beside statues of Elvis and Betty Boop. As much as I may seem to be mocking these restaurants I actually love them! Americans don't tend to realize how unique our food is and often downplay it. In these restaurants abroad I am reminded of how interesting our culture can be via outside eyes. From Memphis Diner in Paris to the Yellow Rose of Texas in Peru if you're ever nearby and in need of a steak, burger, brownie, malt, pizza, chili or any other American Dish stop in. Just don't expect it to be quite what you'd get at home. Oh and American Cuisine abroad is quite expensive so you may want to save up first.

Elvis Presley & Captain Marvel Jr. It may seem odd but there was a time When Captain Marvel (Shazam! Not the Marvel Mary Sue) was one of the most popular characters in Pop Culture, so much so that the Fantastic figure gained a whole family of characters including Captain Marvel Jr. The whole "Marvel Family" included the abilities of Solomon (Wisdom), Hercules (Strength), Atlas (Stamina), Zeus (Power), Achilles (Courage), and Mercury (Speed) as well as some basic magical fantasy abilities. While the comics were stalled out due to being sued, the imagery of Captain Marvel Jr. kept going as Elvis Presley was a massive fan of the character and based his iconic look of blue suit, lightning symbolism, cape, and large collar and even the iconic Presley haircut off of Captain Marvel Jr. Making this obscure character one of the most prolific images of American Popular culture and music.

Prometheus & Methuselah If you've heard of the Bristlecone Pines of the Southwest you know they are estimated to be some of the oldest trees on earth. The current oldest Bristlecone Pine is Methuselah whose location is kept secret so as to avoid harm to the over 4,800 Year Old Tree. But there was once an older Bristlecone Pine known as Prometheus who was around 4,900 Years Old. Then Graduate Student Donald R. Currey was researching the Little Ice Age and with the Forestry Service gained permission to core the trees however... while stories vary and there is vast controversy surrounding it Currey's Increment borer broke and he received permission to fell the tree to access its rings. It was only then that they realized they had cut down one of if not the oldest tree in the Western Hemisphere. You can still find sections or pieces of Prometheus across various places including Nevada, Arizona and California.

When Japan Demanded American Mythology After Commodore Perry forced Japan to open its doors to the wider world and stop its centuries old policy of isolationism Edo Period Japan was hungry for American culture and Mythology, as they were in awe of this powerful country. They received it in the form of some simultaneously fascinating and hilarious depictions of the Founding Fathers including George Washington Punching a Tiger, fighting Asura (A Dharmic God) and being presided over by the goddess of America (Columbia). While Ben Franklin is depicted as a stoic warrior capable of holding and firing a cannon with his bare hands. While John Addams is a super human warrior whose mother is eaten by a snake, Addams than seeks out a Mountain Fairy and with the aid of the Fairy's giant Eagle defeats the giant Snake and avenges his mother. In a strange turn of events many in Japan actually still take these depictions as historic fact. With Washington even a "Kami" at the Hawaiian Shinto Temple.

Gustaf Tenggren & Early Disney One of the most beautiful parts of American Media and Culture were the early films of Disney which drew heavily from European Fairy Tales and Literature. The style was even based largely off these older illustrations. While Walt Disney himself was a talented animator it was a Swedish Immigrant turned American that can be thanked for much of the beauty of the art style. Gustaf Tenggren was a phenomenal and largely unknown artist inspired by the likes of John Bauer, Arthur Rackham, Edmund Dulac, Kay Nielsen, and Howard Pyle his Fairy Tale Illustrations serve as Concept Art that far outclasses even the finished product from Disney. It is he who can be thanked for the beautiful and whimsical designs of early Disney films like Pinocchio, Snow White, and Bambi. He deserves far more credit than he gets.

cleaned_message: Nursery Log This is a fantastic example of a nursery log. Many large trees start off at a disadvantage, and some trees seem to do best when they start off as a tiny sapling on top of a fallen log. As these saplings grow with more access to sunlight, the strongest outcompete the weakest and eventually the roots will reach the soil, resulting in a line of trees with exposed roots. In this example, a line of growing Sitka spruce trees flourish on what once was a huge fallen log, but is now decomposed by time and decay. See more at: www.richleighton.com

Black Huckleberry The black huckleberry is considered by many to be the prize of the mountain berries. These juicy, sweet member of the blueberry family are found from the Rocky Mountains to the Pacific Ocean (with a few isolated locations eastward) and have been enjoyed by wildlife and humans for millennia. This official state fruit of Idaho is a particularly important food source for grizzly and black bears, and traditionally the Native Americans have been eating them in dozens of different ways: fresh, dried, smoked, crushed up in soups or mixed with salmon roe - to name a few. These huckleberries were photographed (then eaten) just below the tree line at the edge of a subalpine meadow in the North Cascades National Park, near the Canadian border in Washington State. Mother's Day (A Son's Love) Dear Mothers Women from girlhood speak of the desire for unconditional love; but they have it already, or it is easily found if not. This love is to be found in your Sons. While it is true a Son might grow to dislike his Mother; love and like being two different things. But you can rest assured he will ALWAYS love his Mommy, without reservation. There is not a Son among the Hyperborean people; child or grown, that would not move the world to save his Mommy or even raise every last inch of it shaking the very roots of the Earth itself in vengeance of her. He will love her completely and truly for the entirety of his life from his first wail to his last gasp, even after she is gone. So raise your sons well! Be gentle with him. Guard his heart so that he might not become cruel, but remember; You are raising a Man. A child brought into this world through countless ages of great hardship and even greater joys, by you! Born and bred of love, a love whose sole purpose is to defend his people with the same vigor he would defend you. To safeguard the vulnerable but not the weak, to teach the lessons he has learned throughout his life so that those under his protection might thrive. So teach him well. Teach him the respect he is due and the responsibilities he must bear. Teach him of sacrifice and love. Teach him his value so that he might not settle, nor demand more than is his due. Teach him both his own value and the value of others. Teach him to think for himself. To question. To understand and see the world around him. Teach him a little rebellion is good for the soul of a Man and to be expected. But also teach him where to draw the line. To give respect but to demand it in return! Remember he's not the shield, nor is he the spear. He is the man who wields these tools! Not the tool to be wielded... Remember it's only through you he will learn what a woman SHOULD be, so be noble. Remember he will one day demand your example of womanhood in a wife of his own. A Woman who will in turn give you Grandchildren who will also honor their Grandmother; or not, in the same way he himself had been taught by you. Become honored. Raise your sons well. Raise them with the dignity and pride only a Mother can have in her Sons! Happy Mothers Day. We Will Always Love You Your Sons The Hyperborean Men of the World. Our Enemies Believe Our Lore, Even if We Do Not The felling of sacred trees, the slaying of the white stag, a coordinated attack has been set against our people, upon the symbols, stories, charms and monuments we hold so dear... and whether we believe it or not the ones that protect and watch over us. In many cases they have already succeeded, innumerable in Albion alone. Yet... there are those in which their machinations have shown but yet to come to pass. Such as The Ravens in the Tower of London and The Rollright Stones, both ancient charms of protection. The Ravens are a gift from the God-King Bran the Blessed. Who was slain in battle and whose severed head was buried facing out so that he could always watch over Albion. The proof of this are his ravens. Once nesting in a Sacred Grove but as the city grew over it they came into the Tower of London. It is said that so long as the ravens remain in the tower Albion shall never fall. The last time they all left the British Empire Collapsed. The 'Mayor' of London has made it clear he wishes to be rid of them... I wonder why? The Rollright Stones; an ancient stone circle approximately 4000 years old on the border of Oxfordshire & Warwickshire, are said to be the petrified remains of Knights of King Arthurs Court frozen by Merlin until Albions' Hour of Greatest Need. They have attempted to put a Road right through them... Like all stories there are many variations on the Ravens and Rollright Stones. All OF Our Lore. This is not the first time such attacks have happened even upon Albions' Shores. Centuries ago they drove out The Bear and The Wolf from the Isles as well as destroying beloved treasures. Now they do the same defacing our remaining "Idols" or eliminating the likes of both The Badger and The Hedgehog, beloved in Albions' animism and history. Our enemies know our Lore and what it means to us, this is War to them. It is we who seem to have forgotten. Why Are Things This Way? The lifestyle of the poor of a hundred years ago is now only available to the wealthy. To the point there are entire genres online of people living a life that would once have gotten you called "Vagrant" or "Hick" but because they've rebranded it to "Off Grid" or "Vanlife" it is now cool. Increasingly the dream is not to move to the big city, it's to escape it, but the small towns once populated by working class people whose ancestors had settled the town centuries past are now vacation homes, hunting cabins and the dominion of the upper class. Those that don't succumb to this fate succumb to urban sprawl or become one of the many ghosts towns that dot the countryside. As land prices skyrocket, and land taxes weigh people down generational homes are a thing of the past, you cannot build your own home even though such homes are often some of the most longstanding domiciles, people can no longer grow their own food in their own yards because they will catch a fine, increasingly the average joe can barely afford a cup of joe, but is expected to work to just survive and be thankful they escaped the horrors of the past, of an intact family living in the rural land growing much of their own food, sewing their own clothes and being self sufficient because they had to be, of having neighbors you knew and trusted, of having rivers to swim in and woods to hunt in! Such a life has become something only the wealthy can afford. While the average working class can barely afford a studio apartment. I do not write this to bag on the wealthy or chastise those who are able to live this kind of life, I merely write it to ask why? Why is the lifestyle the poor were once mocked for now out of their reach, while those with means glory in being able to experience it themselves? What are the consequences and conclusion of this course of action? And perhaps Why, if this is such an undesirable lifestyle did it become something that the rich possess and the poor lament? üèîHyperborean Radio (Uncensored)üå≤

Invincible Season 2 Review: A Disappointing Soap Opera of a Sequel The first season of Invincible was the best of a series of "Evil Superman" shows and films that came out around the same time. The sophomore season however was disappointing. No plot point was truly finished, one (as in the viewer) is left hanging by the end as characters go through trials and tribulations and deal with the fallout from the first seasons revelations. This is all well and good but drags on far too long - by which I mean the entire season. While I don't mind character development and more plot than just 4 episodes of Super Saiyan power ups this season felt like nothing happened. We are still ostensibly at the same place we were at the end of last season. It feels the entire time like the characters are running in place and getting nowhere fast. While there are a few quippy jokes that land, some meta humor that doesn't, the show is at it's core not a comedy but an action story. Invincible is an homage not a satire or parody. I have not read the comics so perhaps this was a faithful adaptation, perhaps not, but it introduces several characters without really giving them anything to do in regards to the main story. Each episode feels as if its building to something that never materializes, but most notably the entire show comes off as some sort of out of time series, with the second season premiering 2 years after the first and concluding 3 years after the first aired. The people who enjoyed the first season are in a different point in their life and Invincible seems as if it is trapped in the past. The world has changed so much in so short a time that the show becomes this odd bizarro depiction of both American Life and the World presented within. While I prefer escapist shows to not be dragged down by current events I couldn't help but watch the show as it seemed to pretend it was something it's not as if I was watching an aging millennial desperate to maintain some sort of cultural identity relevant in his early 20's well into his 30's. Stuck in a world and situation that doesn't reflect the current one it is trying to comment on. This would be all well and good if the show did not attempt such commentary at all, but in doing so it attempts to root itself in the world we live in now, or at least a version of it. As the show continues to walk in place and attempt to project or continue these character arcs. One question arises as to why we should care, the genre it spawns from is falling from cultural consciousness faster than the musical did, the characters seem stuck in the same roles they were in years ago while those outside of it are struggling or overcoming various things. The show in essence has lost anything that once made it special and instead has become a Soap Opera of Sorts, with characters that seem less and less relatable and more and more hollow. I will not be watching Season 3, on pure quality I would probably have given this season 2 maybe 3 stars if I was feeling generous. But I'll never get the 8 hours I spent watching this show back, the best I can do is hope that I can help others escape suffering the same fate. Invincible may be invincible but he is definitely not enjoyable, in fact if I had to rename the show and character it would simply be "Skippable". ‚≠êÔ∏è1 Star/out of 5

Atomic Tourism Over the Course of Four Decades the US Government conducted 928 Nuclear Bomb Tests in The Yucca Flats just over 60 miles outside Las Vegas. In true Las Vegas fashion they capitalized on the tests and began as the New York Times put it ‚Äúthe non- ancient but nonetheless honorable pastime of atom-bomb watching.‚Äù with Dawn-Bomb parties being held at businesses or on the hillsides just outside the blast radius with drinking and singing while they waited for the bomb to drop. Then wearing dark goggles and bracing themselves for the heat wave and raging winds people would gleefully watch the spectacle of the worlds largest bomb being dropped. Las Vegas even became known as "Atomic City" in their promotions of the cities Atomic Tourism. The Mushroom cloud became a popular symbol being made into fashion, candies, Toys, Showgirls Costumes, postcards, headdresses and even Miss Atomic Beauty Contests. The bombs were dropped around once every three weeks and even after the bomb dropped the craters were common tourist sites with people arriving to take pictures and look at the place the bomb had been dropped. Without this BOOM! in Atomic Tourism Las Vegas may never have become the city it is today. As the Cities custom of living in the "Now" was on full display here forget the worries of the Cold War with booze, singing and a giant bomb. Oh!.. and Don't Forget Your Wallet. Vegas Sure Won't.

Winner 41% Disney is a Complicated Company, with a Checkered History that Has Ranged from Good to Depraved. Disney has never been some beacon of Moral Righteousness, but I honestly can't think of a single massive company that is. Almost any of these responses could've been valid, which is why Multiple Choice wasn't a Choice. I wanted to see where people stood with the Mouse House and found that most people took the middle ground. Admitting Disney is a flawed and even depraved company, but has also been a leader in animation and at least during Walt's Tenure a place of magic and dreams. Even if there were still the omnipresent issues beneath the surface. Mickey Mouse, Donald Duck, Goofy and Pluto, Mary Poppins, Snow White and a seemingly endless repertoire of classics once beloved across the world. Now... Much like anything the positives that once existed have fallen away. Walt and his tenure are long gone, regardless of one's opinion of him. Successive Rulers were less visionary, more profit focused. Not that such things were unheard of before between the treatment of actors for Snow White and Peter Pan or the Misleading of the Influential Carl Barks, even attempts to copyright our ancestral cultures; Disney has never been spotless, but now that is all one can see. Disney is no longer the Magic Kingdom, it is the Mordor and Isengard upon the Shores of Florida and California. Consuming Dreams rather than spinning them in dwarven magic and elven craft into films that inspire. Now between the soulless remakes and sequels, attempts to copyright Our Gods, the attack on schools and even desecrating the graves of children. Disney has destroyed it's own legacy. But it's influence upon the world and especially the Medium of Animation can not be denied. Time will tell if that's enough to leave them as more than a footnote in history. Because the Future for Disney... is never a guarantee. Looking at you Bob Iger's Stocks.

When Americans Lived in Tree Stumps The ‚ÄúAncient sequoias,‚Äù ‚ÄúMammoths,‚Äù or ‚ÄúBig Trees‚Äù as John Muir called them -also redwoods- are the giant trees that once ruled over the West Coast. As a sort of primeval land this final frontier of the contiguous United States was a fabled realm for both Americans further East and for settlers coming from Europe to start a new life. Alongside the Gold Rush the most important industry in the area was the logging industry. Given the Fairy Tale and Mythic quality of the size of the trees it was natural that not only would it take months and months to cut them but that they would leave a rather impressive stump. Not ones to let things go to waste the Settlers took to the stumps turning them into hotels, dancefloors, Post Offices, barns and yes! Even Houses! With some being as small as a studio apartment while others were three stories tall! These fantastical Stump Houses are effectively the traditional houses of the Western Coastal States and they existed up into the 1990's as Roadside attractions and Local Landmarks such as the famous stump house in Eureka, California. Sadly many if not all have since rotted away. Though one can imagine the sight of neighborhoods built in the middle of the Forest with dance floors atop amber sealed stumps and homes fit for a Keebler Elf or Forest Faerie.

It's most notable trait is the odd Yellow Color chosen for the protagonists which are meant to be Middle Americans of European Descent. The Color was chosen for the innocuous reason of it being eye catching as people flipped through the channels. However! There is more to this choice than may first appear, knowingly or not they may have gotten closer to showing what we look like and it may be seen most blatantly in a throwaway joke from "22 Short Films About Springfield", the Same episode that gave the world the Steamed Hams Meme. When Lisa gets Gum in her blond hair she goes to the barber to get it out, first he cuts the hair away to remove the gum, revealing pale whitish skin beneath, implying that Lisa is covered head to toe in a Blond Pelt of Hair. While at first to us we may laugh at the ludicrous nature of this joke, it is actually closer to the truth than many may think. You see Hyperboreans, Occidentals, Caucasians, or more Commonly Called Whites or more narrowly "Europeans" are covered in a light undercoat of blond hair we affectionately call "Peach Fuzz" but is actually called Vellus Hair while invisible to us barring a ray of sunshine or lamplight, we notice when it isn't there and the other races simply do not have it. Chimera's may have it such as Ameriblacks having an odd patchy growth here or there, for us it coats us like a fine velvet causing a Halo effect, making us much softer to the touch. As well as being a means of staying warm and dry. To the other races however our Golden Coat is very easy to see, with some even calling us "The Hairy People" (Northern China) Or "Giant Pink Hairy Monsters" (Africans). Tribe & Facial Hair One of the most significant and distinguishing features of the Hyperborean Male is our voluminous beards "Our Manes". Not all of our beards are the same, any man who grows one is quick to notice the differences and eccentricities of each one, "my beard is not the same as your beard". Part of this is age, health and care but a lot of it comes down to tribe. Every Hyperborean tribe has a slightly different style of facial hair that grows naturally, to the point that one of the giveaways as to which ancestral group you belong to, whether it be Gaelic, Alpine, Scandinavian or Greek, is how the beard grows. One need not have one that can be tucked into one's belt but long and wild enough that its quirks and shape are more defined is more than enough to indicate ones ancestral roots. Each Tribal Group will differ within but broader trends are there, the flowy beards of the Gauls, the wavy and wooly beards of the Alps, the wild seemingly sentient beards of the Gaels, the curly beards of the Greeks. This is even present in the shape of the mustache as certain Spanish tribes Mustachios will grow with the trademark Spanish point, while the Gaulish Mustache will drape proudly from the upper lip, For the Alpine German's their mustache will fan out too thick and full to drape and rather jut out to the sides like a wild tree branches. The act of shaving one's beard for our Tribes is one of emasculation to remove an indication of heritage, of tribe. While it can make it a bit easier to ignore different groups in proximity to one another, as was commanded by Alexander the Great to make his men a bit less aware of their tribal loyalties. It is also a punishment historically to force a man to shave his mark of manhood. Notably the Church would punish the Pagan "Werewolves" with shaving, doing so for the reason by their own words "That when they died their ancestors would not recognize them". Deny the Defilement. Winner 67% No, This is My Home When I made this poll months back I was unsure of my answer. I was doubtful that the Midwest where I was born and live now could truly be home, or indeed anywhere on the North American continent. But this is a symptom of the times. But... yes this is my home, or at least where I hope to build it. When my ancestors came over the course of hundreds of years across this land settling the East Coast and as far West as Nebraska and the Far West they may have been homesick whether they came for opportunities here or lack thereof back home, if they were forced by court or by blade, they came here and made sacrifices generation after generation, many of which never knowing I or any of my fellows would come to be, we were an idea one that may never have crossed their minds. Then instead of thinking of what was missing, the thousands of years of history or the mountains my ancestors in the long ago lived in, I instead looked to how lucky I was. This continent, this land is unbelievably beautiful. Mountains that dwarf the likes of much of the world, freshwater seas you can sail like a Boreal Odysseus, and riches in ways that we cannot fathom. Trees fit for giants and seas of grass that seem to drown everything else but the storm and bleached bones. Animals that seem to ooze the age of the land. The gift of our ancestors may not have been the land we held for millennia but it was one they conquered and built for us, their bones are beneath our feet their ghosts were given to our monuments. I understand why many would wish to return, this place seems less and less like home the more we've let it slip. But I myself cannot throw away what our ancestors made for us. Rivers of blood, Oceans of sweat and host upon host of dead built this place for us, left it in its grandeur. I plan to stay and continue their calling. Who knows what the future brings, but I know I stand on a truly hard won foundation. This Land is My Land. This Land is Your Land. This Land Was Made For You and Me.

cleaned_message: William Holbrook Beard (1824 - 1900) What is satire but a preceding idea, forged from imagination? William was a prime example of a painter who threw out all expectations, to paint what most would have deemed peculiar, albeit appealing. He was an American painter, renowned for his whimsical or satirical depictions of animals, oftentimes bears, performing human-like activities. There doesn't appear to be any boundaries which control his subject matter, ensuring it remains tame or refined. It's clear he forged ahead, creating an engrossing world in which people would easily be transfixed to William's different approach to art. What fascinates me the most about his paintings are the pagan elements - almost straight out of an old European fairytale. Dancing bears? Frolicking Squirrels? Cackling witches upon their broomsticks? Much of which gave him vogue because who can really resist happy animals doing human things? Whether or not William drew inspiration from European folklore, the folklore is evident. It's almost as if he tried to create his own idea of the land of the Fae, but with a slight twist, applying it as an experiment to see how the subject matter interacts with the world of humans. The painting he did of Santa Claus is my personal favourite, and possibly one of the best paintings I've seen of Santa Claus, because that is exactly how I would imagine him coming to town, breaking through the veil of our world, bringing cheer and joy. William is easily in the top ten of my favourite artists because his paintings are a reminder of the rich tapestry of folklore we have, best to keep us in high-spirits in an increasingly dark and chaotic world. Escape to the world of dancing bears and animated forests for when you need a break from the muck of everyday life. Nashville is a city that is often thought as the center of Country Music as well as the most famous city in Tennessee. However beyond that I must admit to ignorance regarding it. Snowshoe Thompson Born in 1827, John Albert Thompson was a Norwegian-American considered to be the father of California skiing. Between 1856 and 1876, he delivered mail between Placerville, California, and Genoa, Nevada. Despite his nickname, Thompson did not use snowshoes but rather the method of cross country skiing from his homeland. The delivery trips usually took around 3 days. He carried no blanket and no weapons and claimed to have never lost his way in a blizzard. His preferred route was known as "Johnson's Cutoff,"which today is known as U.S. Route 55 from Placerville, California to South Lake Tahoe. Thompson Peak is a 9,340-ft summit in the Sierra Nevada that is named for him.

Happy Groundhog Day! Groundhog Day is one of my favorite Holidays. Its tongue-in-cheek nature, its simple and community focused elements all centered around a certain famous Seer, one Groundhog. Not Punxsutawney Phil though he is the most famous of "his" seers. The Groundhog himself is a bit different and hard to quantify. You see The Groundhog is a being that is both a delicious dinner and a delightful divinity. In the folklore The Groundhog is often attributed magnificent seer abilities, considered the one true weather prophet and to have been born in Chaos itself, recommended by Mother Earth as the one to search out for true prophecies. Much like other animal spirits and Gods however, The Groundhog exists in the Groundhogs themselves, less in a specific incarnation and more within all of them. The Groundhog exists in a unique cross section of animals, over the years he has been attributed both the old Lore of the Bear Cult of the Germans and the Gaels as well as that of smaller burrowing animals such as rabbits and marmots. Similar to these burrowing animals they carry messages across the realms, traversing in their complex burrows from realm to realm. In the Long Ago it was a bear that was the focal point of the Holiday, but as the Church moved across the land spending a millennia long crusade against its greatest competition wiping most of the bears out and spreading propaganda to paint the Forest Cousin as a fool and an oaf. By the time the Pennsylvania Dutch's Forebears arrived they and other Germans had already traded for Hedgehogs, Badgers and other burrowing animals for the Holiday that eventually became known as Groundhog Day. So the current heir to the Throne of Weather Seer and the focal point of the hope of Spring and Joys of Winter became The Groundhog. The "Bear Rodent" who was also I hear absolutely delicious. So... Happy Groundhog Day! @Hyperborean Radio (Uncensored)

For too long we have sent our elderly to prisons for the crime of being old and infirm. We tell ourselves it is for the best, they tell themselves it is for our good. The story is that it is for their health and longevity, but is it? The horrible truth, the most horrible of truths is the burden. We do not wish to take on the burden nor do they wish to be a burden real or perceived to the welfare of the young. The burden of illness, the burden of mind and temperament, the burden of time and cost. And so they go to the Nursing home or the Elderly Care facilities to be forgot. Like a dog abandoned at the pound to be cared for by those without care. It is true some employees in these places do, but let us be honest... most do not. They are in turn treated as though they are without value or as naughty children to be scolded, forgotten objects, a burden upon society. Do not forget these are our Mothers, our Fathers. Our Grand Fathers and Grand Mothers. Our Aunts and our Uncles. They are KIN! To abandon them no matter the sympathetic stories and rationalizations we tell brings nothing but shame upon ourselves and our ancestors. We teach the young that this is to be expected. We teach them that when a person begins to fail and falter, that they are to be left behind, forgotten and abandoned. Our elders raised us and taught us, they loved us and while we owe them nothing, we owe them everything. Lessons are to be taught whether they were good or bad in their own youth. Care and respect for those who were worthy of such honor, time spent in the winnowing days of dusk. Those moments during the last vestiges of their days which we can never get back. Were they cruel, they might be punished by our very kindness and joy spent with family. A joy they refused themselves and those around them as the light fades from their eyes. So care for our elders, learn and teach what you may. Our children are watching and remember one day... we too shall fade. üå≤Hyperborean Radio (Uncensored) üèî

Title: Western Landscape Date: 1871 Painter: Albert Bierstadt - German-American (1830-1902) Genre: Luminism Landscape painting. The painting is of Romantic style, albeit dark and dusky, possibly to demonstrate the effects of luminism, which is to show how light is applied in a rather dramatic effect in contrast to the grandiosity of the landscape. It's clear Bierstadt desired to show the mountain in all its glory. Although the painting is a bit faded, it appears he included a pack of coyotes at the bottom. It's more-than-likely Bierstadt exaggerated the mountain to accentuate its majesty - something he was known to do - according to a few of his critics.

Red Huckleberry The red huckleberry is one of the best-tasting wild berries that can be found in abundance in the Pacific Northwest, and can be found in shaded forests along the Pacific coasts from Central California to Southeastern Alaska west of the Cascades, and can reach a height of 3 to 12 feet - often in association with rotting wood. Tasting a little more like a cranberry than some of the other darker huckleberry varieties, the red huckleberry is sweet with a very pleasing tartness, and is a valuable food source for deer, mountain beavers, mountain goats, and elk - especially in wintertime where many of the late berries persist after the first snow. These were found growing in the Hoh Rainforest in Washington's Western Olympic Mountains. See more at: www.richleighton.com

Winner 39% Californian The most influential culture in America after three rounds of votes, was California, but that wasn't the real question was it? The real question was whether it was for the better or worse of the country and the world. Which the resounding answer was... No. With well over half the vote, only 4 people voted for it being an improvement. But why? California has or at least had a lot going for it. As a Midwesterner I'm far from the type of person to go to bat for the actions of Californians but let's take a more nuanced approach if we can. California, along with Louisiana, Texas, Florida, Alaska and Hawaii, is one of those states that is culturally distinct enough to be it's own entity, recognizably so. And unlike most states California did something that made it what it is today. It remained it's own entity not like Texas remained a Republic but in the way that Californians are for California first, something that much of the country lost after the Civil War. California built up it's own culture with imported East Coast Elites, Gold Miners, Spanish Missionaries etc, and utilized a complex economy and ecosystem. It's name, if Legend is to be believed takes its name from a Fictional Black Pagan Amazonian Queen whose people rode Griffins and fought beside Muslims... explains a lot really... But California also gave us the Beach Boys, Hollywood, Silicon Valley and to this day has some of the most iconic landmarks and species on the entire continent. California's greatest strength is also its downfall, its cultural and financial influence is such that it forced its beliefs and ideals on the rest of the country. It colonized nearby states and sold a dream which spiraled many bright eyed youngsters into crippling poverty on the streets of the Angels or Saint Francis. The issue at hand of California's influence is no more or less nefarious than that of Rome, Paris or London throughout the ages. But we can choose to say no, even if others say otherwise. Californication is not mandatory.

cleaned_message: Winner 51% Old West (Cowboys, Ranches, Etc) When it came to the most quintessentially American Culture the top 3 ranged from The Hearltland with its Prairie life, winter quilts and small towns to Dixieland itself full of its own culture distinct and iconic with Iced Tea and Cornbread to witchcraft and Confederate Ghosts, but the votes are in with an overwhelming majority the Old West, the Land of Doc Holliday, The Undertaker Emissary of Death, of Broken Men and Untamed Souls of Western Visions and Broken Dreams. A land bathed in blood, sweat, tears and liberty. In the shadows of the Mountain Men the Stetson Hat, Spurs on Boots and Cattle Drives made their own sort of Mythology the Knights Errant of the American Mythos, replete with their own legendary hero, a storm and river god of a sort in Pecos Bill. Rodeos and Work camps, Horseback riding and shootouts, Ghost Riders in the Sky and Giant Vultures whirling up storms, inspiring modern films and media made across the whole globe. While others may claim their cattle hands in lands far to the south, it is truly in the arms of the Lands of Alma Mater Columbia that the Cowboy was born, and from him the world heard from Coyotes Howl to Elks Bugle that the birth of a legend had occurred.

Ripe Saskatoons Saskatoons, or western serviceberries (or ‚Äúpomes‚Äù in botanical terms) are apple-like fruits that look very similar to salal berries and are one of my favorite foraged berries in the Pacific Northwest and Rocky Mountains. Distantly related to apples, they taste like an beautiful mix of blueberry, salal, crabapple and Oregon grape. You can eat them fresh (my favorite!), dehydrate them like raisins, make them into jelly, jam or wine, or bake them into pancakes, pies and pastries. cleaned_message: Self-Heal (Prunella vulgaris) Self-heal (also known as heal-all) is a common North American wildflower and member of the mint family that is found all over North America clear up to the Arctic Circle, as well as Europe (including Britain) from Norway south and east to North Africa and temperate Asia. It is used for a variety of uses in many countries across the globe: it can be eaten fresh as a salad or cooked in soups and stews, a refreshing tea or as a olive-green dye. Medicinally, it is used for the treatment of wounds, ulcers, sores and is known to have antibacterial properties. This one was found growing at the top of Hurricane Ridge in Washington's Olympic Mountains. See more at: www.richleighton.com

The Purpose of America, Calvin Coolidge, February 22nd 1922, Baltimore, Maryland This is a day which Destiny has dedicated to a larger freedom. It takes us back to the early eighteenth century. That period was marked as one of preparation rather than attainment. Both before it and after it the manifest course of history touched a higher crest. Marlborough, the victor of Blenheim, had just departed from the scene. George II, who with his grandson George III was destined to reign over the British Empire for almost one hundred years, had just come to the throne. Men were still living whose fathers might have known Shakespeare and Milton, might have followed Cromwell at Marston Moor and Dunbar, or might have seen the Mayflower as she carried her passengers forth upon a journey which they have not yet completed, and men were living whose sons were to stand at Concord bridge; were to write the Declaration of Independence and adopt the American Constitution; were to take part in the French Revolution and behold the triumphs of Napoleon end at Waterloo; and finally were to see that century which this day began in 1732 close in 1832 with the Parliamentary Reform Bill. It was to be a century of most remarkable achievements, and if its begin...

Alabama The Ghost of Cedarhurst "My flesh shall slumber in the ground Till the last trumpet's joyful sound Then burst the chains with sweet surprise And in my savior's image rise." These are the words inscribed on the headstone of Sally Carter. Sally died in 1837, falling ill while visiting her sister at their family mansion, known as Cedarhurst. She was buried in the family cemetery on the grounds upon which the estate stood in Huntsville. The legend of Sally's ghost began in 1919. The estate had been turned into a hotel. A young boy was lodging there with his family. One morning he revealed to his family that he Sally Carter had appeared to him in a dream. She told him that her headstone had been toppled over during the previous night's storm, and would he please go to her grave and set it upright again. The boy's family played along, believing this revelation to be merely that of childhood whimsy, but they decided it best to humor him. Sure enough, when they arrived at the grave of Sally Carter, her headstone lay flat on the ground. Ever since that day, people have claimed to see Sally's spirit wandering the grounds or even inside the mansion. Some say she watches over children as they sleep. These stores brought an overwhelming amount of attention to the estate and Sally's grave, eventually resulting in multiple vandalizations of her resting place. In 1982, the grave was exumed and she was reburied in an undisclosed location on the property.

Dear Hyperboreans With all the events happening in our lands I thought I should share a story with you from long ago. I don't know how true this is for other tribes but for the Irish it is very true indeed and I hope this helps during these most troubling times. It happened long ago and the memory is a little fuzzy so I hope you understand I have to paraphrase some of it. I was a boy, about eight year of age and a great confusion came over me, like a static overwhelming every sense I had. After several days one of my Uncles knelt beside me as I struggled with the most simple of tasks and taking me gently but firmly by the shoulders bid me look into his eyes. "Boy, I have something to tell you. Something one so young as yourself should not be burdened to know, but it seems you must. What you are experiencing is normal. It is due to an ancient pact that was made between our family and an ancient one. We pledged ourselves to Eire, her, her land, this is our home. To defend her, love her, her inhabitants, her men who also made this pledge, her animals and her soil, her shores and her waters, the birds and the insects. To every creature that runs or swims or flies within her home, our home. There is a call, it is strong and ancient this bond forever calling. The drive to stand, to bury our naked feet in her soil. To laugh and love and die in her embrace. We fight because we are warriors who pledged to defend her for all time because we were the mightiest of those who came. Eirin Go Brahg, it is more than a silly saying or some phrase to sling out without meaning. There are others who have always hated us, many who claim to be her children, but they work only to cut her, to remove her blessings and her bond from the true people of Eire. Those who were gifted and bonded body and soul to the land... You need to know this too. But there is a call, a pull and with that comes a longing, a sorrow, a great beating of the heart and a rage so deep it burns the very bones. A longing for a home you may never know. And for that I apologize. We were driven from our land long ago by these very usurpers. We fought, we killed our own kin to defend her. We killed to defend those who did not betray ambushed in the night, slaughtered in their sleep until a scream went up alerting the rest of us so that we might fight, and live. These were troubling times then and may you never know such times yourself but I fear you may and so you must know. The call is strong and will drive you mad should you let it. It will drive you mad with longing you cannot sooth, a sorrow you cannot know and a fury you cannot avenge. This is just beginning for you and will become more insistent in a few years when you begin into manhood. Eire is with you no matter the soil you stand on because will remain hers as she will remain yours for the rest of time. Perhaps one day we might be able to heed her call, because she is still under threat and always will be, but you must know that we to are under threat here. From here we will raise a great army and free her from her bonds! Blood will flow from friend and enemy alike! She will be free! All of our lands from here to there and back again! Be strong, be brave, and be wise. Take your time and remember. Do you hear me?! Never forget." Sincerely J.A.Coburn, Clann √ì Coill

The Gods Embodied Do You Remember being excited for Santa Claus? Hoping to meet him? Or perhaps catch a peek when he came down the chimney? Do you remember that innocent glee that filled you when you by chance saw someone who looked like him around Yuletide? Maybe even running up to them saying "I've been REALLY good this year Santa!"? You may not have known it but this is one of the oldest of our traditions among The Hyperborean Peoples. The Gods look like us and thus those of us that bear a striking resemblance to the Gods BEAR A DUTY upon our shoulders. To embody them in everyday life and to do right by the sparkling eyed children who look at us with wonder. Others do so as their career or like the most devoted of Santa's in the USA they do both! Both embodying the God in looks and in personality. From the Red Bearded Chieftains -Thor- of Scandinavian Witch Cults, to the Fur bearing Matron God Richella of Italy, through the Alps with Perchten and Krampus to Alibon with Father Christmas amongst the Mummers, we have long embodied the God(s) in both appearance and in deed. Even taking our children to meet them as a rite of passage; as we do to this day, albeit with a more mercantile Santa Claus. Which is why many kids will avoid those but jump up and down in wonder and joy for Old Karl with the belly and big white beard who they meet at the grocer. Santa Claus in that moment is the most real thing in the world! More real than you or me, more important than the presents stuffed under the tree. Magic... The magic of belief. The child might even know it is Karl from the grocer but it doesn't matter as in that moment Karl IS Santa Claus. Every child knows Santa is wherever Santa is needed, appearing wherever that may be, looking through the eyes of others, but once in awhile... well maybe... just maybe, he comes in person. The Wonder of Our Children Must be Protected. @Hyperborean Radio (Uncensored)

Pyrrhuloxia The pyrrhuloxia is a member of the cardinal family that has a range that just reaches into the United States in the states of Arizona, New Mexico and Texas. It is very similar in appearance to the more common red (or Northern) cardinal, but has an overall gray coloration with a red face (males) and red crest. This beautiful male was found and followed through the Sonoran Desert in Tucson, Arizona on a hot spring morning. See more at: www.richleighton.com

Happy Ullr Fest! Every Year in Breckenridge, Colorado a Celebration of Ullr, The Scandinavian God of Snow and Games is held known as Ullr Fest. The tradition stems from Norwegian Ski instructors at Breckenridge Ski Resort holding Ullr Dag Celebrations to honor their God Ullr and thank him for his gift of snow and teaching people to Ski. The celebration grew and Ullr Fest was created, involving Costumes, Winter Games, Snow Sculptures, Lots of Booze, A parade the Crowning of Ullr King and Queen and even a bonfire where old Ski's are burned. One could say that the Heart of the Cult of Ullr in North America is in this Colorado Town. They even put a large sculpture of Ullr up shooting his trademark Yew Bow to honor him and welcome him for the prosperity he has given them.
