Heikki Lunta, Yooper-Finnish Snow God You may have heard of Jack Frost and Old Man Winter but what about Hank Snow? Or as his original name reads Heikki Lunta? Old Hank has many titles and names in local Yooper lore such as Snow, Mr. Snow, King Snow, etc. He may have even descended from a Finnish Snow God from the Old Country, though which has long been lost to time. However Hank Snow has become one of the most well known figures of Yooper Myth and Legend even having the largest Yooper Winter Festival Heikinp√§iv√§ in Hancock, Michigan. Where you can find him blending in with the crowd looking as normal as any other Yooper Man with his bushy beard and snow goggles, wearing a warm thick flannel and a winter cap atop his head, though he may also appear as a pile of living fur coats. The Heikki festival involves the Three Heikki's: The Snow God Heikki himself, A Finnish "Saint" known as St. Henrik and a local Grand Marshall of the festival known as Hankookin Heikki. Those who don't believe say the Legend of Heikki Lunta grew after a supposed origin in 1970 when David Riutta a local DJ wrote the song "Heikki Lunta‚Äôs Snow Dance", this little song caused snow to fall across the land. The song proved too effective and necessitated another song created by Riutta to be written and played, the far less welcoming "Heikki Lunta Go Away". Riutta's first song gained fame for it's snow summoning properties even delivering snow to the Range Snowmobile Club's Snowmobile Race when snow had failed to fall in time for the big event. Like many Gods, Spirits and Legends of American Myth Heikki Lunta is no loner, he may be a God of Snow but he can be as snug around others as a warm fur coat, Old Hank is married to his childhood sweetheart Aino M√§kinen and their marriage has created a large extended family including his less than enthusiastic son Heikki Jr. @Hyperborean Radio (Uncensored)

Common Snowberry The common snowberry is a found throughout most of central and northern North America and is most commonly seen in lower-elevations mountainous forests where it can form immense thickets. Although it is a staple food source for many birds and mammals such as deer, bears, and bighorn sheep, all parts of the plant and fruit are somewhat toxic to humans if eaten in quantity, although many native tribes used them medicinally. Only the Sqauxin Indians of the Olympia, Washington area are reported to have eaten them regularly. These were found and photographed in the Mercer Sough of Bellevue, Washington. Along the banks of the Susquehanna River there are tales told of a 3 to 5 foot tall, ape-like creature. The "Albatwitch," a name thought to be a variation of apple-snitch, are believed to have an insatiable love for apples. Since the early 1800's, people have told stories of these beings stealing apples from picnickers along the river, near Chickies Rock, where the Albatwitch are said to live. The creatures would carry their favorite fruit up into the trees, and when they were finished, the cores were thrown back at the people below.

Little Daily Heresies There has been talk of the endless conflict between Pagans and Christians. However I don't see that, I see a political institution desperately trying to beat back the natural inclination, culture and beliefs of our people. While the "Pagans", blissfully unaware carry on doing what they've always done. Most are Christian One Hour a Week and Pagan the rest. That doesn't seem poised to change. I don't speak of New Age Religions (Asatru, Druidry, Wicca) who masquerade as tradition. No, I speak of the beauty of the everyday little heresies performed innumerably by the supposedly Good Christian. The unintentional, the enjoyable and beloved. When they place the ancient symbol of abundance on the table at Thanksgiving, the Horn of Plenty. When they place idols to Harvest Gods known as Scarecrows in their yards. When they say the days of the week or months of the year in song or poem calling on Woden, Thor and Saturn; Janus, Mars and Juno. When the ancient Yule Tree is brought inside instead of being left out to light the night as it once was. When the ancient egg hunt for Easter of the Dawn is performed. When we place the symbol of Asclepius on our medical texts and take his dogs to see the sick and ailing. When we tell stories of Robin Hood (The Mad God), King Arthur (The Bear King), of Puck and the Fae. When we take children introducing them to one of our Gods, the King of Ghosts and Christmas Cheer himself, like the Witch Cults of Old and Kris Kringle asks the immortal question "And Just who are you my dear child?" Or when we tend to the graves of our beloved dead, or pray to statues we call Angels but know in truth are Genii or Fae. The list goes on and on, performed without thinking listening to instinct and the joy and sense of belonging within their heart. I need not worry or fret over the future of Paganism or the traditional beliefs of our people. We've already won. I merely sit back and smile at the soft beauty of Their Daily Little Heresies. Joseph Palmer, Bearded Heretic It may seem odd to think of today but once having a beard was so culturally unacceptable that people were berated, ostracized and insulted for "wearing a beard". Such was the story of Joseph Palmer, an American farmer who grew a beard and was not only accused of being a heretic who emulated Satan with his mane, but was attacked with scissors in an attempt to remove his beard and then thrown in prison when the burly American proceeded to defend himself with a knife and stab some Christian Zealots in the leg. Serving a 15 month prison term for "assault" Palmer would eventually leave after his mother pleaded him to pay the fine, which he had refused as it would be akin to admitting he was at fault. He then joined the ill fated Utopian group the Fruitlands and after it fell apart bought the land and farmed it. By the time of his death beards had gone from hirsute heresy to the norm once more. His grave contains the Quote: "Persecuted for Wearing the Beard"

Northwestern Garter Snake Unusual but not unheard of, this northwestern garter snake (Thamnphis ordinoides) was unexpectedly found actively hunting in the grass near the beach on a rare February sunny day on the Oregon Coast in Oswald West State Park. One of the smallest of garter snakes in the region, it is also one of the hardest to identify because of the extreme variability in color and pattern. One of the best clues without counting scale numbers and patterns is the head, which tends to be quite small for a garter snake. This one was quite large for this smaller species - it was over 30 inches when the typical northwestern garter is usually around 24 inches. See more at: www.richleighton.com

Cerro Castellan Cerro Castellan - also known as Castolon Peak or Castellan Peak, is a conical volcanic mountain in West Texas that rises 1000 feet above the desert floor (3,293 feet above sea level) in Big Bend National Park. Cerro Castellan itself is part of an ancient series of summits once known as the Corazones Peaks that has since succumbed to millennia of erosion by wind, precipitation, searing heat and bitterly cold winters. Geologically, this ancient mountain range remnant is a high stack of volcanic rocks, including ash, lava, and tuffaceous rocks. It is capped by a dense lava flow underlain by various tuffs and basalts. A somewhat northwest fault cuts the eastern face of Cerro Castellan. Although little vegetation grows on the sheer cliffs and steep, pointed profile of its peak, the lower slopes of Cerro Castellan support a sparse growth of Chihuahuan Desert scrub, including most prominently such characteristic species as creosote bush and ocotillo. Do You Believe in Ghosts? Have you ever felt that spine tingling sensation of what is there... yet not there. Out of the corner of your eye, in the chill of your blood or the thickness of the air. Perhaps you heard a door creak, a window shake, a voice from nowhere as the chair rocked ever so slightly. Have you ever been haunted by the souls of the dead... or the living? You see; Ghosts while ubiquitous and commonly known are oft limited to only a fraction of their true depth and power. A ghost not only a soul of our dead both beloved and reviled, but the spirits of the land and of the home, even The Gods themselves are Among the Greatest of Our Ghosts! But it is not only apparitions and Phantoms, deities and the Dead but also the living, the memory and afterimage, the impact of a spirit or idea that infects and lives its own kind of life, devoid of flesh and sinew but not fervor and spirit. As there are the little deaths to go beside the big one, the death of innocence, of love, of the life that could be. Haunted by what-ifs and maybes, of heartbreaks and summer fun. The most terrifying ghosts are perhaps those of our own making of both the greatest of losses and the grandest of joys! For who can truly say they have never been haunted by the path not taken, or the life lost to misdeed or mistake. Yet along with souls, Gods and memories lay the ghosts of ideas. Among the most powerful and sweeping, the ghost of philosophy, or fiction. The Ghost of Conan the Barbarian or Batman, Lilliputians or Huck Finn, of Religion and Politics. We are to a one haunted by ghosts of all kinds, for just as a rose is a flower, but a daisy is not a rose so too does the title of Ghost befit an endless procession of spirits and beliefs. Whether real or imagined it makes no difference, we are possessed and haunted by these phantom hosts for better or for worse. So... Do You Believe in Ghosts? -I.M.Knosp @Hyperborean Radio (Uncensored)

Remember Who Came Before and What They Went Through Those of us in America are not here because our ancestors had it easy, often when they came to America they were trading one harshness for another. Many died on the frontier, in the pestilent and polluted cities. Others were brought over as indentured servants and many died in the harsh labor jobs of mining, manufacturing, fishing among other jobs where the health of man was outweighed by the health of the dollar. Those that survived these trials and ordeals of course wanted the best for their children, their heirs to their sweat and blood. What they conquered and built shedding the blood of the fallen across every inch of this land. They did not do all this so we could hand it over and paint them as villains because someone who doesn't give a shit about us said we were being mean. Winner 77% Yes, The Hours Make No Sense While not every business in the USA runs on a 9-5 schedule, most do Especially Banks. The hours are in general a left over from the time period when only one spouse would work in the marriage (at least full time not counting small things like selling baked goods, lace or extra eggs, etc.) allowing the one who stayed at home to go out and do the chores. But with both working many business have hours that have only an hour or two on both ends that many can even go to. I myself don't even work 9-5 but the hours still don't make sense. What's more is that many places are still closed Sunday, one of the few days people actually are able to go out and do things when they aren't working because of Church. So we have a schedule for work and businesses that are built around two things we no longer have in abundance, Zealous Christian Populations and Families where only one parent works. Though it seems if everything keeps on standing that we may change course one way even if the hours don't change.

Ancestor Veneration Begins with The Living Recently someone close to us weathered the death of a treasured family member, in the aftermath he discovered something his treasured Mother wrote of her Father -His Grandfather- a short recollection of a man who was her "Freckled Atlas" who raised her well with warmth and a firm hand when needed. This heartfelt description of her father begins as such: "Although he is a big man with a gruff voice which spouts curse words at regular intervals, he has a heart that envelopes everyone around him. I have seen him quiet a whimpering small child and save a grown man's life." and by the end of this short loving bit of prose: "Of all the persons I've known, this man has influenced me the most, not only because he is my daddy but because he is also my friend, who laughs and jokes with me, and my guide, who gives me advice and warns me about the world. Daddy may be a stern and severe father at times, but most of the time he is my "Freckled Atlas" who looks after me and loves me." Reading this while I bear no ties to the family of my friend the love and adoration our friends mother held for his grandfather brought a tear to my eye and reminded me of something incredibly important. Ancestor Veneration Begins with the Living. Remind your parents, your grandparents and all of your family how much they mean to you. They may not be here tomorrow, you may not be here tomorrow, but that love between each other will. @Hyperborean Radio (Uncensored)

Winner 15% Cthulhu, The Great Dreamer I was pretty sure Cthulhu was going to win (though technically "Just Want To See Results Won with Nearly half of the vote, but who wants that to be the winner, very anticlimactic.) but Cthulhu is by far the most well known and popular of Lovecraft's Creations. Cthulhu, The Great Dreamer, The Sleeper of R'lyeh, High Priest of the Great Old Ones, The Star Spwan, Lord of the Watery Abyss, The Sleeping God. He who fought a war in the ancient days with ancient beings that make man quiver and quake, who is tended to by Deep Ones and Shape Shifting Starspawn Eldritch Beings, sleeping in the great sunken city of R'lyeh. With cultists across the world and beyond. But while often treated as evil it is more accurate to define Cthulhu as indifferent, an indifferent god at best mildly amused by the tiny mice upon the planet he conquered so long ago. Cthulhu can also be seen in many Lovecraftian games and stories influencing Pirates of the Caribbean, Bloodborne and Other Souls Games, Hellboy, D&D and an endless series of Lovecraftian and cosmic horror. Shub-Niggurath, Hastur and Nyarlathotep all tied for second with 9% unsurprisingly, though I will admit I expected Azathoth to do better.

The Saga of Johnny Appleseed Johnny weren't this scrawny pencil necked little twerp you see in the movies. He were a beast of a man, strong as an ox, a bronzed hide, his beard and hair grew long and wild and neath his hat were piercing eyes. He carried a tome of sacred knowledge, his sack was full of forest medicine. He ran with wolves, fought serpents and Indians. He was even betrothed to Forest Maidens, old spirits of the wood. Though perhaps I'm getting ahead of myself, let's start at the beginning shall we. Born at the birth of our Nation he was, grew up crowded on all sides. He'd move this way or that and run into his brother or sister. So when the Pioneers flowed west he naturally followed suit quickly getting ahead of them into a land of Mountain Men, River Rats and Forest Warfare. Travelin' barefoot his feet quickly cobbled his own boots of flesh, he could walk through both fire and ice on those feet of his. Even red hot pokers could not pierce them. He had nothing but the clothes nature grew for him or the tattered remains of Christian Charity while in the wilderness. He'd meet and make friends with many Varmints, took a wolf as traveling companion, some even say he crossed paths with Paul and Babe planting his Orchards all across the frontier and doing battle with Indians, Snakes and British Soldiers. The Forest was wilder then, full to the brim with spirits and wonders. The Indians came to view him as a Holy Man a Heathen Hermit or Forest God. At some point the spirits of the Forest came to him and he became betrothed to some of their maidens, though he refused them in life they could have him in death. Yes there is much much more to Johnny than just his apples. I spect he forgot more than most than us'll ever know. In his death he knew his work weren't over and he bent a tree to plant itself and then all the apples across America. In death he dint cease, when he went on ta' the realms beyond he planted a heavenly orchard that you see in the clouds to this day. @Hyperborean Radio (Uncensored)

The Humble Knife "This is my knife. There are many others like it, but this one is mine. My knife is my best friend. It is my life." Since the time of antiquity the right to be armed with a blade has been a symbol of the Free Man. A reflection of the man who possesses it worn proudly for all to see, proving not only his ability and willingness to defend himself and kin but more importantly proof that he is responsible enough to develop a trade. Whether his trade be butchery, rope making, fishing or killing, knives are first and foremost a tool. A hunting knife is not the same as a chef's knife or a fishing knife, nor should they be. Each knife serves a distinct purpose, the purpose of the one who possesses it. The supposed soul of the knife is in reality a reflection of the man holding it. The one who maintains it well, cherishing it for the purpose it serves as well as for what it means, it's history. If the blade is well crafted and cared for it very well may pass on to our grandchildren and our grandchildren's grandchildren. The humble knife passing from father to son, woodworker to woodworker, hunter to hunter. A symbol of Trade. A symbol of Purpose. A symbol of Kin. @Hyperborean Radio (Uncensored)

I've seen things you people wouldn't believe... Attack ships on fire off the shoulder of Orion... I watched C-beams glitter in the dark near the Tannh√§user Gate. All those moments will be lost in time, like tears in rain... Time to die. ‚Äî Roy Batty, Blade Runner Most people miss the point of this short yet poignant dialogue. They think it is JUST an exploration of 'What it means to be human' or 'What it means to be alive'. Others think it is a question of conscience concerning artificial intelligence and what that means. Can AI become conscious? Can AI become sentient? And what does that mean? I would argue that Roy Batty is a stand in for the path that humanity is on. While Rick Deckard is the stand in for those herding the sheep; whether or not they are aware of their role matters not. It is inconsequential to the the real question raised by these most eloquent 42 words in cinema in the most enigmatic way. No, I would argue that it is 'WE' the regular people, the regular people whose lives are so very, very short. Those who are expected to do no more than labor and toil, to suffer for our 'betters', to live and to die for them at their whim and will. It is 'We' who are represented in a dying machine... just an outdated cog, used, chewed up, spat out with distaste and disgust... Yet it is WE who are truly alive. Those of us who have suffered, who have toiled, who have put others before ourselves who have TRULY lived. It is WE who have seen the 'Attack ships on fire off the shoulder of Orion... I watched C-beams glitter in the dark near the Tannh√§user Gate.'! WE who can see the wonders in the world for those with eyes to see them. It is WE who gaze in mysterious wonder and awe at the simple elegance of life. But should we not have family. Should we not have friends. Should there be no one to remember us and all of our glories and wonders! ...'All those moments will be lost in time, like tears in rain...', they shall amount to nothing and soon be forgot. This is why we must live to inspire! To invite people into our lives! To be that which most have been taught is impossible to be! We the Noble and the Brave, the Kind and the Brutal. We can also be the most loving. If it is not we who can understand their heartbreak... their sorrow... then who can? Do not fear, set forth, reach out, do not hold your tongue for fear of offending. But do so with care, care for those who are lost. Love them. Some will run, some will wander away. And that is ok, but try. Say hello, smile in greeting to those of our tribes, become the Man or Woman that others swear in their weakness cannot exist. Do not fear to ask others into your life. Create families and clans. Remember the rules of hospitality so that we might not complete our journey alone as Roy Batty did and so many others of our kind. Text by J.A. Coburn @Hyperborean Radio (Uncensored)

cleaned_message: Barbegazi The Frozen Beards or "Barbegazi" are woolly Wildmen who hibernate cozy and cool, deep in their mountain caverns through the sweltering summer months but at the first hint of winters chill they rise to the surface and their beloved snowy peaks to frolic and make merry! Their short stout stature and thick pelt of snow white hair from the neck down replete with an incredibly thick beard that falls to their waist is well suited to their preferred habitat. Their crowing feature however is ironically at the bottom of their build, that being their hirsute hobbitish feet large enough to act as snowshoes atop the packed snow and long enough to act as skis for fast travel through the mountains. These playful winter spirits have lived atop the French Alps for ages where they tunnel through the snow and "allegedly" cause avalanches. They will also whistle to warn shepherds when storms or aforementioned avalanches are occurring, as well as use their exceptional burrowing abilities to help rescue unfortunate souls buried in the oncoming snow. The Barbegazi are at least somewhat fond of Mankind as they bothered to follow their unfortunately bald and lanky neighbors to the New World settling alongside them in Midwestern Mountain Ranges from the Sawtooth Mountains of Minnesota east to the Mountains of Michigan's Upper Peninsula. Here they are known colloquially as Snow Goblins or Snow Dwarfs, though they possess many other names as well. Small statues of them dot the land and their playful demeanors are on full display in local myth and legend. Often throwing snow from trees at passersby, the harmless fun typical of such spirits complete with a more extreme deadly version of snowfall should the person have earned the ire of these winter Gods. But regardless they contently traverse their mountains those of the Old World and of the New, their wintery mountain homes fitting them as snuggly as their nonexistent snowshoes. @Hyperborean Radio (Uncensored)

On Politics and Universalism If you were to contrast the systems of what we may call Paganism or "Ethnic Way" against what we may call Oneness or "Universalistic Systems of Belief" you would find more differences than similarities, though this is in their undiluted state and not the endless amalgam of folk belief and academic conjecture that so permeates both. To start, Paganism actually embraces and in many ways IS FOLK BELIEF. With literary and theological works only appearing as dogmatic texts long after the actual beliefs, concepts and ideas have already been developed and pressure tested. While on the other hand Oneness is the exact opposite, it starts with what is intended to be a constant system of belief. But in reality is often shifted depending on the political climate of the time and merely tolerates folk belief and different schools of thought in so far as it allows it to grow in power and influence. Regardless of the corruption or synthesis with other conflicting ideals. The second is while Oneness often states itself as the one universalistic truth. Paganism does not. Rather Pagan beliefs are often specific to a people and contain among other things their history, culture and divine beings that populate both. In its undiluted state Paganism is unique to a tribe and is expressed on an individual level. The all-powerful, all-pervading and one true God or Gods that are present in later stages to some degree are typically a central tenant of Oneness. The reason for them and their often moralizing lessons is simple, they arise when enough tribes get together and are often a corruption of a deity or deities from the tribes that make them up. Mankind is inherently incredibly tribal so conflict is inevitable especially when forced to work together with disparate groups who most likely have considerable animosity over everything from wars to broken hearts. Thus this deity or set of deities serves as the watcher and controller, not because this deity ever was or even is such a thing, but because the political powers decreed it as useful. Because once any level of ones Ethnic Way is handed away from the people and instead given to an outside authority. The Gods once a treasured member of the culture and people, instead become a cudgel with which to force the people to submit. Thus the all powerful god that ages of people have died for is little more than the political tool of an overclass. Oneness is politics, nothing more. From this spawns political ideologies where eventually as technology and empires grow the powers that may be find other means of keeping the people in line. Religious Dogma is replaced with political dogma, the all seeing deity is replaced with cameras and informants. The Government is the All Seeing God whether he calls himself the Pope or President. However Paganism should not be confused with the idea of lack of innovation, or a sort of backwards state of living. But rather a rejection of control, confederations of hundreds if not thousands of tribes have banded together before without having to conflate their Gods or make any of them the all powerful, "ONE TRUE GOD". In fact these confederations existed for millennia and even conquered Rome on several occasions. Though it is now known as an empire it was nothing like what one would think. It is called the Celtic Empire. The choice is not the stone age or totalitarianism, nor is it the eternal inquisition of whose brand of Oneness is the correct choice. The choice is as it always has been. Are we true to ourselves or do we join the herd? The One True is merely the oldest of control options. Each and every one of our tribes have our own Gods, traditions and ways of being. An inheritance of mythic proportions. Or we can follow the shepherd to safety and slavery whether he wears a Crucifix, a Mjolnir or a Party Membership Badge. But know we don't have to play their game anymore. We never really did. @Hyperborean Radio (Uncensored)

Why The Radio? In the age of cellphones and computers why did we choose a radio as our symbol? Because the Radio is mundane, an everyday object often overlooked, yet it represents much more. The Radio does not eradicate that which surrounds it, your time is not robbed of you, your attention is not stripped from kin or purpose. The Radio gifts information, it delivers music and discussion, it has been used to broadcast light in darkness, stories of great and daring deeds, war correspondence and conversations between those who may never have met otherwise. Unlike the Neon Lights of the Urban Wastelands and Monitors that dominate the home the Radio never displaced the Hearth from its flaming abode instead it was its amiable neighbor. One could dance with the one they love, knit, whittle or play cowboys with the nearby Radio as congenial companion. As tech expanded from portable radios, to Walkman's, to MP3 Players, to the tiny magic mirrors we carry in our pockets everyday this function remained, at least in its function as a Radio. A walk in the woods, a fishing trip in the family boat, a game of Monopoly that never completes all of these and more can be done "BESIDE" The Radio, not in-spite of or in resistance to. The Radio is freedom it is connection by choice, addition without bindings, it is the open road and Sunday nights with Family. This is what Hyperborean Radio aspires to be, an addition in your lives. Without stripping any of the meaning and joys that we have in life. Broadcast for all to hear. The Normalcy of Paganism Paganism or "The Ethnic Way" is Normal, in fact it is Normalcy itself. The traditional Spiritual Memory and Outgrowth of a people, their mytho-history, divine family, ancestors, ghosts and customs. When Grandparents tell stories, when holiday customs are passed on to the next generation, a father teaching his son to hunt, a mother teaching her daughter to cook, the legends of their land and clan and any that may have been picked up of use over the years. A Hunt may be a hunt and even end with the age old custom of blowing the hunting horn. It may even involve stories of The Wild Huntsman, The Eternal Hunter, Ullr, Artemis or any number of hunting or woodland deities. But it doesn't have to. People may embody their gods in spirit or simply as role models much as one does with pop culture figures, the surrogate gods and heroes of the modern age. It is in everything we do, while some may have more blatantly pagan customs involving carved masks, Treats left for ancestral spirits or forest gifts. The Odd American Alphabets The United States has its share of odd and obscure history including the invention of new alphabets. Here are three of the more notable examples. Franklin Alphabet: Developed by Benjamin Franklin in 1768 an original American Phonetic Alphabet for a "More Natural Order" to writing language. Franklin sought to not only aid in building a national identity but also "remove bad spelling" he removed letters he considered redundant like C,J,Q, W, X and Y and also added 6 others of his own design, he gave preference to sounds formed by the Breath as opposed others. While he was able to convert Noah Webster of all people, most others were not so supportive and even ridiculed his alphabet as a corruption of Language and a nightmare for future etymology. Cherokee Syllabary: Invented by the Cherokee Man Sequoyah over 12 years to help his people maintain their language and provide a more fitting alphabet, this Syllabary differed from Latin Alphabets in that it represented the Syllables in the Cherokee Language rather than consonants and vowels. This Syllabary is still in use today in increasingly diverse ways among the Cherokee Tribal areas. Deseret Alphabet: Invented by George D. Watt and born from the Utopian and idealist views of Brigham Young and the Mormon Church the Deseret Alphabet was intended as one of many reforms for the "Latter Days" before the second coming of Christ and was intended, much as Franklin's above, to make reading, writing and spelling easier. It never fully took off despite being encouraged to be taught to the young. Some detractors even claim it was meant more to keep Mormon's from reading outside literature than anything else. In recent years it has seen a revival as a Cultural heirloom for Members of the Latter Day Saints Church. How about You? Know Any Weird or Obscure Alphabets from your neck of the woods?

cleaned_message: Anyone Else? Lately I don't quite know how to describe it but I haven't been feeling quite as interested in things as usual. I'm not talking depression or anything of the sort, but rather I was watching Television and the thought struck me "I am watching a bunch of adults get paid absurd amounts of money to play dress up and run around playing pretend" It became hard to see characters and all I could see were the actors who played them. The immersion, that ability to melt into a film or TV show was gone. It's not much better for Youtube; not that like most people, there are individuals whose content I still enjoy here or there, but I find myself increasingly uninterested in video format and media of any kind. It's like I can feel the time being etched away as I sit in front of the screen. I find myself increasingly more drawn to older things vinyl, radio and books. It's not that I'm against movies, Social Media or Video Games. I just view them as less and less important or prominent in my life, but its more than just not wanting to, its a complete lack of desire. Movies have lost their luster, Social Media the likes of Youtube, Instagram etc seem like a mixture of useful tool and complete time suck where I wake from a daze not knowing what I'd been doing for the last hour. I still; like most people, enjoy music, a good book, time with friends, the outdoors, Radio both classic and the more modern "podcasts". In a way its freeing, but the way it happened was odd. It was as if a spell that I'd been under since I was young, enamored and enthralled by screens and fast paced media had completely collapsed and I could walk away whenever I wanted, or use it when I felt like it. I want to post less to Social Media, not just for myself to have more free time, I don't want to take up too much of yours either, time, attention is the most valuable resource we have. Thank you for spending it reading this. I don't know I often overthink things... does anyone else feel this way?

Results Conclusion: Around 30% of Americans Seem to consider around 75% or less of their diet originates in their State, 50% or More are unaware or consume even more. Interesting... so on my end I'm unaware of how much of my food comes from my state of residence. (nothing unique there) However while I can find Gummy Candy in my state, explicitly made in my state, its hard to find other more obvious things. I live in the Great Lake Region yet Freshwater Fish is hard to find for sale, much of what is fished out of the Great Lakes is sent abroad while this allows for an income it also strips one of the most valued resources, on the same token I use to live in Iowa which despite having the most farmer's markets per capita in the USA is also the epicenter of Big Agriculture, to the point that some have tried to start making Iowan Tofu to utilize the immense amount of Soy grown in Iowa. This doesn't change the fact modern farming in Iowa is stripping the soil in favor of cash crops, mostly due to Federal Policy. I may be overthinking it, seeing shared brands in different states but little to no local food available aside from specialty stores or Farmers Markets is surreal. The world doesn't work like this... yet it does. You can eat Steak from Texas, African Chocolate, Wisconsin Cheese, Maple Syrup from Canada all in the same dish in Indiana (What the ever loving Fuck are you eating? ahem...) While this is a marvel of the modern world it is also horrifying, the amount of biomass lost or moved, culture loss, and just genuine loss of resources is insane. Which is why I was curious as to how much the average American got from the local state. All 50 States are in theory meant to be individual countries and they seem to be set up more akin to counties. While many States are larger than all of the UK! Maybe I'm just overthinking it but I wonder how stable this is and who will bare the costs when a worldwide food system faces its inevitable collapse. Which states, Which individuals, will thrive and which will starve?

Winner 45% The American Bison or "Buffalo" While it was a close race between our National Bird and our National Mammal, The Bison won by 5%! -I was surprised by how many people saw sense in Franklins Suggestion of The Turkey, Very Interesting- While the Bald Eagle is a Majestic Looking Animal and a Quintessentially American Symbol, I don't think there is a more quintessentially American animal than the Bison. It's strong herds that once stretched as far as the eye could see, its delicious meat, powerful gait and wild beard and horns, but quite possibly while the Bald Eagle may be iconic, the Bison is important. It had immense impact on our history, our culture, we even call it "Gods Cattle" While the East Coast doesn't tend to have Bison, for most US States from Appalachia to the Western Edge of the Rockies this wondrous Beast, this manifested God of Storms in its booming rumble has made a mark on all who've seen it. We did not nearly drive these to extinction, they were nearly wiped out when Amerindians drove whole herds over canyons in their "Bison Runs" No... We were the ones who SAVED THEM! Much as beautiful Columbia was replaced with Uncle Sam -Though this was a mistake imo- Perhaps its time for the US to shift its focus to a Beast that embodies our dreams, our hopes and in some ways our history. Rather than a hold over of Rome, an Empire most of our populations ancestors didn't exactly have a great experience with.

Gringo For Americans that are unaware of the use of Gringo, it is not a term of endearment it is an insult. There are several possible origin stories for the word from it descending from Greek, being related to a misconstrued lyric from the song "Green Grow the Rushes", to the most likely origin of it being derived from a Kentucky Regiment Stationed in Mexico's Green Coats. The simple fact is this word is a slur. My own personal opinion is I don't really care, as just like anyone else who isn't told to get all fired up when a word is used it doesn't tend to bother me. What does bother me is that people are unware of the words use as such and will stand idly by and even use the word playfully letting certain groups constantly insult us because we think its a playful nickname. It's not. They know it's not. That is all.

Did They? It is often thought that the Church "won"; that it replaced the Heathen Gods and Ancestral Customs with a new religion complete with doctrine, dogma and a crushing political structure. While I do not dispute this importation of Doctrine, this enforcement of Dogma, nor the Political Empire stemming from the Church halfway across the world... I have to wonder "Did they?" Did they erase the veneration of Heathen Gods? Did they erase the folk culture and beliefs of the people involved? I mean they definitely tried, but look around, how well did they do? Just from the obvious bits they missed from the ancestor veneration of Halloween and the Yuletide, to the fertility customs of Easter and May Day; it's not any secret that they did a rather poor job of eradicating these heretical acts. And I'm just getting started! That's merely in America and I haven't even gotten to our Lumberjack Forest Gods or Ghost Riders in the Sky. Across the Pond back to the Old Country it's no secret that many areas even to this day have a local wise elder, or to dispense with pleasantries a "Local Witch" whether male or female is rather superfluous. Their own holy buildings which are blasphemous in and of themselves, are useful only as a political seat, even if such a use is now merely a dwindled formality rather than the real power it once exercised. The Green Man, Protective Spirits known now as Gargoyles and the Masturbating Fertility Gnomes known as Sheela and Sean na Gig stare unabashed from chapel rafters. We still have more tales than we can count of Puck, Holda, Thor, Basa Jaun, The Leshy among many many other Gods. Though occasionally they are in fancy dress and misnamed Mary, Michael or some such surrogate name of blasphemous belief. All they managed was to twist these beliefs, adding biblical gunk to the gears. So I ask again... Did they? Or did they only convince us they won, so we would stop fighting for what they could never destroy?-HR @Hyperborean Radio (Uncensored)

The Old Round Church Richmond, Vermont Designed in 1812-13 by New Hampshire native William Rhodes, to be the Town Meeting Hall and place of worship for members of five Protestant denominations. Notable for its rare design and well-preserved detail, it is possibly the sole surviving example of an early 19th-century 16-sided wooden meetinghouse. One of the theories as to the building's shape is to make certain that the devil had nowhere to hide within.

Nine More English Words With Pagan Meanings Automaton: An Automaton is a living object in Greek Myth, the most famous is Talos a bronze man filled with Ichor who guarded Crete. While Automaton is oft used as a steampunk equivalent to Robot this is a falsehood as the two words are diametrically opposed. Robot means "Slave" while Automaton means to "Imbue with Free Will" or a sense of self. A stark contrast between our current age and the mindset of the Ancients. Example: Talos, Gullinbursti, Pinocchio, Manann√°n's Horse/Boat Eldritch: While Eldritch is often synonymous with Lovecraftian Cosmic Horror or the Abyss the words origin is actually "Elf Kingdom" or "Fairyland" Thus the word Eldritch implies it finds its origins in the strange ways of the Otherworlds and realms, specifically the Wyrd ways of the lands of Fae and Elphame. Example: "This Elf Stone radiates Eldritch Qualities". Oneironaut: Oneironauts are travelers within dreams, both in a visionary sense or in an innate ability to project ones consciousness or spirit out of their body during dreaming. Whether between realms or dreams. Example: Inception or A Christmas Carol, "The Oneironaut traveled through the Dreamlands and came to the Realm of the Dead" Kind: Kind is a wonderful word still used today. To be Kind, or of a Kind is to be of the same race, nation, character or nature. Kindness or the act of being Kind is to exemplify the most noble natures of your Kind. A wonderful multifaceted word with many implications. Example: Mankind (The Species of Man/Hyperboreans), Goblinkind, "Your Kind Deeds shall not soon be forgot" Craft: One's Craft is ones skill or strength, it is also sometimes used as short hand for the ability to perform miracles or work the Wyrd, among other things. Example: Woodcraft (the Skill or Strength in regards to woodworking), Witchcraft (Craft of Wise Ones), Starcraft (Astrology in its practical use for weather and calendar purposes) Man: Man is us, while A Race of Man currently refers to any Human shaped entity of Middle Earth, the specific word "Man" is originally a description of the species indigenous to Northwest Eurasia and related groups. While many epitaphs exist, at our core we are still Man. Note: The sexes were previously demarcated as Wifman and Werman. Seen today in the words Wife or Werewolf. Example: "From the forest, hewn in song and holy groves, in bears blood and calloused hands the first tribes of Man were born." Lore: More than tales and legends. Lore is teaching, knowledge, tradition, the ways and whys of a people or craft. Before Lawgivers gave chains of starry thoughts The Lore ruled the nature and traditions of Man and was how we passed down who we were, the guidelines and warnings to go with the inheritance of Flesh and soul. Example: Sealore (Teachings/Knowledge of the Sea), Woodlore (Lore of the Woods), Battlelore (Lore of Battle and War) Petrichor: The Smell of Dust after it rains, though it is constructed from words that translate it to the Blood of the Gods among the stones, a reference to not only the wonders of the ethereal experience of the scent of Earth after the gift of rain but that most sacred of elements... water. Example: The rapturous scent of Petrichor filled the spring morn as the trees seemed more radiant and otherworldly than at any other time of the year. Rapture: Often the result of a state of extreme emotion, frequently used akin to the similar word Ecstasy. Referring to an intense emotional state of elation or excitement wherein one is "carried off"; their consciousness seeming to drift from its normal place of function. Time and space seem less defined in this state. Note: American Christian Teachings abscond with this word often used in reference to the second coming of Christ, but it is not theirs to use. Example: Her Rapturous Experience washed over her, she was never the same after that. For the first set click Here. @Hyperborean Radio (Uncensored)

Stonehenge, Ancient Amphitheater? STONEHENGE! The most famous of all standing stone circles in the world! A place of rituals, enchantment and untold legends. But what was Stonehenge used for? Why, We Still Build Them Today! Stonehenge was used for the same thing all monuments of its design are used for... performance! Music, Speeches, Plays all those wondrous things Mankind has found to connect, discuss, revel and entertain ourselves. For Stonehenge's greatest secret... is its wonderful acoustics. Shaped as it is as an Amphitheater, even without a top, sound behaves in a weird fashion within its stone circles. It is not unlikely that a roof of wood, cloth or leather may have covered it at one point creating a dome with which sound may travel far further out to the revelers. Similar structures were built by the Romans such as the Colosseum or Arles Amphitheater in France -depicted in the top right corner- While this may seem farfetched our people have always celebrated events both festive and political with music and merriment and to do that you need good acoustics. While a Valley or hastily constructed amphitheater may do, natural Amphitheaters like Monserrat in Spain and Red Rocks in Colorado -depicted on the bottom- are places our people are especially drawn to for revelry from the moment we realize its acoustic potential. Sadly not everyone is so lucky as to have The Gods carve one for them, so we often build our own. From Cathedrals to Football Stadiums, Fourth of July Concerts to Congressional Halls acoustics have long been a factor in the most important of our buildings and events. Why would ancient sacred sites be any different?-HR Happy Midsummer @Hyperborean Radio (Uncensored)

cleaned_message: Watershed Democracy: The Plan of John Wesley Powell John Wesley Powell was an American Veteran, Scientist, Ethnologist and Passionate Advocate of Ecology. Whose experiences exploring the mostly unexplored Western USA along the Green and Colorado Rivers would radically change him, inspiring him of the necessity of what came to be called "Watershed Democracy" yet what is that and who is this bearded bestial looking man anyway? Born in Mount Morris, New York in the Spring of 1834 Powell went on to fight in the Civil War where he lost most of his right arm from a Mini√© ball at the Battle of Shiloh, forever leaving him with but a stump where his arm used to be. Not long after he would lead several expeditions to chart the West, though they were perilous, one he undertook with ten men and several rowboats down the Green and Colorado Rivers. Only to come out in the end with 6 half naked men and a few pounds of moldy flour between them. He'd become an American Hero but was forever changed by his experiences. After his expeditions, he advocated that America must carefully settle the West as unlike the bounty of the Mississippi and Great Lakes that the East has, most of the West was a Desert. Using a combination of Mountains, Forests and Rivers of the Land he and his team charted the Western Watersheds and advocated State and Country Boundaries to be based around these natural land marks to avoid conflict and the destruction of the Land. However between his stubborn, wild and passionate demeanor and the fact he was going against the Narrative of the Time of the endless bounties of the West and of Gods divine intent for America his ideas were rejected and most senators of the time ended up detesting Powell and his ideas. Yet one wonders what may have happened had his idea been heeded, how different the map would be? Would the Dust Bowl Never happen? Would the Colorado River still charge forth into Mexico? No one can deny, his prediction of the conflict wrought by the scarce water of the West was all too prophetic.
Photograph of John Wesley Powell with Tau-Gu a Southern Paiute in 1871-1872
John Wesley Powell by Edmund Clarence Messer 1889

The Chipmunk One of the less grandiose of America's Iconic Species the Chipmunk (Eastern or Least Subspecies) has made an immense mark on American Culture. With the Animated Singing Group Alvin and the Chipmunks not to mention Chip and Dale of Disney Fame. With its pudgy stuffed cheeks, wired energy and distinct appearance the Chipmunk is instantly recognizable. But the Chipmunk is also the King of the Trees. Despite its small stature the small tree rodent, half the size of its Rival the Grey Squirrel, within their chests beats the heart of a Wolverine! The Chipmunk will actively hunt! Consuming birds, snakes and other small mammals. The Chipmunk is one of the most vicious and effective killers able to force all other tree dwelling or burrowing rodents away from their territory under PENALTY OF DEATH! Luckily they are too small to really be of a concern to us, so we just think they're cute with their Cokehead Energy and Half Hamster-Half Squirrel Appearance. Summer Courtship The Summer Romance. An ages old tradition, yet whether it is but a trifling moment of Summer Folly or a long commitment depends... on you. Our Holidays have many functions not least of which is the bringing together of community and perhaps the conception of new families, yet one that has fallen from common practice are the various traditions of Midsummer. So ingrained is one of these customs that our women practice it on instinct from girlhood. The Flower Wreathe. This long held custom is not simply about the creation of a trifling trinket, rather it is a declaration of intent, of affection and of a hope for something more. Upon Midsummer whatever name it wears the women make their Floral Crowns and should a man meet their measures she shall gift of him her wreathe. There are many customs that follow from giving her his Oak wreathe, returning hers to many others to indicate that he reciprocates. Yet a Great Man may receive many wreathes but now that the intent of the Woman is known it is to the Man to decide how this shall proceed. Does it end here, a summer crush, or does he embrace her? Should he accept, then across the year they may find themselves courting; testing each other and their kin. Becoming engaged in that practice marriage where a babe is conceived and skills are put on trial. Then through Procession and Gauntlet, oaths are exchanged and a family grows. All this from but a moment in the Summer Sun and a modest wreathe of flowers.-HR Illustration for Legends of Charlemagne by N.C. Wyeth @Hyperborean Radio (Uncensored)

You Know The Thing Things! One of the most common words in the English Language, simple, versatile, All Natural, Vegan Unfriendly, and... Political? Things are a matter of meetings, one could also call them a Folkmeet or a Folkmoot -the origin of a "Moot Point"- it was and is a meeting of the people's leadership -and the people themselves- to discuss topics of relevance and various social matters, but they could also be what could be called Festivals, Fairs or Carnivals if said festivities also involved plenty of shall we say political discussions -essentially if Congress met only during the State Fair or Major Holiday(s)- We still call such gatherings the same thing today though in English thing has become more generalized as to include objects or non human entities -Look at John Carpenters The Thing or the Marvel Superhero of the same name- Norway (Storting), Denmark (Folketing), and Iceland (Al√æingi) all maintain a variant of "Thing" as their National Legislature while a variant of the word in another language populated other western countries. Congress (Meeting) and Parliament (Speaking) come From Latin and French respectively. Yet in the slang and common tongue Thing maintains it's origin in tribal councils and assemblies. Mid-June on Mount Rainier It may look like a winter scene, but this close-up of Mount Rainier was photographed from the tree line where altitude and elevation inhibits further growth of trees and shrubs and the lush evergreen forests peter out into icy, snow-covered expanses of white. Look closely and you will see one of the 25 major glaciers on the peak that look much like a rocky, frozen river of ancient ice that ever so slowly flows down this enormous active volcano at its own pace. Some of the glaciers you can see here are (from left to right) Van Trump Glacier, Wilson Glacier, and Paradise Glacier. See more at: www.richleighton.com

Prometheus & Methuselah If you've heard of the Bristlecone Pines of the Southwest you know they are estimated to be some of the oldest trees on earth. The current oldest Bristlecone Pine is Methuselah whose location is kept secret so as to avoid harm to the over 4,800 Year Old Tree. But there was once an older Bristlecone Pine known as Prometheus who was around 4,900 Years Old. Then Graduate Student Donald R. Currey was researching the Little Ice Age and with the Forestry Service gained permission to core the trees however... while stories vary and there is vast controversy surrounding it Currey's Increment borer broke and he received permission to fell the tree to access its rings. It was only then that they realized they had cut down one of if not the oldest tree in the Western Hemisphere. You can still find sections or pieces of Prometheus across various places including Nevada, Arizona and California.

Woolly Vetch Woolly vetch (sometimes called winter vetch) is an important crop used in agriculture for fixing depleted soil nitrogen, and is often planted in fields to correct deficiencies resulting from extensive farming. Found in nearly all of North America, woolly vetch is doubles as a tenacious weed that is sometimes hard to remove as vast numbers of seeds are released early which grow back the next season. Whether they were down on their luck common folks, Doctors on Death Doors seeking adventure and release, Men who did good things that just so happened to be against the law, bad men, good men, gunslingers and show offs, businessmen and barbers, Former Marshalls and Future Marshalls such is their mark that they have already achieved Legendary Status. A time however short truly worthy of Legend and Myth.

Obscure Wildlife of America #4-Eastern Hercules Beetle Range: New York State South to Florida and West to Eastern Texas in the South and Illinois in the North. Description: "Beetles are about 1-¬Ω to 2-¬Ω inches long and colored yellowish or greenish-gray with brown to black spots, rarely are they reddish- brown. Males have three projections on the shield behind the head (pronotum) with the central one the longest and nearly meeting an additional projection on the head. Females have only small raised area (tubercles) in place of the horns. Larvae are large C-shaped grubs like huge June beetles. There are many other species of scarab beetles in Texas. The name rhinoceros beetle has been used for this species as well as the close relatives. However, the name now appropriately is applied to Xyloryctes jamaicensis (Drury). This is a dark brown species about 1 inch long and with a single long upright horn on the head of the males. Females have a small tubercle instead of a horn. Larvae feed on roots of ash trees. The ox or elephant beetles, Strategus sp., are large (up to 2 inches long), brown rhinoceros beetles (Dynastinae). Males have three horns behind the head (on the pronotum). Immature stages look like very large white grubs and can be found in compost heaps or occasionally infest potting media."-Texas A&M

Obscure Wildlife of America #3: Star-Nosed Mole Range: Eastern Canada South Through the East Coast of the America and East towards the Great Lakes and Central Appalachia. Description: "The star-nosed moles most prevalent characteristic is a nose with a ring of 22 fleshy appendages that are used as a sensory device known as Eimer's organs a touch organ with more than 25,000 minute sensory receptors, with which this hamster-sized mole feels its way around. With the help of its Eimer's organs, it may be perfectly poised to detect seismic wave vibrations. The tail is as long as the body, and constricted at the base, annulated, and scaled. The total length is from 161-191 mm. Birth occurs between March and August with females producing 1 litter per year of 3-7 young. They are diurnal and nocturnal, gregarious and perhaps colonial. Burrows are found in marshy or riparian areas. They are 3-6 cm in height, and located 3-60 cm below the surface, often with an underwater opening. The nests are located above the high water flooding level, and are composed of dead leaves, straw, and dead grasses. They are limited by the loss of suitable habitat (moist, boggy soil, humus, sandy loam, marshes, swamps, along streams). Predators include: large fish, red-tailed hawk, great horned owls, screech owls, long-eared owls, barn owls, skunks, weasels, and cats. is a small mole found in moist, low areas in the northern parts of North America."-Virginia DWR
Blinka and Her Kitten Photo by John Marriott

Obscure Wildlife of America #2: Hellbender Range: Western New York South through Appalachia and nearby waterways to Mississippi, Alabama and Georgia and East to Southern Indiana and Illinois and Missouri. Two Subspecies Exist in the Ozark Hellbender and Eastern Hellbender which have Different Ranges. Description: "The hellbender‚Äîsometimes called a ‚Äúmud devil,‚Äù ‚Äúdevil dog‚Äù, ‚Äúground puppy,‚Äù and ‚Äúsnot otter‚Äù‚Äîis a large, fully-aquatic amphibian with a flat head, wrinkled body, and paddle-shaped tail. Its body is usually dark gray or brown with irregular dark spots along the back. Although sometimes confused with mudpuppies, hellbenders are easily distinguished by their lack of external gills. Reaching four to five pounds (1.8 to 2.3 kilograms), the hellbender is the largest salamander in North America by weight and Third Largest Worldwide. Adults average 20 inches (50 centimeters) in length, but can grow up to 29 inches (73 centimeters)."-National Wildlife Federation
La Madre by Walton Ford 2017

Obscure Wildlife of America #1: Pyrrhuloxia Range: Southern Texas, Arizona and New Mexico and Northern Mexico Description: "This 'desert cardinal' is common in dry country of the Southwest. It is similar to the Northern Cardinal in its song and behavior, and the two overlap in many desert areas. However, the Pyrrhuloxia can tolerate drier and more open habitats; it is less sedentary and more social than southwestern Cardinals, with flocks often wandering away from nesting areas in winter. The odd name 'Pyrrhuloxia,' formerly part of this bird's scientific name, combines the Latin term for the Bullfinch with a Greek reference to the bird's bill shape"-Audobon.Org

Memorial Day, What Was, What Is, What Could Be. Memorial Day or Decoration day is a Federal Holiday in the USA where one honors and remembers the lives and sacrifices of the Fallen of our various wars. But where did it begin? After the Civil War there was a call for a National Day of remembrance for the many who lost their lives in the bloody conflict on both sides, May 30th was initially chosen because flowers were in full bloom and it was not the anniversary of a particular battle. Once known as Decoration Day due to the custom of decorating the graves of slain soldiers. Eventually conforming to Industrial/Federal schedules it was moved to the last Monday of May where it remains to this day despite contention. After WW1 the day began to honor all American soldiers slain in war. For those who have personally lost loved ones Memorial Day remains a Solemn occasion, while for others it has become the first day of summer a time for BBQ's, Picnics, Camping and Travel. A Day of the Dead in general. Yet this is not the whole story... Memorial Day stems from customs of graveyard picnics beside flowers and folk art adorned headstones freshly cleaned by loving hands where tales are told of the beloved dead amidst both mourning and celebration. A Vernal All Souls Day once known by many names became Memorial Day, yet in place of Witches and May Trees stand Soldiers and Flagpoles. Some decry the Summer Joys as a lack of Solemnity of a day to honor fallen heroes. But in truth this is a day to celebrate hope paid for in the blood of our Forefathers. Represented in the Poppy, each bloom a drop of heroes blood from a thousand thousand battlefields. So remember the fallen, but do not forget the living. Each child taught of the price paid in blood will carry the flame of our people within their hands. There is no shame in enjoying this day, Hyperborean Radio (Uncensored)

The Battle For the American Spirit I don't need to tell you American history is complicated and has been deliberately misrepresented for decades if not centuries. There has been an ongoing battle, a war for the Soul of America, for "The American Spirit". I am not referring to the oft declared war between Good and Evil, or any machinations of the Devil. No this battle is much more shades of Green than black and white. The battle between the freedom to be as we may and that of a controlling overarching doctrine. One could call it the war of the Pagan vs the Puritan. Though it is more complicated than that. While we are often told of The Quakers and The Pilgrims, we are rarely told of the Mountain Folk or the "Werewolves and Witches" who escaped the flames of Europe and brought their Wild Hearts to American Shores. We are told of "In God We Trust" but rarely its precursors of "E Pluribus Unum" or "Mind Your Business". But if you dig a bit deeper you find centuries of warring ideas, the heathen-like Cedar cutters forced off their hard won homes by would be land barons, the Mountain Folk of Appalachia forcing away the IRS or National Guard. Stories of Old West Psychopomps that take the form of Undertakers, Forest God Lumberjacks, Giant Sailors Atop Clouds, or of the Fallen Warriors Who Dwell in the Meadows of Fiddlers Green, of a God of Liberty who came to Washington, Veneration of the Beloved God Columbia, of a Deified Pioneer or Mountain Men Hermits and Wild Berserkers, of River Gods and Freshwater Faeries, of Dogmen who fought in the civil war, of ancient blond and red haired bear men, of flying Yuletide Elves and Ghost Riders in the Sky. This is a land where Folk Songs challenged Jesus to a Fight and Bear Gods greet the Worthy, where Bees are kept in Mountain Kitchens and Bison come to tea. This is the land I value so, this is the land I live in, this is the side of the story I treasure.

Toys, The Idols of the Imagination Across great mountains, grand forests and the bones of horrific monsters the knight rides to rescue his princess and discover great lands. It's been quite the adventure, then.... DINNER TIME! The Knight is placed upon the carpet and despite protests of being in the middle of something the child finally runs to have the age old argument involving a mean woman and the evils of broccoli. An idea hatched involving a Wicked Plant Witch, the child goes back the quest to avoid Broccoli failed, engaging once more in the most ancient of rituals, Play. In their hands, one of the oldest of old things an Idol with whom the possibilities are endless once the spell is cast, a Toy. Though one may know them as Action Figures or Dolls, the correct classification an argument that may never end upon the Playground. Yet from now to the long long ago stretching back countless ages it is a common object of affection, imagination, hope and the potential of the days to come. Nowadays it may be the Superhero or Barbie Doll but once the figures whose faces stared back from the toys were those of the Gods and Heroes. Apollo, Heracles, Thor and many more. A wooden or ivory facsimile of the divine with which many grand adventures were had! A popular gift at Saturnalia and Yule from long ago to this very day. When the boys came of age or the girls married they would ask the Gods to bless their toys, these childhood treasures eventually passed on or ritualistically destroyed as many of us did with our beloved wooden and plastic friends. A rite of passage that has never left us until perhaps recently... Yet we can truly return these childhood idols of Gods and Man once more to enliven that most sacred of gifts, the game of childhood. In what way could the Gods more inspire, touching the hearts and souls of their people, then to be the beloved friend, role model and protector to those who need them most? Mother's Day (A Son's Love) Dear Mothers Women from girlhood speak of the desire for unconditional love; but they have it already, or it is easily found if not. This love is to be found in your Sons. While it is true a Son might grow to dislike his Mother; love and like being two different things. But you can rest assured he will ALWAYS love his Mommy, without reservation. There is not a Son among the Hyperborean people; child or grown, that would not move the world to save his Mommy or even raise every last inch of it shaking the very roots of the Earth itself in vengeance of her. He will love her completely and truly for the entirety of his life from his first wail to his last gasp, even after she is gone. So raise your sons well! Be gentle with him. Guard his heart so that he might not become cruel, but remember; You are raising a Man. A child brought into this world through countless ages of great hardship and even greater joys, by you! Born and bred of love, a love whose sole purpose is to defend his people with the same vigor he would defend you. To safeguard the vulnerable but not the weak, to teach the lessons he has learned throughout his life so that those under his protection might thrive. So teach him well. Teach him the respect he is due and the responsibilities he must bear. Teach him of sacrifice and love. Teach him his value so that he might not settle, nor demand more than is his due. Teach him both his own value and the value of others. Teach him to think for himself. To question. To understand and see the world around him. Teach him a little rebellion is good for the soul of a Man and to be expected. But also teach him where to draw the line. To give respect but to demand it in return! Remember he's not the shield, nor is he the spear. He is the man who wields these tools! Not the tool to be wielded... Remember it's only through you he will learn what a woman SHOULD be, so be noble. Remember he will one day demand your example of womanhood in a wife of his own. A Woman who will in turn give you Grandchildren who will also honor their Grandmother; or not, in the same way he himself had been taught by you. Become honored. Raise your sons well. Raise them with the dignity and pride only a Mother can have in her Sons! Happy Mothers Day. We Will Always Love You Your Sons The Hyperborean Men of the World. url_title: United States of America (1776-) Patriotic song "Columbia, the Gem of the Ocean" (1852)
url_description: "Columbia, the Gem of the Ocean" is a United States patriotic song which was popular during the mid-19th and early 20th centuries, especially during the Civil War era. It functioned as an unofficial national anthem in competition with "Hail, Columbia" and "The Star-Spangled Banner" until the latter's formal adoption as the national anthem of the United States in 1931. For many years, the song's melody was used as the Voice of America's interval signal.

url_title: It's Everybody's Business | Cold War Era Propaganda Cartoon on Capitalism & Free Enterprise | 1954
url_description: ‚óè Please SUPPORT my work on Patreon: https://bit.ly/2LT6opZ ‚óè Visit my 2ND CHANNEL: https://bit.ly/2ILbyX8 ‚ñ∫Facebook: https://bit.ly/2INA7yt ‚ñ∫Twitter: https://bit.ly/2Lz57nY ‚ñ∫Google+: https://bit.ly/2IPz7dl ‚úö Watch my "Old America" PLAYLIST: https://bit.ly/2rOHzmy This animated short film is a Cold War-era propaganda product presented by the United States Chamber of Commerce. The main goal of the cartoon is to glorify the capitalism and the free enterprise system. The film does a great job of demonstrating the basic concepts of capitalism. It explains how business and competition works. It says that we pay taxes to have schools, hospitals, roads, fire and police departments, aid to the needy and obviously national defense. It also says that we shouldn't want the government to provide non essential services since they have to be paid for by higher taxes. The film was produced by John Sutherland. The Freedoms Foundation awarded the film its gold honor medal as "the best film developed in the United States during 1954 to further better understanding of the American way of life". HISTORICAL BACKGROUND / CONTEXT After World War 2 nuclear anxiety, anti-Communism and international political realignments fueled the Cold War-era United States and turned the country's media landscape into a battleground from the late 1940s on. In the press, on the radio, and increasingly through the newly emerging medium of television, business and labor struggled for power over the national consciousness. These opposing forces fought to redefine the economic structure of the American nation. To most working people, postwar "normalcy" meant a final farewell to Depression-induced privation, access to consumer goods unavailable during the war years, and a redistribution of the economic pie through the newly powerful labor movement. To business, however, the end of hostilities promised freedom from New Deal liberalism. Corporations sought an end to planning and government influence, to communist, socialist and labor movements, and above all, shrinkage of the public sector, swollen in sixteen years of economic depression and war. Both sides characterized their points of view as patriotic and their opponents as un-American. Business fought for influence through organizations like the U.S. Chamber of Commerce. Their intentions were presented as lofty and neutral: to educate Americans about their economic system and its benefits. Launching a giant propaganda offensive, these organizations pumped out press releases, published books, organized public and private meetings, bought advertising and produced motion pictures. Differences between capitalism and communism: Capitalism and communism are two political theories which can be stated as the complete opposite of one another as their fundamental ideologies contrast each other in the most prominent ways. Capitalism can best be defined as a financial and a social system that recognizes individual property rights, individual consumption and approves of the private ownership of capital. It gave rise to the industrialization and is based on the rights of the individual and allows individuals unlimited opportunities in creating wealth for themselves. Capitalism also encourages the individual to own as much property and goods that they can afford to buy which in turn results in inequality. This inequality then results in each citizen striving to accumulate more wealth in order to stand above the rest and yet, each individual is supposed to respect the rights of other individuals. The citizens of a capitalist society are provided with equal opportunity when competing as sellers or buyers of goods or property, with the government playing no part in it except setting up certain rules and regulations regarding the process. Capitalism is honest competition and letting the marketplace decide who has the better product for better prices and one sees no oppression of the individual here as a result. Communism is based on the belief that individual gain must be scarified in order to achieve collective gain. Thus‚Ä¶

Dogface Bridge Located along Indiana's Kankakee River, there is bridge that is said to harbor a spectre with the body of a nude woman, but with the head and face of a dog. According to a story dating back to the 1950's, a honeymooning couple was driving across the bridge one stormy night, when suddenly, a hound dog appeared to walk out in front of them. They swerved to avoid hitting the animal, but of course, their vehicle plunged into the river, decapitating the wife in the process. In some stories, the dog is taken down with them, while others believe that the dog is a malevolent spirit who intentionally caused the wreck. Could the apparition of the dog faced woman be some mutated entity that manifested from this tragedy? Photo by Doug Plencher

Roanoke Phantom In the days of the early settlers on the Roanoke River, hunters told tales of the Phantom that inhabited the forest. According to the stories, the phantom had once been a man of flesh and bone, whose wife and child had been killed by the Moratoc Indians. From that day forward, his passion was vengeance. It was a passion that left its mark on the forest for centuries to come. The phantom was described as being seven feet tall, with a bushy, black beard. He carries a knife in each hand, with a third cleaned between his teeth. Fearsome as this image may be, it's the eyes that are seen first, glowing red with fury. As one story goes, the Moratoc were attacking a white settlement, setting it ablaze and killing anyone they saw as a threat. The Moratoc were known for taking able-bodied women and children as slaves. The sun was barely peaking over the treetops as the savages led their bound captives along the river the next morning. Suddenly, a thick fog began to form around them. The settlers could hardly see 6 inches in front of them through the haze, and they all froze in place when they heard the agonizing, gurgling screams of their captors. Then everything went quiet. Not even the frogs were singing now. After a few moments, one set of heavy footsteps began approaching the women and their terrified children. They could not make out any image of what was standing in front of them, but out of the fog came a voice. It was strong and comforting, "Do not be afraid," it said. Suddenly the ropes binding them fell to the earth. "Go now. Return home. They will not trouble you again." Later, when the women told their account, they said that after the voice spoke to them, the fog lifted. They were astonished to find that the Indians lay dead, all around them. Their throats had been cut. Their hero was never seen, but for many decades since, stories persisted of the fierce phantom, watching over the settlers as they prospered in a new life.

Tradescantia virginiana, Virginia spiderwort Tradescantia is a genius of 85 species of herbaceous perennial wildflowers. Family: Commelinaceae Common names of this species include Wandering Jew, inchplant, spiderwort, and dayflower. Virginia Spiderwort has a plethora of medicinal uses. In folk traditions, it was made into tea to treat stomach upset and constipation. This tea can also be beneficial for kidney issues and ‚Äúailments or rupture‚Äù related to the uterus. A poultice of the root is used for cancer. The Cherokee cooked young growth and leaves parboiled, fried, or mixed with other greens. The secretion from the mashed leaves can be used to treat bug bites and scratches. "The entire plant is edible. The flowers and leaves can be eaten raw and added to salads. The leaves can also be added to soups, omelets and stir-fry. The stems can be braised or roasted like asparagus. Spiderwort does not get bitter in the heat of the Florida Summer like many other greens."

Heathenry Heathenry is not a religion, nor is it a philosophy; it is something else entirely, something more, more important, more integral to mankind than any mere belief system could ever be. And it's all in the name. A Heathen is "Of the Heath' 'An Inhabitant of Open Country" In short a country person specifically one connected with the land and the people on it. The bone and blood that fills the soil, the trees planted by their ancestors centuries before. They know the path of the creek, the nature of the trees, the mark of the mountains, the stories of the stones and valleys. The reason Heathen became synonymous with the Old Ways, Paganism or "Ethnic Faith" is because the countryside is the place where the beliefs, stories, customs, history and wisdom of the people is most well protected. Here the beliefs of the Church's Religion ebb and sway falling away nearly as fast as they come up. Instead songs sung in the pub, the naming of children to cheering crowds, reading the sun and the wind to find the storms who may come for the wheat or sink the fishing fleets. Such is the Heathen that they know their land, they know their community; its history, its nature and how it all interacts. When Heathens fade from this world they take comfort in having lived a life with those they held most dear as their flesh joins the ancestors in the soil and the sea, one once more with the land and folk they so treasured while alive. Whether they believe they walk to the embrace of their forefathers or oblivion; they find comfort in knowing they truly lived. This is why Heathenry is not a religion, it is so much more. To lack this most fundamental need of Mankind is to continually feel as though something is missing. The embrace of loved ones and hallowed earth. It is why as long as we breathe who we are, our old ways will never die. Are You Reverent Enough for Hyperborean Radio (Uncensored)?

cleaned_message: When Other Countries Have American Themed Restaurants Have you ever wondered if other Countries have American themed restaurants? Well turns out they do! The results are hilarious and amazing! Popular themes include 50's Diners, Cowboys, Steakhouse, Texan, BBQ, Burgers, Midwest or Sports Bar. Though Amerindian, Surfer and well known city dishes also happen. Japan has several including Bronco BIlly's serving famous American dishes like ‚ÄúI stewed the Bronco hamburger and beef muscle meat of collagen plentiful.‚Äù & who can forget traditional American Bacon boiled and served in the water it was boiled in just like Mom's. There is Indiana Caf√© in Paris which serves Traditional Hoosier Cuisine or Tex-Mex, order classic items like Nachos Indiana if you're feeling homesick. There are also chains such as Ireland's Eddie Rocket's which serves 50's Diner fare though if you want extra cheese you'll need to use the American phrase of "Pimped-Up" to let them know. Quite possibly one of the most beloved institutions and birthday party destination is Spur Steak Ranch with an Amerindian theme whose menu includes varieties of traditional American Schnitzel with Mushroom Soup atop it, Spur is beloved across South Africa. There's Old Wild West in Italy a bizarro Olive Garden. Moscow has Beverly Hills Diner complete with a Pulp fiction dance performed by staff to really make you feel American beside statues of Elvis and Betty Boop. As much as I may seem to be mocking these restaurants I actually love them! Americans don't tend to realize how unique our food is and often downplay it. In these restaurants abroad I am reminded of how interesting our culture can be via outside eyes. From Memphis Diner in Paris to the Yellow Rose of Texas in Peru if you're ever nearby and in need of a steak, burger, brownie, malt, pizza, chili or any other American Dish stop in. Just don't expect it to be quite what you'd get at home. Oh and American Cuisine abroad is quite expensive so you may want to save up first.
