Riverside, Iowa - Future Birthplace of Captain Kirk James Tiberius Kirk Captain of the Starship Enterprise is one of the most well known science fiction characters of all time. Joined by Spock, McCoy, Sulu, Uhura, Chekhov and of course Scotty but there is always that burning question... where was he born? Well! It turns out there is an answer to this oh so very important question! He will be born in Riverside, Iowa on March 22, 2233 (or as the sign says March 22, 2228 Canon is a funny thing) so how did this come to be? Well Kirk was always from Iowa or at least as soon as a rough idea of where he was from was presented in "The Making of Star Trek" and its' Biography of Kirk mentioned he was from a small town in Iowa. This was most likely due to Iowa being considered quintessential Middle America Old McDonald Smalltown Cornland in the general mindset of Americans. Anyway where was I... oh yeah how it became official. Well a local Star Trek Fan Steve Miller decided to put it to a vote at the town council to change their annual river festival to Trekfest and claim to be the Birthplace of Captain Kirk. To Miller's surprise the motion passed and Trekfest and the birthplace have been canon ever since. With Roddenberry even amused at the enterprising action and was quoted as saying ‚ÄúAs far as I‚Äôm concerned, the first volunteer has it.‚Äù The town even has a parade float modeled after the Enterprise called the U.S.S. Riverside, a Statue of Kirk unveiled in 2018 (Kirk not Shatner) and even sold jars of local soil called "Kirk Dirt" which were used as fundraising for the statue. Riversides' Trekfest and all its Nerdy elements continues to this day. And That is the Story of Captain Kirks Birthplace.

A Glad Eastertide Happy Eastertide! But not Easter... or maybe Easter. It can be a bit confusing when the Holiday actually is, even though it is quite possibly the easiest of our holidays to pinpoint. No need to worry about Solar or Lunar Calendars, Solstices or Equinox's. Rather you can see Easter with your very eyes all around you, no calendar needed just look outside. Are the eggs laid? Are the goslings following the Goose? Are the baby bunnies hopping around? Are the kits beside the Vixen and Reynard? Do the Spring flowers pierce the once frozen ground? Do the buds and blossoms coat the limbs of the orchard tree? Even with a light dusting of snow one can see the gift of new life abound. The hope and possibilities of the time before us! This is why I say Happy Eastertide instead of Easter. It depends on where you live and yearly weather patterns. Last year Easter did not arrive until nearly June, the year before the Church's choice was surprisingly spot on. But that is where I live, further North it may be months behind and further south it may have arrived much earlier. But regardless the season of Easter or "Eastertide" is in play you can feel in it in the air just as you can Halloween or Yuletide. A Glad Eastertide To All! Hyperborean Radio (Uncensored)

Your Favorite Spriggan Have You Heard of Spriggans? If not you almost definitely have seen one! With his famous Catchphrase "I Am Groot!" But I may be getting ahead of myself; what is a Spriggan? They are a type of Gaelic Fae well regarded for their loyal and protective natures. They are often plant like with twisted limbs and childish heads. Sometimes small as a flower other times swelling to enormous proportions when protecting that which they hold most dear. Spriggan are the bodyguards and defenders of Fae as well as locations or beings to which they grow attached. They are playful and mischievous known for befriending small creatures which live in and on their herbaceous form; guarding standing stones, burial mounds, homes and newborns as well as many Fae Folk. Not known for their conversation Spriggans have a rather limited vocabulary. Some say they are young giants, others elderly giants, others still say ghosts of giants. Most are sure they tie into trolls but never how. Spriggan are known to freeze in place when untrustworthy folk are near, hiding as plant or hillock. They can also be deadly, known for their disproportionate strength and Wyrd strain of Luck where a bloody war could be happening all around, yet escape unscathed dancing joyously all the while. If that sounds familiar it should, He is Groot! Which is especially fitting as Groot is the defender of the Guardians of the Galaxy all of whom are canonically depicted with Faelike appearances and abilities. Media does not arise from nothing, it is part of a well of lore that reaches back to a time forgot. When used it often draws great joy from our people. Thus In modern media it is important to not only be able to recognize creatures from our folklore and spirituality. It is equally important that once they have been identified to protect them, cherish them. For our spirits are as precious and real to us as angels are to Christians. It falls to us to safeguard their stories. Yours Truly, Hyperborean Radio (Uncensored)

"I am of old and young, of the foolish as much as the wise, Regardless of others, ever regardful of others, Maternal as well as paternal, a child as well as a man, Stuff'd with the stuff that is coarse and stuff'd with the stuff that is fine, One of the Nation of many nations, the smallest the same and the largest the same, A Southerner soon as a Northerner, a planter nonchalant and hospitable down by the Oconee I live, A Yankee bound my own way ready for trade, my joints the limberest joints on earth and the sternest joints on earth, A Kentuckian walking the vale of the Elkhorn in my deer-skin leggings, a Louisianian or Georgian, A boatman over lakes or bays or along coasts, a Hoosier, Badger, Buckeye; At home on Kanadian snow-shoes or up in the bush, or with fishermen off Newfoundland, At home in the fleet of ice-boats, sailing with the rest and tack- ing, At home on the hills of Vermont or in the woods of Maine, or the Texan ranch, Comrade of Californians, comrade of free North-Westerners, (lov- ing their big proportions,) Comrade of raftsmen and coalmen, comrade of all who shake hands and welcome to drink and meat, A learner with the simplest, a teacher of the thoughtfullest, A novice beginning yet experient of myriads of seasons, Of every hue and caste am I, of every rank and religion, A farmer, mechanic, artist, gentleman, sailor, quaker, Prisoner, fancy-man, rowdy, lawyer, physician, priest. I resist any thing better than my own diversity, Breathe the air but leave plenty after me, And am not stuck up, and am in my place. (The moth and the fish-eggs are in their place, The bright suns I see and the dark suns I cannot see are in their place, The palpable is in its place and the impalpable is in its place.)"-Excerpt From Walt Whitman's A Song of Myself Photo of Walt Whitman by W. The Many America's When I started this channel with my friends I wished to promote American culture which I saw decaying and neglected across the country. Over the the last year though I have become more and more ardent in my belief in the fact that America is not a single nation but many. Pretending we are is killing us. It decays the local cultures, disregards the needs of the local community in favor of some amorphous concept of the national benefit. As if the West Coast cares what the East Coast needs, or the Great Lakes concern themselves with the Gulf. The reliance of different regions on the others for resources erodes the local identity and the inability to tell another group to go fuck themselves causes increased animosity to the point that millions pray every year for California to sink into the sea or New York City to Burn to the Ground, though those are just the most famous of what is an increasing sea of bad blood across the Union. Where once the accomplishments of ones region, state or town would've been a means for pride. Increasingly these are treated as meaningless as the overall identity has faded. With it not simply being state vs state, but states themselves are made up of several "Nations" that are tearing themselves asunder. For America at its founding was several nations, each with its own cultures and beliefs. One was Virginian before one was American. Each state was part of the Union by choice, each one had consented to be part of something for the benefits such cooperation could create. In truth the United States was a Confederation of Nations and Tribes not unlike the Franks of Europe or the Sioux of the Plains. To protect our local cultures, our identity we must divorce. If not as a Confederation, or a Union, as an idea of a single Nation. The Mountainfolk of Appalachia and the Forestmen of Cascadia are not the same. I don't have any interest in destroying our cultures that descend and flourish from our ancestors in favor of some false conception of a singular nation.

Spirit Bears, are a subspecies of Blond Black Bears Native to the Temperate Rainforests of North-Western North America. They are sacred animals to the Hyperborean's of this land. The Bear has been our "Forest Cousin" for eons and in some stories the Bears come from us or we come from them, a mythic element that actually originated from Europe and was placed over Amerindian Folklore. Even to this day areas will have Bear festivals, children hold Teddy Bear Idols, and areas will have local Bear gods, Mama Bear and Papa Bear are some of the most common names. Many American Wilderness Prophets would be cloaked in Bearskins or flanked by Bears such as Grizzly Adams and Davy Crockett.

A glacier bear rests at the base of a tree in Alaska's Tongass National Forest By Lance Nesbitt 2018 The Glacier Bear is Native to Alaska. Glacier bears AKA Blue Bears are a rare color morph of American Black Bear, they are a mixture of their natural black coloring and the blond found in the Spirit Bears. This resulted in their blue or "Glacier" coloring. Like most bears they have all the same hair colors Hyperborean's do in their pelt variety.

Maine Lobstermen In Maine and parts of the Northeastern States Lobster Fishing is a traditional and incredibly important industry. Due to the nature of Lobsters though there are incredibly important rules and traditions followed. These require an understanding of the Lobsters life cycle, habits and behavior on a deep level to be able to properly trap for Lobsters. Unlike other fishing industries, Lobster Fishing has remained largely small scale and family oriented with the various fisherman enforcing their own code of conduct such as limiting the number of Lobsters one can take or as seen in the above video marking breeding females to be unable to be kept. Lobsters can live over a hundred years being effectively immortal, only dying when they become too big to molt. As such a properly tended environment and population of Lobsters can feed people indefinitely but it requires understanding, genuine care and respect for these delicious buttery crustaceans.

cleaned_message: The Honey War Have you heard of The Honey War? The Honey War was a territorial dispute that almost erupted into a full blown war between Iowa and Missouri in the mid 1800's. It More or less began in 1816 when a land survey decided Iowa's southern border was at "The Rapids of the River Des Moines" but the problem was, Which Rapids?. Things only got more ridiculous from there with the governors of each territory becoming more and more hostile with each other. With part of Van Buren County in Iowa being effectively annexed by Missouri. The matter continued to escalate when Missouri Tax Collectors or in some stories impatient Missourians cut down a bunch of "Bee Trees" in the same area which gave the war its name. It stopped just short of erupting into full scale conflict due to the intervention of The Supreme Court who decided in Iowa's Favor in 1849 (Some say 1951 or at least that was when the decision was accepted) though it may have also been averted because when men went with whiskey, torches, pitchforks and shotguns. The Night was what can only be described as Fekkin' Cold! Many deserted as a result. One of the many conflicts between different states over borders or other things. As the States were once allowed to war with each other to solve their own issues. This was due to each state effectively being it's own country as opposed to post Civil War when the USA became a more or less singular country. Which one could argue just allows a bigger mess as each state fights the other with bureaucracy and Bullsh*ting. With far larger issues now hanging over our heads from a Dead Zone in the Gulf to the Entire Southwest's Water Supply being more or less hogged by a single state... One wonders...
The Battle of Lexington by William Barnes Wollen

Rouge Bouquet by Emmet Watson "In a woods they call the Rouge Bouquet There is a new-made grave today, Built by never a spade nor pick, Yet covered with earth ten meters thick. There lie many fighting men, Dead in their youthful prime, Never to laugh nor love again Or taste of the summer time; For death came flying through the air And stopped his flight at the dugout stair, Touched his prey - And left them there - Clay to clay. He hid their bodies stealthily In the soil of the land they sought to free, And fled away. Now over the grave abrupt and clear Three volleys ring; And perhaps their brave young spirits hear The bugle sing: ‚ÄúGo to sleep! Go to sleep! Slumber well where the shell screamed and fell. Let your rifles rest on the muddy floor, You will not need them any more. Danger‚Äôs past; Now at last, Go to sleep!‚Äù There is on earth no worthier grave To hold the bodies of the brave Than this place of pain and pride Where they nobly fought and nobly died. Never fear but in the skies Saints and angels stand Smiling with their holy eyes On this new-come band. St. Michael‚Äôs sword darts through the air And touches the aureole on his hair As he sees them stand saluting there, His stalwart sons; And Patrick, Brigid, Columkill Rejoice that in veins of warriors still The Gael‚Äôs blood runs. And up to Heaven‚Äôs doorway floats, From the wood called Rouge Bouquet A delicate cloud of bugle notes That softly say: ‚ÄúFarewell! Farewell! Comrades true, born anew, peace to you! Your souls shall be where the heroes are And your memory shine like the morning-star. Brave and dear, Shield us here. Farewell!‚Äù-The Wood Called Rouge Bouquet by Joyce Kilmer 1918 Kilmer and Watson Served Together in France in WW1

The Lady of the Lake 1940...Wrapped in blankets and hogtied, the body of a woman was found floating in Lake Crescent, Olympic National Park. The woman was identified as Hallie Latham Illingworth, a waitress and resident of Port Angeles. Hallie had been reported missing 3 years prior to her body being discovered. Miraculously, her body had been well preserved by the minerals in the lake interacting with her body fat, resulting in her flesh becoming a soap-like consistency, able to be "scooped like putty." This is a process called 'Saponification' The near freezing temperatures of the water also helped the corpse remain intact. Hallie's body showed signs of blunt force trauma and strangulation. Investigators focused in on her husband. Montgomery "Monty" Illingworth. Monty was known for his temper and jealousy. Hallie's coworkers revealed that she had often come into work with bruises. One day Hallie didn't show for a shift. When questioned by her boss, Monty said she had runaway with an Alaskan Sailor. When the body was discovered, Monty insisted it was not Hallie's body, but a dental hygienist confirmed that the dental plate within Hallie's mouth, was one he had constructed for her specifically. The condemning evidence against Monty, was the rope used in the crime. A shopkeeper came forward with what he said were the remnants of that rope, which Monty had borrowed 3 years prior. The fibers matched. Monty was sentenced to life in prison, but severed only 9 years, before being paroled. He lived out the rest of his life in California, and died in 1974. Ever since Monty was released, Hallie's ghost has been seen at night, glowing in the darkness, a white figure drifting along the surface of the cold waters of Lake Crescent.

What Do These Gods Have In Common? After many claims concerning "But I'm -???- and I can't find any information." Let us begin with the obvious for America. The Bear: As America was settled we returned to our wild natures and with it came to recognize once more our Forest Cousin. We again learned and lived alongside the most beloved of animals The Bear, The Face of Gods. Columbia: American War Goddess and Alma Mater. She who nourishes the ideals of Life, Liberty and the Pursuit of Happiness. She who joins us when we are led astray. So beloved songs were sung to her, giant idols carved, people once even called America Columbia. Paul Bunyan: Born of trees and mountains, his axe crafted by dwarves and whose mighty crew molded the nations landscape reminding man how to live with nature. When his lessons were scorned Paul took his leave to the North Pole where he and babe now create the Northern Lights. Kris Kringle: Santa Claus, the God of Christmas, Children, Hope and Winter Storms, The King of the North and Beloved Dead who gives gifts to the noblest of children and punishes the worst. Embodying the Spirit of Giving and Communal bonds. Joe Magarac: The Spirit of American Steel and God of crafting, Industrious and Hard Work, Born of Storms and Mountain Ore. He so loved his people that he melted his metal flesh into the steel itself so that they may work and flourish. Lady Luck: The most fickle of Gods, credited with the Revolutionary Victory that created America, today her shrine can be found, it is known as Las Vegas. Where the Lucky and Unlucky alike court her favor. Barn Quilts If you've driven across Rural America you have probably seen a painted Barn Quilt. Hanging on the side of a house or barn these large square examples of Folk Art have a rich history stretching back to before the founding of the country. Similar in appearance to the Pennsylvania Dutch Hex Sign the Barn Quilt is less specific to an individual group and is practiced in Rural areas from the East Coast through to the Southwest. Though they are most well known from the Midwest where certain areas have a painted Quilt Square on pretty much every barn if not multiples. A Barn Quilt is rather simple in idea but immensely varied in design. As the Barn Quilt can be any pattern or shape but is most often painted with Quilt patterns and designs. Such as Corn and Beans, Jacob‚Äôs ladder, Compass Star and Carpenter‚Äôs Wheel, among many others. Many are based off patterns that have been passed down in family lines making the Barn Quilts a form of familial Heraldry. Other Barn Quilts will use regional, local or even historic patterns to paint their Barn Quilts. Many of the Barn Quilts are painted in honor of historic moments and even in memory of a loved one. Despite the iconic Folk Paintings they are today, the oldest Barn Quilts are thought to be pictures sewn into Quilts and Hung on the Side as a way to communicate who lived there or even occupation. They have since exploded in popularity since the turn of the millennia and become a popular tourist attraction with several Barn Quilt Trails popping up. (Some people who will not be named because I don't agree with disparaging the differently abled think they invented it in 2000) Do You Know of Any Barn Quilts? Atomic Tourism Over the Course of Four Decades the US Government conducted 928 Nuclear Bomb Tests in The Yucca Flats just over 60 miles outside Las Vegas. In true Las Vegas fashion they capitalized on the tests and began as the New York Times put it ‚Äúthe non- ancient but nonetheless honorable pastime of atom-bomb watching.‚Äù with Dawn-Bomb parties being held at businesses or on the hillsides just outside the blast radius with drinking and singing while they waited for the bomb to drop. Then wearing dark goggles and bracing themselves for the heat wave and raging winds people would gleefully watch the spectacle of the worlds largest bomb being dropped. Las Vegas even became known as "Atomic City" in their promotions of the cities Atomic Tourism. The Mushroom cloud became a popular symbol being made into fashion, candies, Toys, Showgirls Costumes, postcards, headdresses and even Miss Atomic Beauty Contests. The bombs were dropped around once every three weeks and even after the bomb dropped the craters were common tourist sites with people arriving to take pictures and look at the place the bomb had been dropped. Without this BOOM! in Atomic Tourism Las Vegas may never have become the city it is today. As the Cities custom of living in the "Now" was on full display here forget the worries of the Cold War with booze, singing and a giant bomb. Don't Forget Your Wallet, Vegas Sure Won't.

Hoop Snake This legendary creature is just like any other snake at first glance, but when it sets its sight on the next meal, be it human or critter, the serpent takes his own tail into his mouth and rolls like a wheel after the victim. What's more, the Hoop Snake has a poisonous stinger at the end of its tail, and if while in the pursuit of its prey, it should get caught in a tree, that will be the end of it. This seemed to be a fairly common occurrence, as it was suggested that if you found yourself in the path of this predator you should take your safety in a tree. The impact would unloop the snake, the stinger would become stuck, as this unusual creature cannot pull its stinger frontwards, it would starve. In these cases, the tree would become the victim. The poison would surely kill it. In one incident, an unfortunate woodcutter fashioned a toothpick from the splinter of such a tree, and he was dead before nightfall.

Tinkerbell The beloved animated Disney character from Peter Pan, based on the fictional character first created by J.M. Barrie for his 1904 play Peter Pan and later novelization in Peter and Wendy. Most people have based their understanding of Faerie off this character and that is perfectly understandable as people learn from stories and when combined with "Seeing is believing" well quite frankly this is a powerful spell cast upon the innocent Hyperborean mind. While she is NOT Faerie she is quite obviously Fae. So if she is not a Faerie or a Pixie what is she? Tinkerbell is what would be known as a sprite! A tiny glimmering light of hope and innocence that is as malevolent as she is gentle. Sprites are tiny creatures often winged but not always and are known to perform such wonderous tasks as the setting of dewdrops upon the flowers in the morning sun or guiding pollen to the flowers so that they might reproduce. Sprites on occasion ride upon the rays of light that cast through the canopy or even the sparks of the evening flame. While Tinkerbell might be fictional in and of herself this does not mean we cannot love her, appreciating her character and imagery, her heroism however small and overlooked. To safeguard not only her but our long and varied customs, we must first recognize her for what she is regardless of any misnaming by her various creators. She is a Sprite! A cute, adorable, mischievous little Sprite! Is that not enough? What more must she be? Is such a thing as a Sprite too small for you? Or is she... perhaps... the perfect size? Guardians of Traffic by Henry Hering and Frank Walker 1930's The Guardians of Traffic in Cleveland Ohio are massive outdoor Art Deco Sculptures designed by Frank Walker and carved by Henry Hering and a large team of artists. All of the massive over 40 foot figures are crowned in either Laurel Wreathes of Winged Helmets. They also hold a different means of transportation meant to indicate the progression of transport. 3-Gun Style ‚ÄúNo man has the right to be an amateur in the matter of physical training. It is a shame for a man to grow old without seeing the beauty and strength of which his body is capable.‚Äù-Socrates One of the most common, complex and important questions that we get asked regularly is "What Martial Art if any should one seek to learn?" The reality is there is no singular style that is best and it is often situational. This is why Hyperborean Martial arts such as Catch, Boxing and Wrestling often incorporate many differing styles into their training. But while these function well for Hand-to-Hand combat Hyperborean's also have a long history of armed martial arts. Not least of which is the use of firearms. The capability to use one expertly was once a mark of adulthood. So the real question is "Which martial art fits most into the modern world and has the greatest probability of being useful in the most situations both real and imagined?" To that we suggest taking up the sport of 3 Gun, though potentially cost prohibitive for some it provides the most well rounded skill set for the modern world and is usable both on and off the modern battlefield... and lets face it "It's just fun to make guns go brrrr!". - 3-Gun Style is a sport that involves proceeding along timed courses using 3 Guns: Rifle, Shotgun and Handgun while shooting certain targets and NOT SHOOTING others. These obstacle courses are often reminiscent of Zombie-Apocalypses, Old West Shootouts and other common adventurous scenarios. It is probably one of the best ways to train oneself physically, mentally or strategically for the modern world. Even if one never needs to use it off the course and firing range. After all it is what was used to train John Wick Himself! Are You Capable Enough for Hyperborean Radio (Uncensored)?

What if I told you we still wear Traditional European Dress? The most common style of dress one may see in modern America is a combination of shoes Sneakers/Boots work pants Jeans/Cargo Pants A light shirt T-Shirt a light jacket Flannels etc. a hoodie and maybe a hat. This style has remained more or less unchanged since the 1990's. Many will decry this as a degradation of style or a symptom of the downfall of civilization! But that is far from the truth. Without strict social demands as to what one can and can't wear we simply return to our own nature and as such anything we wear must serve some kind of pragmatic purpose. As such with what we have at our disposal we rebuilt a traditional European Dress using modern garments. The hoodie is the modern cloak, work pants a form of light armor akin to the past, shoes are hobnail boots, the two layers of shirts are a continuation of older layered garb. This returning to pragmatism and making what can be termed a "Modern Traditional Dress" has sent the Fashion Industry into a panic! As after dragging around the zeitgeist by its nostrils for the last thousand years people finally realized that the same industry whose passion is making dresses for men and suits for women is more a symptom of mental illness than anything they'd like to represent. What is missing that we can all sense from this modern dress is in fact Quality. If we truly wish to return to a form of clothing that is less controlled by large industry and better for us as a people than my suggestion is to take what works for people and simply return to traditional materials and tailoring methods. After all what are logos and graphic prints if not a replacement for folk patterns and embroidery? With our peoples natural builds, fabrics and symbols taken into account this common clothing would be a natural continuation of any traditional garb of Europe. We are as we have always been, Are You Pragmatic Enough for Hyperborean Radio (Uncensored)?

Washington's Vision While at Valley Forge Washington had a vision of a goddess. This tale is said to originate with Washington at Valley Forge but was not published until the 1880's. Oatmeal cream pies 1 cup butter 3/4 cup packed brown sugar 1/2 cup white sugar 2 eggs 1 tbsp molasses 1 tsp vanilla extract 1/2 tsp salt 1/4 tsp ground cinnamon 1 tsp baking soda 1 1/2 cups flour 1 1/2 cups rolled oats 1. Mix butter and sugars together. 2. Add eggs, vanilla, soda, molasses, salt, cinnamon. 3. Add flour then oats. 4. Use a cookie scoop (preferably) and drop into cookie sheet. Press slightly to get a flat cookie. Bake at 350 for 8-10 minutes, until they're just starting to brown. Let cool completely before adding the middle 'frosting'. Courir de Mardis Gras The Courir (Running) of Mardi Gras is a Cajun tradition, not dissimilar to Wassailing but far far more debauched and riotous. It involves homemade costumes in a French Style that has changed little in the last few hundred years, Horse Back Riding capitaines, A group of "Villains" who physically beat any offenders who break the rules, singing, live folk music, chasing a chicken in an attempt to catch it, scaling a greased up pole, dancing and plenty of drunken merry making ending in a massive Cajun Feast involving communal gumbo and much much more. A unique cultural experience of Louisiana's Cajun tribes.

Nine Common English Words With Pagan Meanings Weird: This is still used correctly even if we don't realize it. Previously Spelled Wyrd as in the Web of Wyrd or the God Wyrd it means the unexplainable, the unexpected, the odd, the strange, the lucky combined! Modern remainders of this ancient meaning include The Weird Sisters and Weirding Women. Isn't that Weird? Example: "Christ is Mighty, but Wyrd is Mightier"-Old English Saying Oz: If you hear the word Oz you might think of a nickname for Oswald or Osbourne, perhaps even The Wizard of Oz! But Oz is actually a very old word. It's meaning? God or Godlike! Which might explain why most people with Oz as a name are A LOT. This is also the name and pictographic meaning of the English "O Rune". Thus The Land of Oz is the Realm of the Gods! Example: Norman Osbourne = Northman Bear-God Robin: Robin is a given name but it is actually much more. Robin was used as a code or byname for a god or powerful spirit by British Witch Cults. We still see this today in Robin Hood (Robin Wode) even the bird known as Robin Redbreast is often associated with storm gods and is a favored form of orchard spirit. The church instead translated Robin to mean Devil. Example: Robin Goodfellow = God of the Pagans Jack: Jack is a name for a "Spirit" such as Jack Frost (Spirit of Frost), Jack of the Green (Spirit of the Green), Jack O'Lantern (Spirit of the Lantern) similar to Robin it was used in Engaland to refer to both gods and godlike beings. It also was used to reference certain ghosts such as Jack-in-Irons or trickster figures like Jack the Giant Killer. Example: Jack Flash=The Devil (Possibly Spirit or God of Fire/Light/Surprise Originally?) Ghost: While currently meaning the disembodied soul of the dead Ghost actually has a much broader meaning encompassing not only human souls but nature spirits, spectral beings and even gods. This is in contrast to spirit which actually means "Divine Breath". This makes sense as the line between a soul of man and a household or forest god is extremely loose or even nonexistent. Example: The Ghost of Christmas Present Genius: Geniuses or Genii (Not to be confused with Djinn) are Roman tutelary gods and the divine masculine spark present in men as well as places and things. When we call a man a Genius we are calling him a god incarnate. The Cult of the Emperors in Rome actually venerated The Genius of the Emperor. Example: Genius of Julius Caesar Hour: Descended of The Greek Female Gods known as The Hours or The Horae being gods of the seasons. Every Hour is thus a season unto itself and thus has its own god associated with it. Example: God Carpo the Hour of Harvest (Season) Mad: An extreme ecstatic or emotional state. Whether anger, joy, sorrow, seen in figures such as The Mad Hatter, Mad Max or The Mad Irishman Stephen in the Film Braveheart. There are also several gods known to be mad such as Robin Wode (Another name for Robin Hood), Woden (The Mad God) and The Corn Giant Wode (The Mad). The emotional state of rapture could also be considered a specific type of madness. Those who were "Mad" were sometimes considered touched by the gods or simply "Touched". Example: "The Almighty tells me he can get me out of this mess, but he's pretty sure you're fucked!" Stephan the Mad, Braveheart Stem: To Stem From, we use it with the same connotations to this day. Though more often in association with plants then other uses. However! Stem also has a rather obscure meaning as it is another word for Tribe! (Tribe is actually derived specfically from the three founding groups of Rome thus the "Tri" part) This is most clearly seen in the German Stem Duchy (or St√§mme including Franconia, Bavaria, Saxony, Etc) as well as in a German name for "Family Tree" Stammbaum. Thus each tribe stems from the larger tree of our peoples! Example: "Well we live in the Midwest now but our family line stems from the Alps!" Are you Weird enough for Hyperborean radio (Uncensored)?

Love & Faerie Games The Fae; especially ones so powerful as Puck or Harlequin, they are enamored by these wonderful beasts, these gods in the making called mortals. Especially those whom are their distant kin known as Hyperboreans. There is a love there. A love coupled with the love of games which their divine cousins do so seem to enjoy... Yet the Fae have never been all that good at understanding us. Mortals are the eternal puzzle that they have yet to solve, however hard they try. Harlequin beguiled by human morals and concepts, while Puck is enamored with human Imagination. But regardless they love to play with us hoping against hope that we will love them in return. Such is the hope of Harlequin throughout many stories old and new. One recent example is that of Labyrinth (1986) a film that features "The Goblin King" an epithet and role of Harlequin, played by David Bowie who is a dead ringer for him from his flamboyant outfits to his Goblin and Pooka subjects. In it, enamored as he is with the young Sarah he decides to give her her wildest dreams. Giving her everything she wanted. Her brother gone, a grand adventure with hardships untold and perils unnumbered. The Least She Could Do Is Say Thank You! Or something... anything... "You cowered before me! I WAS frightening." But instead she has to go and end the game. For all the quirks of the Faerie they are sticklers for rules and the game Harlequin chose to play was full of them. In a twist of irony the film ends with Harlequin the only Fae involved in the game to not end up beloved by Sarah. Such is the irony of the fate of The Faerie. They try so hard to be all we desire, but in doing so their lack of understanding makes their grand gestures often more harrowing than endearing. Are You Game for Hyperborean Radio (Uncensored)?

Helvetia Is this Switzerland? Well... Yes and No. This is Helvetia, West Virginia. Settled in 1869 by Swiss Immigrants mostly artisans. Helvetia is a little taste of Alpine culture in Appalachia. The area like most had their German heritage downplayed in WW2 but has persevered regardless. Named after the Helvetii Celtic Tribes that settled in the Swiss Alps the area continues the culinary, linguistic, and artistic traditions of Switzerland. Especially notable is their celebration of Fasnacht (Swiss Carnival) which is combined with another Swiss Pagan rite of Spring Sechsel√§uten which burns the B√∂√∂gg an effigy of Winter. In Helvetia the B√∂√∂gg has been replaced with Old Man Winter but Green Men, Animal and Plant Spirits as well as ghosts and various traditional costumes such as Mountaineers predominate. Other elements of Appalachian Culture have bled into Helvetia including Appalachian folk music and Square Dancing. When Old Man Winter is burnt one is likely to hear Country Roads Take Me Home rather than a traditional Swiss song. The culture may be rich and the Cell Service may be nonexistent but Helvetia's population has sadly fallen to 59 and like many similar towns that preserved and perpetuated traditions in the USA such as the Amana Colonies in Iowa the town is dying. We need to do what we can to preserve these towns and their cultures.
A Mothman Mask During Fasnacht in Helvetia, West Virginia

In Helvetia, West Virginia a Small Community of 85 People has Kept their Swiss Culture Alive and Well Continuing the Tradition of Fasnacht (German Carnival February 21st) while in Switzerland their Tradition involves the burning of The B√∂√∂gg A Snowman and Winter God/Effigy in America this has been transferred to Old Man Winter.

The Great White Moose of Maine In 1891, sightings of a spectral white moose were reported in Maine. A hunter in Bangor, was the first to come forward. The man claimed that this was no ordinary moose. Aside from it being the most luminescent white, he said the creature stood at 13 feet tall and its antlers had to have been 10 feet across. The hunter fired several shots at the magnificent specter, but it was as though the bullets just bounced right off. After this, he figured it best to run on home. The moose was seen again in 1899. This time the witness, a boy on a bicycle, stated that it charged at him, resulting in the abandonment of his transport as he frantically climbed up a tree to safety. He said that after inspecting the bicycle, the animal disappeared into the forest. A few more people came forward with their own stories well into the 20th century. In the 1950s, a group of hunters killed a giant white moose, cut its throat and strang it up to skin the next day. When morning came, they were baffled to find that their kill had vanished! If that wasn't enough to rattle their teeth, when the moose reappeared that night, bloody throat and all, the hunters believe they had to be mad. They shot the moose dead...again, but only a couple minutes later, the thing got back up and slowly walked away. They decided to just accept their losses. The stories of this great white moose don't all end with the witnesses shook up. One man who lost is way in the forest, was rescued by the animal. He said the moose scooped him up in its antlers and carried him back to town.

When American's Lived in Tree Stumps The ‚ÄúAncient sequoias,‚Äù ‚ÄúMammoths,‚Äù or ‚ÄúBig Trees‚Äù as John Muir called them -also redwoods- are the giant trees that once ruled over the West Coast. As a sort of primeval land this final frontier of the contiguous United States was a fabled land for both Americans further East and for settlers coming from Europe to start a new life. Alongside the Gold Rush the most important industry in the area was the logging industry. Given the Fairy Tale and Mythic quality of the size of the trees it was natural that not only would it take months and months to cut them but that they would leave a rather impressive stump. Not ones to let things go to waste the Settlers took to the stumps turning them into hotels, dancefloors, Post Offices, barns and yes Houses! With some being as small as a studio apartment while others were three stories tall! These fantastical Stump Houses are effectively the traditional houses of the Western Coastal States and they existed up into the 1990's as Roadside attractions and Local Landmarks such as the famous stump house in Eureka, California. Sadly many if not all have since rotted away. Though one can imagine the sight of neighborhoods built in the middle of the Forest with dance floors atop amber sealed stumps and homes fit for a Keebler Elf or Forest Faerie.

Godkin All of our people are Godkin. Within each of us lies the divine spark that can be nurtured to shine like the Northern Stars in all their splendid majesty. If he continues to nurture this divine nature he will enter the Lore of our people as a legend in his own right in that pantheon of bards who strike the strings of the soul and the harmonies of the gods themselves. Heikki Lunta, The Yooper-Finnish Snow God You may have heard of Jack Frost and Old Man Winter but have you heard of Hank Snow? Or as his original name reads Heikki Lunta? Well technically that is his original name, he has many variations in his name in local Yooper lore such as Snow, Mr. Snow, King Snow, etc. He may have even descended from a Finnish Snow God from the Old Country such as the one often translated as "Jack Frost" in the Kalevala. Not out of the question as Finnish Americans are most concentrated among the Michigan Yooper culture and kept many of their old pagan traditions from Finland. However Hank Snow has become one of the most well known figures of Yooper Myth and Legend even having the largest Yooper Winter Festival Heikinp√§iv√§ in Hancock, Michigan. He is often depicted with a bushy beard and snow goggles with a winter cap and a flannel. Though he is also depicted as a pile of living winter fur coats. This Heikki festival involves the Three Heikki's the aforementioned Snow God, A Finnish "Saint" known as St. Henrik and a local Grand Marshall of the festival known as Hankookin Heikki. Heikki's legend became most pronounced after his supposed origin in 1970 when David Riutta a local DJ wrote the song "Heikki Lunta‚Äôs Snow Dance" which supposedly caused snow to fall. When the snow is too prolific another song by Riutta is played "Heikki Lunta Go Away". The former of the two songs supposedly gained fame for delivering snow to the Range Snowmobile Club's Snowmobile Race when snow failed to fall. Heikki Lunta is said to be married to his childhood sweetheart Aino M√§kinen and has a large extended family including a son Heikki Jr.

Powwow is defined as folk magic with elements of both Christianity and European folk beliefs. Those who practice it are called "Powwowers" or "Powwow Doctors" or "Braucher" --------------------------------------------------------------- After several years of misfortune and a variety of illness, John Blymire became convinced that he had been cursed. He went to the River Witch, Nellie Noll for her help. After all, Nellie had cured him of measles as a baby. After several sessions, each costing him $5 dollars apiece, Nellie revealed that the person responsible just so happened to be John's neighbor; Powwow Doctor, Nelson Rehmeyer. John couldn't deny the cold that kept up his spine when he heard the name. Everyone in York County knew who Nelson Rehmeyer. Most steered clear of him if they had common sense. Something wasn't right about that man. Even his wife refused to stay in their home, as she described her husband as being "too damned peculiar." Nellie explained to him that the Hex was too strong for her to lift. She told John that he must do it himself. In order to do this, he must burn Nelson's book of charms and bury a lock of his hair. Now, this book of his is actually a well known to the Pennsylvania Dutch. It was written by John George Hohman in 1870. The title: The Long Lost Friend. Within it, the reader will discover old German folk magic, herbal remedies, among other things. (Side Note: the Pennsylvania Dutch are of German descent, not Dutch, I guess people were confused back then, but I haven't really looked into it). Fueled by desperation and rage, John entered Nelson's home with 2 other men. They beat Nelson, and tied him to a chair, then interrogated him on the location of this book. When it became clear that Nelson wouldn't budge, John drenched him in kerosene and set him on fire. At his trial, John Blymire claims that even though the flames engulfed the body, it did not burn. Nelson Rehmeyer's house still stands. The area, origin Rehmeyer's Hollow, has been commonly referred to as Hex Hollow ever since Nelson's death. There are many stories involving the paranormal associated with the property. Some claim to see a black dog with red or green eyes, looking down from the branches of the tree under which, Nelson was buried. Teenagers have created a tradition of throwing rocks at the house, only to have the rocks hurtled right back at them.

Jester of the Faerie Court There are some things that are older than old, so old in fact that despite appearing everywhere you look, you never give them a second thought. Among such things is one of the most prolific and widespread deities of Europe and you never even knew he was there. Who is He? He has been called many things. Some call him The Grand Actor, others name him The Dark Assassin or The Great Jester. You may even know him as The Goblin King, his most prolific name however is The Harlequin. Though in recent years one more infamous epithet of his has become a household name... The Joker. He is The Divine Fool, The Jester of the Faerie Court and a most powerful Fae King. He is the oldest friend of Puck sharing with him his fascination of Mankind and his penchant for using reality as a plaything. But the playmates of The Harlequin are not children. It is with far more lethal individuals that the Harlequin chooses to play his games. He has many followers, at first glance they may appear to be quite mad. It is far worse than that, his followers are in fact incredibly sane. The Harlequin does not understand these things mortals treasure; Justice, Duty, Honor, Nobility. These immutable yet intangible things. To understand them The Harlequin has his games, his mummers farces. Elaborate flamboyant plots and contrivances. These games are often fatal though not always, for more than anything else he is puzzled and infatuated with Death and how it ties into these things. The Harlequin does his best to understand, he slays the thief of a cup and slaps the wrist of a murderer unable to understand with his most convincing of performances why these are not just or fair or noble. What strange fools these mortals be. For such riveting endless macabre performances The Harlequin became the idol of Actors, Assassins and Highwaymen alike. This stage wherein the tender strings of reality are played. He has become the God of Th√©√¢tre! His visage once shaggy, horned the wildest of Witch Gods, soon became draped in pied patterns of finery. His black mask replaced with elegant patterns. He became embodied in The Court Jester, The Mime, Pulcinella, Pierrot, Arlecchino, Punch and even the humble Clown. His visage spread with his craft across the realm on the front of Playing cards, the circus clowns reigning in charging elephants defying death with a manic cackle, they prance at the edge of Carnival, his followers juggle and play for the whole world is their stage! In due time even when the Wild Faerie King became shrouded in old tomes and passing fancies he was reborn in a figure quite well known to us still playing his games, still pondering the riddle of Man. And in this performance a man known as Heath Ledger embodied him so much that he suffered a fate not unknown to those who have come to know Harlequin... he died. To Harlequin and his games, life is nothing but a comedy and standing smiling and confounded as much today as he was the first time he saw us, he marvels at our madness and our supposed rules with contented wonder... "Pagan" Symbols What if I told You There Are No Such Things as "Pagan" Symbols? "Pagan" History? Or Even "Pagan" Gods? Let Me Explain... What we call "Pagan" is merely a term used to refer to the Instinctive Ethnic Ways innate to OUR people. To the point that it was not uncommon to call unbaptized children "Little Pagans". The term however has become corrupted into a dichotomy of Abrahamic Vs. Non-Abrahamic. History, Ancestry and even Symbols the entirety of a peoples inheritance is split, uprooted and taken from them. This is such a strong split that it is not uncommon for peoples to consider their Genesis as a Tribe or Nation to be within the last 1500 or even 1000 years. This has caused a disconnect present throughout entire cultures wherein it is not uncommon to find people cheering the conquest of their own people by the church; because those "Pagans" weren't them, even if their blood, their ancestry and history is entirely tied up with them. It is to the Church that most end up tracing their history from their peoples conquest to Christianity's Judeo-Roman origins and then before Yeshua tied into the Old Testament. This severs most from their history, their ancestry, the entirety of their inheritance stretching back through the ages. The "Pagan Gods" are not pagan gods, They are OUR gods! Jurate, Brigid, Thor, Heracles, Dajbog, V√§in√§m√∂inen etc. Not only that by OUR lore these gods ARE our ancestors both in flesh and in soul. These symbols and stories are OURS they are not pagan. Nor are they lost as some supposedly foolish religion before the coming of the Church, they are a part of us. Our INHERITANCE! The longer we continue to allow the false schism to persist the further we will be torn from our own peoples Neverending Story. An attack on OUR gods is an attack on US, an attack on "Our Ethnic Ways" is an attack on OUR cultures and the peoples. Your Forebears weren't Pagans They Were Your Forebears. cleaned_message: She'll Be Comin' Round The Mountain You've probably heard of the well known folk song "She'll be Comin' Round the Mountain" But did you know its origins? If one does a quick glance around the interwebs they will see claims it originated as a Christian Song specifically in Ameriblack Circles. Or that it started life as "When the Chariot Comes" that it was a reference to The Underground Railroad and later used for Mother Jones a Labor Activist... This is all complete and utter Sh*t. The Song is actually about what else, a prostitute. It was sung by workmen specifically miners and the like who would often look forward to the arrival of or traveling to "Entertainers" specifically of the female variety. Though in the modern day this may seem crude the reality is it was not uncommon outside of the heavily Puritanical areas of the United States Prostitutes' were common and might even have status. Folklore is replete with them such as the magical Brothels of Paul Bunyan Lore or the beloved Mate of Doc Holliday Big Nose Kate or even Pecos Bill's true love Slue Foot Sue. Like most of these elements of American Folklore repeated attempts have been made to clean up the Song rebranding it, changing history in order to fit the false idea of a heavily Christian and prudish nation (Prudish Nations Don't Make Cowboys). The Song despite being considered a Children's Folk Song is more of a Workmen's song expressing their excitement for the prostitutes and the lyrics are all thinly veiled references to the acts and joys the men would associate with these women. The Six White Horses are the Men Lining up to be "Ridden" while many of the other lyrics change too often and have been altered deliberately to reveal the songs original meaning. Don't let them Destroy Our Folklore and Our History.

Yuletide Birds Birds are a common symbol of the Yuletide/Christmas Season. Partly this is due to Ancestral Ghosts often taking the form of birds such as Robins, Ravens, Magpies, Sparrows among others. Part of this may have to do with many birds not going South for the Winter and actually nesting in the woods and nearby human settlements. They would congregate in the old sacred groves where Yuletide and Christmas celebrations would be celebrated with a big bonfire (Yule Log). The birds attracted to the warmth and shimmering ornaments in the trees would be a common sight of Yuletide. In America that has carried over Robins, Sparrows and many other birds remain symbols of the season. But perhaps the most popular by far is the beloved Cardinal one of the most well received and treasured bird of the continent. With its blood red plumage, sweet song and striking Mohawk the Cardinal has become a Cultural Mainstay near the level of the Turkey and Bald Eagle. But it has something the other two do not, The Cardinal is the De facto most popular bird of the Yuletide in North America. Appearing in Folk Art, Christmas Ornaments and even Yuletide Embroidery. This tradition of the Ancestors visiting along with the birds continues to this day. Welcome them leave them some food and a place to call home this Yuletide. If nothing else their Birdsong is a welcome addition to the Yuletide Carols. üå≤üî•üéÑ Good Yuletide and Merry Christmas (Krismas) Folks!

Welcome Sign to the Town of Santa Claus, Indiana Originally named Santa Fe the town wouldn't be known as Santa Claus until they tried to get a Post Office Started and were rejected due to their already being a Post Office for a "Santa Fe, Indiana" after several town meetings the Town was renamed Santa Claus (1856). The town supposedly has the worlds only Post Office named after the Eponymous Christmas God and as a result receive many letters from children around the Country. A group of Volunteers Known as "Santa's Elves" ensures that all of the Children's Letters receive a reply from Santa Claus.

The Christmas Pickle The Christmas Pickle is an American Christmas Tradition where a Pickle Ornament is hidden on the tree and the first child to find it gets to open the first present. Starting the Holy Day off with some friendly competition. The Pickle likely originated from Michigander-Germans. It was once thought to have originally come from Germany but apparently the tradition was unheard of in the Old Country. The exact origin of the Christmas Pickle is unknown but the tale of it being an Old German Custom was likely started as a way to sell Glass Pickle Ornaments to Americans Eager to connect to their roots in the 1800's. Though it is also possible it started becoming an American-German Tradition and simply was thought to have originated in the Old Country rather than being an American original as there were once several Christmas Pickle Festivals such as the one in Berrien Springs, MI.

Hunter's Moon Have you heard of the Hunter's Moon? Not that new age nonsense, but the actual Hunter's Moon. The one looked forward to and treasured by Rural Huntsman since the Long Long Ago. The Hunter's Moon is not a Scheduled Moon, it's not even necessarily a Full Moon. The Hunter's Moon is a Hunter's Moon because it is so bright it lights up the night. Thus when combined with Winter's Glittering Snow the Hunter's Moon crafts a day nocturne. In the Den of Winter tracking is easy in the snow while daylight leads to Snow Blindness, it is in this time the Moonlit Hunt becomes a treasured event. The Hunter, the Woodsman, the Parent with mouths to feed, the Hermit, stomachs growling for their next meal all go out into the light of the Hunter's Moon. Whether by snowshoe or pick up truck, alone or in a party this Hunt is something special. The antler of the Stag glitters in the night, hoofprints following like sunken memories and should they escape your keen eyes one can always follow the Blood Upon the Snow. So the real question... Have you enjoyed the Moonlit Hunt? -I.M.Knosp Picture: An actual Hunter's Moon reflected off of the snow Are You Jolly Enough for Hyperborean Radio (Uncensored)?

Snowball fight from A Book of Winter Sports: An Attempt to Catch the Spirit of the Keen Joys of the Winter Season 1912 "We have had great times snowballing since this snowfall the 22nd NY and the 1st Ver- mont regmt got at it and the 1st Vermont drove the 22nd completely out of the field into their quarters, then the nex night the 22nd came up after our regmt and the 9th NY to go [end of page] down and help them drive the 1st Vermont so we went down officers and all, The Vermont regmt lay on the hill in edge of the woods they were all formed in line and deployed skirmishers, we skirmished with them about half an hour, then we charged them, we drove them for a while then they rallied on us and drove us back down the hill we formed again charged them and drove them out of their position down into their camp and in their quarters, then they surrendered and gave up, they did not like it much to think that three regments should all pile on to one, to be sure there were three reg- ments of us but we did not number any more men than they did after all for they were a strong regment and all turned out and the 22nd only numbered 400 men, the 8th only 500 and our regiment only 600 and out of all three only about half turned out, so you can see we were no stronger than they were." - Edwin Finch a Teenage Union Soldier Describing a Snowball Fight he was part of in a Letter to his Sister in 1865.

The Mystery of the Carroll A Deering In 1921, Commercial schooner, Carroll A. Deering, departed from Virginia to Brazil, transporting coal. She reached her destination, but when she was found in North Carolina, just one month later and with her entire crew missing, the east coast began buzzing with suspicion. Rumors targeted the captain. It was said that he was a hard hearted man, who often enjoyed psychologically tormenting his crew. As a result, mutiny was also speculated. When investigators were searching the ship for clues, it was found that navigation equipment, personal effects, and two life boats were gone. Food, in the process of preparation had been left out in the kitchen, was rotting. The only life they found, was that of the six-toed cat, kept for rodent control. It just so happened that several other ships had gone missing around that same time, and the government got involved. This indepth investigation proved fruitless. No official statement has been made as to what happened to crew of the Carroll A Deering. But that didn't stop people from forming their own theories. Everything from, they fell victim to the Bermuda Triangle or other paranormal events, to Communists or Smugglers, has been suggested.

"Thomas Nast was born in Bavaria though he spent most of his early life in America having emigrated there in the 1840‚Äôs. Nast is famous for being one of the progenitors of the current Santa Claus image and while his view was likely colored partly by his families Bavarian heritage the Santa Claus he would end up depicting was unapologetically American. He had to be, for Nast was not a painter or an illustrator by trade, he was a political cartoonist. His earliest depictions of Santa Claus for Harper‚Äôs Magazine paint Santa Claus as not only a firmly American figure but also firmly Union, as Nast was a staunch Republican and during the Civil War his depictions of Santa Claus began to appear on a regular basis. The first such one may mark the original depiction of Nast‚Äôs Santa and he is neither decked out in furs nor in red, but in the Stars and Stripes. Nast‚Äôs first depiction of Santa in his Stars and Stripes was printed in 1863, forty years after the anonymous publishing of ‚Äôtwas the Night Before Christmas. Yet aside from the prominent belly and what appears to be white tailed deer not much has been retained from one figure to the other. It is unclear how much of Santa‚Äôs coming down the chimney existed before the famous poem but it is more than likely it predates it and instead merely popularized it. The same can be said of his deer, while the number and name of the deer can both be credited to the poem, Santa Claus having a deer cannot, that predates the poem. The famous poem attributed to Moore can also be disregarded as originating most of the customs rather popularizing them or at least the knowledge of them."- Excerpt of I.M. Knosp's The Origins of Santa Claus. The Legend of Santa Claus "Born in the Yuletide in times long past some say he is a spirit, others a forest god, some say he is a man of flesh and blood just as you or I. He is all of these and more. Many of us grew up hearing the stories of a Jolly Old Elf riding across the sky and flying down the chimney delivering gifts from his endless sack of toys, children filled with Christmas glee would leave cookies and milk, tobacco and carrots all for this Christmas gift giver. Yet his story is much much more told bit by bit over the centuries his myth as rich as any other. In the genesis of his tale he walked door to door across the snowy landscape, stars in the sky, breath frozen in the raging blizzards. A Yule Log or tree strapped to his back and an ax hanging from his side. He was alone. A Yuletide traveler stopping place to place with gifts, for he was a toy-maker adorned in rich furs and smelling of pipe tobacco. Some children greeted him with joyful smiles others with cries of terror as they would be spirited away never to see their families again while they toiled among his Elves. Other times he held the reins of a horse or stag much like other ghosts of the Parade of Spirits. He was on foot or on hoof and following him were the winds of winter, frost and snow freezing the cobblestone paths and windows he passed. His abode like others of German and American myth was a great castle, it appeared out of no....".-Excerpt from The Origins of Santa Claus by I.M Knosp Click the Link Above to Read the Entire Yuletide Article from The Lore Keeper Battle Santa by R. The Banshee of the Badlands It is said that many years ago, a white woman was murdered by a jealous Indian man, in the Badlands of South Dakota. She was already married, and the Indian became blinded with rage when she rejected him. From that day forward, people seen her ghost wandering what is now known as the "Watchdog Butte" region of the Badlands National Park. She is known as the "Banshee of the Badlands", for just prior to the sightings, a bone rattling scream is heard. A scream that seems to unsettle the land itself. Sometimes the banshee is accompanied by a luminescent skeleton, who plays a violin. Using enchanting, otherworldly notes, it is within a trance-like state, that this music lures victims to his mistress, who then wraps her arms around her prey, and carries them off into the sky. These forlorn folks are never seen again.
Photo by Jake Woll. Badlands National Park, South Dakota
Christmas at Valley Forge by N.C. Wyeth

The Gods Embodied Do You Remember being excited for Santa Claus? Hoping to meet him? Or perhaps catch a peek when he came down the chimney? Do you remember that innocent glee that filled you when you by chance saw someone who looked like him around Yuletide? Maybe even running up to them saying "I've been REALLY good this year Santa!"? You may not have known it but this is one of the oldest of our traditions among Hyperborean Ethnic Ways. The gods look like us and thus those of us that bear a startling resemblance to the Gods bear a duty upon our shoulders. To embody them in everyday life and to do right by the sparkling eyed children who look at us with wonder. Others do so as their career or like the most devoted of Santa's in the USA they do both! Both embodying the god in looks and in personality. From the Red Bearded Chieftains -Thor- of Scandinavian Witch Cults, to the Fur wearing goddess Richella of Italy and beyond through the Alps with Perchten and Krampus to Alibon with Father Christmas amongst the Mummers, we have long embodied the god(s) in both appearance and in deed. Even taking our children to meet them as a rite of passage as we do to this day albeit with a more mercantile Santa Claus, which is why many kids will avoid those but jump up and down in wonder and joy for Old Karl with the belly and big white beard who they meet at the grocer. Santa Claus in that moment is the most real thing in the world! More real than you or me, more important than the presents stuffed under the tree. Magic, the magic of belief. The child might even know it is Karl from the grocer but it doesn't matter as in that moment Karl IS Santa Claus. Every child knows Santa is wherever Santa is needed sliding in and out of reality, looking through the eyes of others but once in awhile... well maybe... just maybe he comes in person. We must protect and encourage this Wonder.-TLK Do You Have Enough Wonder for Hyperborean Radio (Uncensored)?

The Beast of 'Brusco Chrurubusco, Indiana, 1898 It was on a misty morning when farmer, Oscar Falk, was fishing at the edge of a seven acre lake on his land, when he saw something that made his bones rattle. The largest snapping turtle he had ever seen had broken the surface of the calm waters. Falk and the turtle watched each other closely for several minutes, before the reptilian behemoth, slowly submerged itself again. In his excitement, Falk drove into town and told everyone he encountered, all about what he had seen. He estimated it to have measured 4-5 feet across its shell and weighed 300-500 pounds. He soon realized his mistake, when over the next few days people began trespassing on his land and harassing him, hoping to get their own sighting, or to hunt the creature. Eventually Oscar Falk stopped talking about the encounter all together, and the story was mostly forgotten.... But then in 1950, 135 miles away in Black Oak, a surveyor (Samuel E. Brownsten) and a farmer (Henry "Potato King" Ewen) were draining one of four swamps in the area, when the drain became clogged. The men reported that the blockage was caused by a monstrous snapping turtle, "with a head as big as a human's!" (Brownsten) Ewen claimed to have tried to aid the animal, " I pushed on its shell, but man, when I saw the size of that thing, I knew I didn't want to tangle with it. It was as big as a beer barrel."

Not Who You'd Think... - The stockings are hung by the chimney with care, in the hopes of the Wild Hunt soon to be there, led by a man neither god nor beast, in his honor the people doth feast. His Name‚Ä¶. is Santa Claus. One of the most well known figures of myth around the world, his image is one of the most prolific of any spirit or deity. Velvet coat of crimson red, trimmed in snow white fur, dark boots, large arms and round belly like a bowl full of jelly. His eyes piercing and cheeks rosy, behind him a sack of toys hangs across his broad powerful back. Ash sprinkled across his face staining it rich and black, walking through the flame of the hearth to place gifts beneath the tree and in the stockings of good little boys and girls, while the naughty receive only coal. His sleigh is pulled by nine reindeer, powerfully built and enchanted to fly across the sky with the magic of Christmas. His beloved wife Mrs. Claus doting on her beloved husband. A chest of weapons, an ax at the ready, a tree over his back and a shimmering light emanating from his personage. Ancient eldritch traditions hang from him as naturally as hair or skin. He appears in hand carved idols, small offerings to ancestral spirits, on products and on sacrifices, in film and literature. Yet‚Ä¶ who is he? Where did he come from? This Jolly Old Elf. This Bearded Yuletide Wildman. This Nighttime rider. This Old Saint Nick! He was born in the Yuletide. For the Rest Click Here

The Grinch's Ancient Origins? The Grinch is a famous Christmas character created by Dr. Seuss. Yet where did the lovable misanthropic Furry Green Man come from? While the Green color was merely a movie choice with the Grinch originally being black and white the idea of a "Hairy man" living on a mountain and being associated with Yuletide is actually an ancient tradition. Wildmen AKA Woodwose are often seen living on Mountains (Rubezahl, Pan, The Orc) and are also associated with the end of the year and the fertile rebirth of the earth. Traditions involving the death of a bear or Wildman only to be symbolically reborn at the end of the mock battle or the next year is older than history. This is often done during the Yuletide. Sometimes the Wildman is a bear, but the Black and White Grinch is even inspired by European Wildman folklore, and when combined with Christmas fulfills an ancient element of the season, with Doctor Seuss even referencing these myths as the inspiration for The Grinch. So remember the next time you watch or read this beloved holiday classic. That you are enjoying the latest retelling of a myth older than modern memory.

Papa No√´l, The Cajun Santa Claus In Louisiana the Cajun's have a Santa Claus all their own, descended of the French-Acadian traditions of the settlers of the region, they have developed a figure known as Papa Noel. A Cajun Santa often dressed in traditional Cajun clothes or as a fur trapper. He rides in a traditional Cajun Canoe led by 8 alligators, one of which is female known as Nicolette, who is albino with growing green eyes to light the way. A tradition calls to light bonfire on Christmas eve to light the way for Papa Noel to find the houses of people, as he leaves his swamp to deliver presents to all the boys and girls. While Papa Noel still enjoys a kind of Cajun Sugar Cookies, he enjoys shellfish far more and had received a rather boisterous girth from his love of crawdads and other Louisiana seafood.

American Football American Football, also known as Gridiron or just Football is the most popular sport in America and is quintessentially American to the point the Superbowl is nearly a national holiday and Thanksgiving is often celebrated with the watching of a game or tossing around of the 'Pigskin'. Football diverged from the traditional Soccer Games of Europe in the late 1800's and the father of Football Walter Camp a Yale Coach is often credited with fleshing out the differences between the two sports. College football became increasingly popular spreading from the Midwest out. With Professional Football finding its origins in 1892. Football is slightly older than Thanksgiving as a national holiday and when Thanksgiving was chosen as the date for the College Football Championships the All-American Sport and the American Harvest/Hunting Festival were joined at the hip from then on.

Thanksgiving Thanksgiving is an American Holiday, descended of traditional harvest and hunting festivals of Europe. As well as arguably some Bear cult ones as well. The First thanksgiving as it is often called was by no means the first merely being used as a way of trying to unite the country as the myth of the Pilgrims and the Indians came about during the Civil War, and it was around this time that Lincoln declared it a National Holiday. Though the harvest feast had been performed for centuries beforehand. Various foods have been added to the table over the years, the Turkey is referenced in New England Thanksgiving Cookbooks, Pumpkin Pie was much the same, Macy's Parade started in the 1920's and Football and Thanksgiving have been joined at the hip for over a hundred years. This Holiday is about Family and Gratitude and should we treasured regardless of the nonsense spread about it by certain people in the modern day.

Ragamuffin Day Ragamuffin day was a nickname given to Thanksgiving as many Irish-Americans would dress up as devils, hobos, homeless, Indians, Blacks, and even cross dress and go door to door as amateur beggars. They would also perform traditional Irish Music while they did so. This was a continuation of ancient Mumming traditions from Europe. This version of the Holiday has since faded and been replaced with an annual Ragamuffin Parade in New York. It is one of the many examples of Mumming traditions that were in America but faded and became boiled down to Trick or Treating and Caroling in the modern day but was once far more widespread. The tradition was also celebrated with bonfires, mince pies, and many other traditions that have fed into modern Holidays.

We get the popular idea that no two snowflakes are the same from his quote regarding his over 5000 snowflake photographs: ‚ÄúEvery crystal was a masterpiece of design and no one design was ever repeated. When a snowflake melted, that design was forever lost.‚Äù Photo of Bentley and one of his Photos both from 1910

Our Wintersleep? Ugh, the snow the clouds I'm so tired, darn seasonal effective disorder - Oh quit you're whining, it's not season defective order the seasons work just fine. We just ain't allowed our wintersleep - Our what now? - *Sigh* I guess I gotta explain this too See most animals in the North are well adapted to changing temperatures, tempestuous climates and Winter. Now there ain't much to do in Winter, seeing as there is snow everywhere and its dark most of the time and the time it ain't could render you blind from the shimmering snow. So what do most animals do? They hunker down for their Wintersleep, or as you might know it they "Hibernate". It's not "True Hibernation" in the way Frogs and Gators do, most animals in the north sleep when its dark and cold and if it warms up enough they go around a bit collecting food or patching drafts "Semi-Hibernation". Then when it cools down they sleep again. We are much the same way, from Siberia to Iberia, America to Tasmania wherever our people go, we would stock up food and firewood and get ready to sleep most of the season away. We'd even prepare much as the animals do, with great feasts to pack on the pounds. In our homes, in our great halls we would take our Wintersleep. Waking for our Holy Days as the wheel turned or if it warmed enough that we may go hunting though at night when the Moon shines upon the snow and the world lights up with an eldritch glow, we'd follow the blood and hoofprints in the snow for a bit of extra meat. There are even memories of this laden across our lands in the tales of The Bear Kings slumber or the Yuletide Myth of the wedding of The Bear and The Maiden Fair. Seen in Snow White & Rose Red as well as the White-Bear-King-Valemon. The Wildman and Woman find each other and go to rest amidst the Yuletide, perhaps arising in the spring with a new generation in arm. Yes, Winter is a time of rest and rejuvenation in contrast to the harsh months of Summer. There is even play the gift of Ullr and Jack Frost for the youngins with too much energy to sleep. They build Idols to Ullr and Jack Frost with carrot noses and button eyes. They play games in their honor, mock war with their snowballs and forts. We even found ways to make traveling more fun with skis and toboggans if anything movement gets a bit easier in Winter, so long as you know what you're doing so long as you don't trounce around all foolish like. Yes, its not Winter's fault we're tired. IN FACT THAT IS HER GIFT. Rather the fault lies at the feet of the world as it is now; that it denies the reality of our people, our nature and our needs, to feed us to their machine. Never resting, never healing. How much closer would families be? How much more energy would we have? How better would the quality of life, the length of life be? If only we were allowed our wintersleep. They even invent disorders, blame the seasons and make artificial summers. Because those in their high towers know, if we slept as we should neath Winters warm blanket. They could not keep things as they are. They could not keep us bound in Gleipneirs reins.-TLK Goldilocks And The Three Bears by Kerry Darlington Are You Rested Enough for Hyperborean Radio (Uncensored)?

cleaned_message: A pioneer and frontiersman, Daniel Boone's escapades made him one of the first folk heroes of America. 250 years ago, Boone led his scouting party through feral wilderness, uncrossable rivers, and treacherous mountainsides. It was a long and hard journey, but because of his determination, the land they treaded on, would soon become settled, and become what we now know as the state of Kentucky. Boone and his party, were the first frontiersman to settle beyond the borders of the 13 colonies. Today, you can walk through the Daniel Boone National Forest, and take the same paths that Boone, himself cleared. You can even find his initials on some of the trees. A fascinating and wonderful aspect of this land, is that the vast majority of the wilderness has been left untamed and unspoiled...just as Daniel Boone found it. Boone lived a long life (uncommon back then), and died peacefully in his sleep at the age of 85. I highly recommend reading more about him. Watch the movies, read the books. He was absolutely fascinating.

On December 31st, 1812, Theodosia Burr boarded the sailing vessel, "The Patriot' and, was never see again. Daughter of former vice president, Aaron Burr, Theodosia, though struggling with health problems throughout her life, was a highly intelligent and cultured woman. In 1801, she married plantation owner, and later governor of south Carolina, Joseph Alston. They had one child. The boy died of malaria at the age of 10. Stricken with grief, it was immediately after this that Theodosia decided to book passage from South Carolina, to be with her family in New York. Both She and the sailing vessel she boarded would never make it. To this day it is unknown what exactly happened to "the Patriot" or Theodosia. There have been various theories over the years. This was during the War of 1812, so some speculated that the Patriot was sunk by enemy ships. Another theory states, that a group of shipwreckers known as the Carolina Bankers were responsible. These men camped out on the edge of Nags Head, a town on the outer banks of North Carolina, and would send out false signals to ships at sea, in order to murder the passengers and crew, and take any goods they might be carrying. What is known is that it disappeared somewhere beween South Carolina and New York, and in 1869 a portrait of what many claim to be Theodosia Burr was uncovered in Nags Head, North Carolina. Part 2 A doctor was called out to a fisherman's cabin, to treat the fisherman's ill wife. When the doctor arrived, he could tell it was only a matter of time until the elderly woman slipped from this earth. He did what he could to ease her pain. The fisherman, though greatful, had little money. Instead, he offered the doctor a fine portrait of a young woman and asked if the doctor would accept this as payment. The doctor was surprised to find such a valuable work of art in the home of a poor fisherman. The doctor asked him how he came by such a thing. The fisherman told him the story of how many years ago, a woman washed up in a rowboat on Nags Head. She had no memory of who she was or where she had come from. The only item she carried with her was this portrait, which she would not allow anyone to take from her. The woman was cared for by the kind people of the town, and she soon became a well loved member of the community. The doctor asked the man what had become of this woman since then, and the man said with a smile, "She married a silly old fisherman" Touched by the story, the doctor said he would happily accept the portrait as payment. But when the woman heard this, she sprung up from her bed, screaming "It is Mine! It is mine! You shall not have it! I am on my way to visit my father in New York, and I am taking this picture of his darling Theodosia!" The woman snatched the portrait form the doctors grasp and fled out into the night straight into the ocean. She was never seen again, but a week later, the portrait drifted back onto the beach. The painting now hangs in the Lewis Walpole Library in Farmington, Connecticut.
