The Dairy Defender John and Mary Corliss, along with their dairy cows, were the most valued pioneers in the township of Alexandria, modern day New Hampshire. Their cows produced all of the townships dairy goods of the time. One day, when John was away, Mary spotted a pack of indians, unsuccessfully hiding in the treeline. These Indians had come around before in the hopes of stealing the Corliss' cows. John chased them off with his gun. Mary frantically began pacing, trying to figure out what she should do. She was unarmed. Then the thought struck her! Luckily, unlike other homes during that time, the Corliss' had built in a cellar stairway with shelves installed above it, on which they kept the wheels of cheese. Mary went over to the cellar shelves, yelling towards the open window, "Come on, boys," she threw a wheel of cheese down the cellar stairs. "Go get em," another wheel of cheese was thrown. She knew if anyone had seen her, they would think she had gone mad, but she carried on like that for several minutes until the shelves were bare and all the cheese had been thrown down the stairs. She looked out the window. The savages had vanished, thinking all that racket belonged to the footfalls of many men ready to defend the Corliss' home. Nope, just cheese.

"Here are some baubles I found in the chest where I got the clothes I'm wearing" He spilled a handful of flaming rubies into his palm. "They're worth a fortune themselves." He dumped them back into the bag and handed it to her. "But I can't take these-"she began. "Of course you'll take them. I might as well leave you for the Picts to scalp as to take you back to Zingara to starve." said Conan. "I know what it is to be penniless in a Hyborian Land. Now in my country sometimes there are famines; but people are hungry only when there's no food in the land at all. But in civilized countries I've seen people sick of gluttony while others were starving. Aye, I've seen men fall and die of hunger against the walls of shops and storehouses crammed with food. Sometimes I was hungry, too, but then I took what I wanted at sword's-point. But you can't do that. So you take these rubies. You can sell them and buy a castle and slaves and fine clothes, and with them it won't be hard to get a husband, because civilized men all desire wives with these possessions"-Excerpt of The Black Stranger by Robert E. Keepers of the Eternal Flame? Man! Women and their candles. So endearing - What do you mean? - Do you not see Why they do so? Well let me help you It's easy to forget what each of us once did for each other. Yet since the time of myth, fire has been the tool of Man. For the Men it was a tool of forestry and forge but for the women it was the hearth flame, the heart of the home. Before matches and lighters, before the flick of a switch could create fire in the blink of an eye. Fire was much harder to control, it was power given form. With simple flame one could build an empire or burn it down in a day. Women have always been attracted to power. Who knows how it began there have always been gods of fire but the one who controls it who holds it in their hand has always been the female. Men wield flame as a weapon... as a tool, Women nurture it. Such has it been since the Long Long Ago, imagine a woman cloaked in only her pride carrying the fire of her people for generations, not the smoldering ashes we see around us today. It's only in recent years fire has lost its purpose, it's light dimmed that The Eternal Flames began to go out. Household after household no longer keeping fires burning. Yet the women still do it you see? They still instictively wish to tend the flames, they have no crones to teach them, they have lost the wisdom of a thousand thousand grandmothers. But the Lore of the Blood is far stronger than mere words. So they continue to amass candles they light them for baths or any old reason. They know it in their bones, their very being that they are the Keepers of the Flame. Long after the Heart of the Home ceased to be the Hearthfire replaced by the soft glow of technology. Yet still memories from beyond the mists of time call to them to guard the flame. One can only hope that one day they will be given the opportunity to keep Their Flames Eternal once more.-TLK By the Hearth (Platt Powell Ryder) 1881 Are You Caring Enough for Hyperborean Radio (Uncensored)?

Veronica americana, American speedwell 1 of about 500 species of Veronica. Veronica is the largest genus in the family Plantaginaceae (plantain family). The Veronica plants are commonly named speedwell, bird's eye, and gypsy weed. Veronica americana is native to both arctic Asia and North America. Many of the Veronica species are edible and have similar medicinal properties. They are said to have a flavor similar to watercress. Veronica americana has been used to treat disorders of the nervous system, respiratory tract, cardiovascular system, and metabolism.

Pitty Pat Pitty pat, pitty pat, pitty pat That is the sound you hear when the Pitty Pat is after you. The sound of malformed feet, swiftly making their way closer. As far back as the stories go, no one ever got a good look at the Pitty Pat, for it is strictly nocturnal. It was described only as a shadowy, animalistic being that had an unsettling, human familiarity about it. The creature is said to dwell on Shipley Hollow Road, which is sometimes called Pitty Pat Hollow. The first accounts of the Pitty Pat came a few years after the end of the Civil War. Probably one of the most common stories tells of a mother traveling with her infant son, in a horse-drawn buggy. It is said that the horse was the first to sense something wrong. The animal knew danger was close. It reared up, and took off at full speed. Taking a sharp bend, the buggy overturned , throwing the two passengers into the woods. When the mother set herself straight, she realized they were not alone. She frantically began looking for her son, who she could hear crying, but saw nothing in the pitch blackness of night. Then she heard something else among the cries of her child. Pitty pat, pitty pat, pitty pat She could just barely make out a figure, thin and slightly hunchbacked, walking on two legs. She had the strangest feeling that it was not quite human. She was completely paralyzed with fear, and unlike most mothers, did not make any effort to defend her child. The creature took the boy, and disappeared into the night. In another story, a steamboat captain was returning home on the same path that the baby went missing, when a "shadowy creature" appeared and began chasing him. The captain pounded on the door of the first home he happened upon, and not waiting to be invited in when the startled couple opened up, he jumped into their bed and stated "I'm staying with you tonight!" Stories continued to circulate for years about the dreaded hollow and the fearsome entity who inhabited it. Some reports suggest that there is more than one Pitty Pat. In the early 1900s, a doctor was traveling through the hollow on horse and buggy, when he began hearing shrieks and chittering from the tree tops, in all directions. He also described the signature pitty pat, pitty pat, pitty pat... only this time, there was most certainly more than one Pitty Pat pattin'! Then two shadowy figures jumped from the darkness, and onto the horse's back. The animal lost all composure and took off running as if hellfire was lapping at its hooves. The horse became detached from the buggy, the things still on its back as it ran off, abandoning the doctor. The man swore he heard the creatures cackling as they rode away. The stories have become a local favorite to tell in modern times, to give folks a good scare, and given the silly sounding name, maybe a good laugh as well. But all jokes aside, many will admit to feelings of unease while walking through the hollow at night. Some say they feel they are being watched...and some still swear up and down that they will hear the Pitty Pat's pitty pattin' behind them.

The Haunted House? Oh yeah? If Halloween is so Pagan and not secular what is the point of a Haunted House then?! - Well I'm glad you asked. Juss calm down a second an I'll explain to you something you already know. Fear! Fear dear child is the name of the game and what is Fear except a thing to be faced? To be overcome! The nameless and faceless horror of the dark oozing dread and despair! Well the haunted house as we think of it now is just a continuation of what once was when great festivals echoed and rang across the land when great play acting sets were erected across the country side with one soul purpose... to inspire pure and unadulterated TERROR in the hearts of the meek, the mild hearted, the gullible and the na√Øve! To what purpose? Well to teach them that they do have courage should they choose to use it. Once we created entire armies and entourages of spooks and specters and nameless horrors to traipse across the moors and fields beating their war drums and blowing their hunting horns for the entire purpose of the young to face in their fear of the unknown. Children and... let us call them "children" would be sent out into the countryside at night unaware of the inside joke that was being played on them as all manner of clamoring and howls of fear and anger and despair and DEATH were howled across the land. All with the express purpose of them being able to find their courage... after all how can one find courage without first knowing fear? What is courage? Well that is another conversation! Now stay on topic! Well see these customs began to be frowned upon by those who seized power through various means and so the Haunted House was invented to take its place. With something as simple as do you have the courage to enter the dark door and pass through the dark passage ways to exit into the light of courage. And a game of sorts has even sprang up among the young now who are unfortunately aware of the trick being played of 'Can you make it all the way through without crying out in fear or jumping like a cat at a slammed door?". So yes it is a Pagan custom of testing your nerve, your courage for those who are young or frail of heart. A small test so that they might learn who they are... that they can find courage even in the absence of light. Are You Brave Enough for Hyperborean Radio (Uncensored)?

In the 1800s, it was common practice on the night of Halloween, to divine one's future. One of the most popular rituals would reveal the identity of your future spouse. A woman should light a candle (this should be the only source of light), and while walking up the stairs, she should carry a hand mirror. She must hold the mirror in front of her face, never taking her eyes from her reflection. It was said that once she reached the top of the stairs, an apparition of her betrothed would appear in the mirror, standing behind her own reflection.

Hyperborean Halloween #1: Scarecrows The humble scarecrow symbol of rural life, Harvest time and holidays like Halloween and Thanksgiving. But there is more to this idol than meets the eye... for starters ever notice he doesn't scare away crows? The reason for this is that scaring birds away is actually not ideal as birds tend to eat pests more than they do seeds. But mostly this is not the purpose of the Scarecrow. So what is his purpose? Well... people like him of course! Same reason we do anything -oh you wanted more? Like Lorewise? oh ok- *Ok grab a beer and sit down for a moment.* Modern scarecrows are centuries old but descend of much older customs. Notably the idol of the fertility god in the field as seen with the Corn Giant Wode or the Greek Priapus. The latter of which often had an idol kept in the field -sometimes with a threatening message of gross sexual harm by the god on anyone who messes with the garden, Greek gardeners weren't messing around- Meanwhile in Germany and the German Diaspora we find the tradition of The Butzemann, a plant spirit placed into a Scarecrow to guard and tend fields. Near Halloween The Butzemann is burned and its spirit is taken by The Wild Hunt, in Pennsylvania Dutch tradition The Butzemann is take by Frau Holle and allowed to reincarnate from her mill. In Saxony-Anhalt the Giantess Frau Harke appears as a Scarecrow in carnival processions. In the modern day Scarecrows are more a Halloween and Thanksgiving decoration found at your neighbors home vs. the Rural fields. However the Scarecrow has immortalized itself in modern culture. Appearing as the Monster in Jeepers Creepers, a recurring villain for Batman, as well as the Companion of Dorothy in the Wizard of Oz. So next time you see a Scarecrow in the fields or in the foyer, remember the long long history and the gods and ghosts who like to smile from its burlap and pumpkin headed visage. -TLK Scarecrow by Charles Livingston Bull Are You Studious Enough for Hyperborean Radio (Uncensored)?

This map by Gotthelf Zimmermann reflects the importance of German immigration to North America in the mid-19th century. When the Revolution of 1848 failed to produce desired reforms within the German confederation, droves of disillusioned Germans turned their sights abroad. Maps such as this helped show them the way. At the time, land in the United States was cheap, fertile, and plentiful, making it an ideal choice for immigrants eager to establish new settlements and to begin new lives. German communities in the United States became so prevalent that on the eve of World War I, six percent of American children spoke only German in primary school.

A map of Cape Cod drawn in 1945 by F. J. Miller. It covers all of Cape Cod as well as parts of the adjacent South Shore including New Bedford, Fairhaven, Plymouth, Buzzard Bay, and Duxbury. It also names important towns and roads in addition to offering a wealth of border vignettes showing various aspects of Cape Cod life from fishing to sunbathing, to gathering clams and mussels.

State Symbol Gargoyle at the National Cathedral in Washington D.C. The Cathedral's Website Describes it as: "Installed in 1975-76, a bear represents the bears on the state seal of Missouri. In its hands it holds the famed St. Louis Arch. The Eastern Missouri Committee of the National Cathedral Association donated the gargoyle, wanting to ensure that the Show-Me State had a permanent home at the Cathedral. The bear is one of 112 gargoyles and grotesques across the Cathedral, which act as water spouts to divert water away from the building." On a Side Note a Bear being depicted on a Cathedral for any reason is always something to make me smile as the Church led a millennium long smear campaign against the bear, as the Bear Cults in Europe were so firmly ingrained the Bear was considered direct competition for the Church, a major threat as one in fact. So it's a little like the Bear Cults still fighting and peeking through.

The Paul Bunyan Trophy Originally presented as a publicity stunt by then Governor and Michigan Alum G. Mennen Williams in 1953 to welcome Michigan State to the Big Ten Conference the Paul Bunyan Trophy is given to the winner of the Match between The Michigan State Spartans and the Michigan Wolverines. It represents Paul Bunyan Folk Hero and God of the Northwoods and celebrates the states Lumber Industry. To this day the two college teams play for the Trophy with the winner keeping him until the next showdown.

When the Cathedral was looking to find new subjects for its Grotesques (The Actual Name for the figures on the Cathedral, Gargoyles are the water spouts or alternatively a name for the protective spirits that inhabit the grotesques) and held a competition in 1986 to replace the faded ones. No two Grotesques are supposed to be the same so the competition had a wide range of options and other Gargoyles currently at the Cathedral include a Gas Mask, a Yuppie and an American Rattlesnake. During the competition Darth Vader came in third submitted by Christopher Rader. However, the figure has since become the most popular draw for the cathedral. If a Haunting is What You Wish? Do you believe in ghosts? No... Scratch that... Are you Afraid of Ghosts? Why? They are Just the Ancestors come to visit. Sure some may be angry, others a bit more temperamental or needy but the ghosts of our dead are nothing to fear. They come on the wind, beside the hunt bisaddle and side saddle, they ride on the North Wind to arrive at our doorstep following the Ghost Lights, The Will'O'The-Wisp's and Jack O'Lanterns. They come as black dogs, furious riders, hopeful gnomes, and helpful mice wearing a bonnet three centuries out of fashion. They are here to visit the living, leaving the Meadows and the Sunshine of the Otherworlds. They peek from the rafters and behind the hay bales, seeing how their descendants are carrying on. If they find us fitting they may choose to stay. Becoming a House Spirit... for a time. They come with the gods and the other spirits of the land. They arrive for a meal, they trick or treat with Buzz Lightyear and Iron Man that one kid that showed up out of nowhere... that one just a bit off. If you are fun enough, interesting enough, caring enough perhaps they will choose to stay with you. For many they find fear in this, a door closed surprisingly! Something going bump in the Night! Or perhaps a light was turned off before your eyes! DON'T PANIC! The door being closed may be Grandpa Tom "Shut that or we'll get a draft! No I'm not turning the thermostat up you pussy!" or perhaps the attic going BUMP! was Aunt Dolores "Well I always thought the Couch was better close to the window" or the light being turned off may be Dear Old Dad "Turn off the lights when you're not in the room Buddy". These hauntings are more than likely just our family ghosts and they are doing family things. Whether they be Hobgoblins, Brownies, Lares, Domovoi or Nisse. Since the Long Long Ago when we Buried our Dead in our Homes, when the mounds were both houses and tombs, when the groves were the forests of the dead. Our dead have always liked to stay close to us. Many today grow scared when they show up, when they try to clean or tidy up, or let you know you're not alone in a world where most of us are. Don't fear or panic, it's just our Family Ghosts. Be respectful, be welcoming, be understanding and do not be rude or insulting. I mean if you came all the way from the land of the dead for a visit would you not be mad at such disrespect? Might even leave in a huff with a few things broken for good measure? So if it is a Haunting you Wish, best be fun! Best be grand! Best be caring! Ask yourself what kind of ghost wants to be around ungrateful and fearful descendants? They're on vacation after all. I.M.Knosp Are You Brave Enough for Hyperborean Radio (Uncensored)?

Halloween Rewind I love Halloween. I love the Halloween season. I've loved it when I was a kid going as a Werewolf, Pirate Ghost and Post-Apocalyptic Raider house to house Trick R' Treating. It has been my favorite Holiday since I can remember and to be honest it's never been about the candy. It was about the feel of Halloween, while I was young I didn't quite understand it, we've all heard the "Halloween was Invented by the Candy Companies" line at some point, but that is a lie. Halloween is a very, very old Holiday. Last year we posted many times on the Lore and History of Halloween and its customs, rather than rehash the same ideas by rote I thought I'd just collect them for ease of access. 2021 Halloween Posts Trick R' Treating Spirit Animals Witch Gods The Eternal Hunter Masking Ghosts Goblins The Grim Reaper Veles & The Dead Will-O-The-Wisp Chernobog Black Dogs The Wild Huntress Vampires Goddesses of Death Food of the Dead Samhain & The Bear King Booo! Fairy Godmothers Graveyard Picnics Fear The God of Gallows Fairy Toadstool Freak Shows Liminal Spaces La Castanyada Halloween Apples Halloween Around the World I Love Halloween Scarecrows Halloween, like the various other Holidays for the Dead found across our lands, is a season. It is not a single day. None of our ancient holidays are bound by calendar dates, you can feel it in the air! Right beside the crisp fall breeze. You can feel something more in the air when the Ghosts & Banshees, Gnomes & Goblins are all ready to revel alongside us! Despite all the pushback Halloween has received from the powers that be it is still to this day a Holiday that is beloved and treasured. I hope that all of us enjoy it to the fullest extent that we are able, both the living and the dead. Sincerely I.M.Knosp & J.A. Coburn of Hyperborean Radio (Uncensored)

Halloween Cryptids #2: The Mothman Mothman is a Cryptid, Alien, Faerie, Mutant or Spirit from Point Pleasant, West Virginia. He appeared during the time span of 1966-1967 (Though many claim he is much older). He is described as having large wings and glowing red eyes. He is often thought to be a Sandhill crane or other bird. However, aside from the usual legends of flying over cars and scaring a passerby the Mothman is also connected to the deaths of 46 people as he was spotted and connected to the Silver Bridge Collapse in 1967. After this the Mothman became more associated with being an omen of destruction or misfortune, perhaps a spirit who feasts on fear?! (According to the Locals who know the Lore, only idiots and tabloids think he causes the bad things he is a warning an omen bringer according to them) In typical American Fashion the Mothman is often considered either a Nuclear Mutant or an Alien. As such the Men in Black ended up being mixed into the story somehow. Whatever someone may think of Mothman his status as one of the most popular figures of American folklore has been cemented over the years with the Mothman Prophecies Book and Film, the Fallout Games, his yearly festival on the Third Weekend of September and the many customs, art and stories created in his name. During Mothman's festival there is a custom of leaving a light on for him, in doing so one invites him to visit their dreams. While those who see him as a monster may balk at that, those who view him as a guardian and a bringer of omens welcome the Mothman in.

Halloween Cryptids #1: The Jersey Devil The Jersey Devil, also known as The Leed's Devil is one of the most famous creatures of American myth, the monster that haunts the New Jersey Pine Barrens. It is said a woman named Jane Leeds had 12 children and on finding out she was pregnant with a 13th cursed the child to be "The Devil" and after the child was born as a normal babe it quickly turned into a chimeric monster and fled up the chimney, though others claim he was the son of the Devil. The Jersey Devil is also the calm companion of the Golden Haired Girl spirit that lives in the Pine Barrens, and is actually intelligent, capable of speech and talking with some of the soldiers who once came to hunt it. While its appearance is standardized now it was once much more amorphous in description. The Jersey Devil has had immense impact on folklore and culture and has appeared in popular media such as the X-Files and is the namesake of the New Jersey Devils Hockey Team.

This WWII bunker was once the home of the Fort Fisher Hermit. His name was Robert Harrill. Robert left his mundane life behind him in 1955 when his marriage failed. He hitchhiked from Morganton, North Carolina to Fort Fisher on the North Carolina coast, where he made his new life, just in the edge of the Cape Fear River in the Fort Fisher Recreation Area. He furnished his home from driftwood he collected and lived on a diet of fish, clams, oysters, shrimp, snails, and crabs. Many people came from all over to pay him visits and talk to him about his life and philosophies, often leaving donations in a frying pan. "Everybody ought to be a hermit for a few minutes to an hour or so every 24 hours, to study, meditate, and commune with their creator ..."- Robert Harrill Robert lived as a hermit for 17 years, until 1972 when his body was found. Fred Pickler, who was in the process of writing a book on Robert, was the one who found his body. Fred stated; ‚ÄúI went in, the first thing I saw, he was laying on his back and his arm was up like that...He was dead. Obviously. He was covered with sand. He had cuts on his arms, on his face, like he'd been drug on the ground.‚Äù Cause of death was labeled "heart attack," however locals believe he was killed by 3 drunk teenagers, who a fisherman allegedly witnessed running from the entrance of the trail that led to Robert's bunker. No autopsy was done. The true cause of his death remains a mystery. Robert is buried at Federal Point Cemetery near Fort Fisher. His headstone says, "He made people think." A Myth on the Origin of Humans Bears have always been an important being in Hyperborean tradition. The divine ancestor and form often taken by many of our gods. Even in American Towns local Bear Cults still exist and gods such as "Mama Bear" exist as forest bear gods in the Upper Peninsula of Michigan for the European Americans. There is a myth that falls into this pattern supposedly from The Shasta Tribe of Northern California, but... well.... you'll see what I mean. It tells of "The Great Spirit" (Which isn't really a thing its a Christianization of Injun Animism) creates golden haired bears who walk on two legs and use clubs. Mount Shasta is considered the homeland for The gods and animal spirits and a place of eternal summer and reincarnation. After a mighty storm the Red Haired Daughter of the Great Spirit is flung out and taken by a bear to his family, where she is breastfed by the bears and eventually marries his son. The result of their union are the first humans with beautiful reddish skin (Not Copper, reddish) The Great Spirit is furious and curses the bears to be unable to talk, use tools and forced to walk on all fours. Taking his daughter back into Mt. Shasta. See what I Mean.... this is odd and doesn't sound like it belongs to the Redman Turkey Feather Indians, but it certainly isn't a pure Hyperborean Tale.

Mexican-style spurs made by August Buermann in Newark, New Jersey in 1900 - 1910. These have dangling jingle bobs or pajados attached. When a horse hears the sound of your bobs, it knows you have spurs on so will behave better. Today jingle bobs are a mostly a fashion statement but in the golden era of the cowboy they were seen as a badge of honor because jingle bobs were earned and worn only by the better horseman. The ranch boss awarded jingle bobs to the cowboys he felt deserved recognition for their horsemanship. Also the sound is widely recognized in movies and signaled that a man of skill was making an entrance.

(Continued From) ...mit or Forest God. The Animals became his friends he traveled with a Wolf who he'd helped out of a trap who ran with him through the moonlit trees. At some point the spirits of the Forest came to him and he became betrothed to some of their maidens, though he refused them in life they could have him in death. Yes there is much much more to Johnny than just his apples. I spect he forgot more than most of us know. In his death he knew his work weren't over and he bent a tree to plant itself and then all the apples across America." "Even in death he dint cease, when he went on to the realms beyond he planted a heavenly orchard that you see up there in the clouds" at that we heard a chirping of a bird as a Cardinal flew into view. "Seems Johnny liked the story boy, those Cardinals are friends of Johnny's they knew him in life and they sing for him in death. Now I'll ask ya again" he bent over that same glint in his eye "what do you know of Johnny Appleseed?" I squirmed slightly as he smirked, he'd gotten the reaction he wanted. He chuckled slightly and motioned for me to stand "Well no use dawdling let's get those apples or your Mother 'll have my hide" I followed after him slightly perturbed, until finally I said "None of that sounds real! It sounds like you made it up on the spot! Johnny is just a fairy tale a weirdo from olden days who planted trees whats the big deal!" My Grandfather turned to me an apple in hand he knelt down so we were eye to eye and held out the apple to me "Here, take a bite" he said. My anger fled me and I did as he asked. As I bit into the crisp apple the Cardinal flew to me and landed on my hand, looking right up at me its eyes glimmered with a sort of kindness I'd only seen in men like my Grandfather, patient and well lived. The Bird tilted its head side to side and flew away with a chirp. My Grandfather stood up "Well let's keep going, the apples ain't gonna pick themselves." I followed after still not sure why, but I felt something... something fuller as I watched the Cardinals frolic apple tree to apple tree and the sun began to fall. "I'm going to pick them" I said running after him. He shifted his eyes to look at me, and smiled. Happy Johnny Appleseed Day from Hyperborean Radio (Uncensored)

The Saga of Johnny Appleseed It was a Windy September day and as I walked through the Orchard with Grandfather he whistled a little tune. I recognized it and asked mockingly "Oooh is that from Johnny Appleseed?" That had been a mistake the stern White Bearded face of my Grandfather turned to stare at me with that mischievous glint in his eye common among Grandfathers. "Oh and What do you Know of Ol' Johnny Appleseed?" he motied for us to sit beneath an Apple Tree and fell to spinning a Yarn as he was oft to do. The Wind caused the swaying of both branches and beard granting the whole story a more dramatic tone. "Johnny weren't this scrawny pencil necked little twerp you see in the movies. He were a beast of a man, strong as an ox, a bronzed hide, his beard and hair grew long and wild and neath his hat were piercing eyes. He carried a tome of sacred knowledge, his sack was full of forest medicine. He ran with wolves, fought serpents and Indians. He was even betrothed to Forest Maidens, old spirits of the wood." He stroked his beard as if in thought than resumed . "Though perhaps I'm getting ahead of myself, let's start at the beginning shall we" He straightened his back and pointed to the sky, fluffy white clouds rose from the hills and spread across the horizon "See that" he asked looking at me, I nodded. "Without Johnny, wouldn't have that Apple Blossom Sky there" he chuckled softly "born at the birth of our Nation he was, grew up crowded on all sides. He'd move this way or that" he mimed Young Johnny's movements "and run into his brother or sister. So when the Pioneers flowed west he naturally followed suit quickly getting ahead of them into a land of Mountain Men, River Rats and Forest Warfare. Such was Johnny that he walked barefoot his feet quickly cobbling his own boots of flesh, he could walk through both fire and ice on those feet of his. Even red hot pokers could not pierce the soles of his feet. He had nothing but the clothes nature grew for him or the tattered remains of Christian Charity while in the wilderness. He'd meet and make friends with many Varmints, some say he even met Paul and Babe. Using his knowledge of Forest Medicine to aid a sickly Babe. He planted his Orchards seed by seed all across the frontier, doing battle with Indians, Snakes and British Soldiers. The Forest was older then, full of spirits and magic. Though even here in the Orchards you can feel something else" he turned away and looked around and a chill ran down my spine. "The Indians came to view him as a Holy Man a Heathen Her.. (Continued)

The Planting of the Apple-Tree by William Cullen Bryant Come, let us plant the apple-tree. Cleave the tough greensward with the spade; Wide let its hollow bed be made; There gently lay the roots, and there Sift the dark mould with kindly care, And press it o'er them tenderly, As, round the sleeping infant's feet, We softly fold the cradle sheet; So plant we the apple-tree. What plant we in this apple-tree? Buds, which the breath of summer days Shall lengthen into leafy sprays; Boughs where the thrush, with crimson breast, Shall haunt and sing and hide her nest; We plant, upon the sunny lea, A shadow for the noontide hour, A shelter from the summer shower, When we plant the apple-tree. What plant we in this apple-tree? Sweets for a hundred flowery springs To load the May-wind's restless wings, When, from the orchard row, he pours Its fragrance through our open doors; A world of blossoms for the bee, Flowers for the sick girl's silent room, For the glad infant sprigs of bloom, We plant with the apple-tree. What plant we in this apple-tree! Fruits that shall swell in sunny June, And redden in the August noon, And drop, when gentle airs come by, That fan the blue September sky, While children come, with cries of glee, And seek them where the fragrant grass Betrays their bed to those who pass, At the foot of the apple-tree. And when, above this apple-tree, The winter stars are quivering bright, And winds go howling through the night, Girls, whose young eyes o'erflow with mirth, Shall peel its fruit by cottage-hearth, And guests in prouder homes shall see, Heaped with the grape of Cintra's vine And golden orange of the line, The fruit of the apple-tree. The fruitage of this apple-tree Winds and our flag of stripe and star Shall bear to coasts that lie afar, Where men shall wonder at the view, And ask in what fair groves they grew; And sojourners beyond the sea Shall think of childhood's careless day And long, long hours of summer play, In the shade of the apple-tree. Each year shall give this apple-tree A broader flush of roseate bloom, A deeper maze of verdurous gloom, And loosen, when the frost-clouds lower, The crisp brown leaves in thicker shower; The years shall come and pass, but we Shall hear no longer, where we lie, The summer's songs, the autumn's sigh, In the boughs of the apple-tree. And time shall waste this apple-tree. Oh, when its aged branches throw Thin shadows on the ground below, Shall fraud and force and iron will Oppress the weak and helpless still? What shall the tasks of mercy be, Amid the toils, the strifes, the tears Of those who live when length of years Is wasting this little apple-tree? "Who planted this old apple-tree?" The children of that distant day Thus to some aged man shall say; And, gazing on its mossy stem, The gray-haired man shall answer them: "A poet of the land was he, Born in the rude but good old times; 'T is said he made some quaint old rhymes On planting the apple-tree."

The Gods on The Bronze Doors In the Library of Congress there is no shortage of mythical imagery. From personifications of virtues and humanities to references to World Myths from Europe to Biblical and Beyond. One of the most interesting of these examples is that of The Bronze Doors on the John Adams Building, a pair of sculpted doors feature a total of 12 gods (and heroes), four of which are European all of which are cast in an Art Deco Style. The Four European Figures are: Ogma (Celtic God Who Gifted the Ogham Alphabet) Odin (The Eddic God who received the Runes, though breaking from the pattern it should've been Heimdall who was pictured as he actually gave the Runes to Man or Bragi as god of poets, but its an understandable oversight) Cadmus (Greek Hero Who introduced the Phoenician Alphabet supposedly) Hermes (Hellenic God who invented the modern Greek Alphabet) The Other Eight Figures are Thoth, Ts‚Äôang Chieh, Nabu, Tahmurath, Itzamna, Sequoyah, Quetzalcoatl and Brahma. All of the 12 figures are thought to have something to do with the invention or use of written languages.

The Apotheosis of Washington by Constantino Brumidi 1863 Painted in the Rotunda Dome of the United State Capitol Building, the Apotheosis of Washington is one of the most beautiful murals in the District of Columbia. It depicts Washington ascending to godhood flanked by Libertas and Victoria (Roman goddesses of Liberty and Victory, while enveloped by the 13 colonies. Around the edge are six (or more) gods including the Goddess of America Columbia (War) in her role as war goddess. There are also five other Roman gods each representing a different element of American culture and excellence including: Minerva (Science) alongside famous American Inventors Morse, Franklin and Fulton. Neptune (Marine) depicted with American warships and the goddess Venus laying the transatlantic telegraph cable. Mercury (Commerce) depicted giving gold to American Revolutionary Financier Robert Morris. Vulcan (Mechanics) depicted with a steam engine and cannon balls. Ceres (Agriculture) depicted with a McCormick mechanical reaper, a personified Young America holding the reins, while the goddess Flora collects flowers. With this and many other depictions much like Romulus founder of Rome, our own Romulus ascended to godhood long ago. It's a shame few realize it (Except oddly the Hawaiian Shinto temple... go figure)

Enthroned Washington by Horatio Greenough 1840 This statue was created in honor of the Centennial of Washington's Birth and is based off the famous statue of Zeus by Phidias. One of the Seven wonders of the ancient world. His right hand points to the heavens and his left holds a sheathed sword meant to symbolize his giving of power to the people after the Revolutionary War.

The Apotheosis of Washington by Samuel Moore In this version of the Famous Subject matter, Washington ascends "To heaven" or "The land of the gods" accompanied by the Seven Virtues. Below Him Columbia, the Goddess of America looks up to him the man who made the country of which she presides. In front of her the sixteen states personified mourn their "Father" as collective orphans.

The Apotheosis of Washington by John James Barralet Washington Ascends from his tomb with two figures personifying Genius and Immortality. Faith, Hope, and Charity Look on while America is personified as Lady Liberty with her staff and Liberty Cap and as an Amerindian Man mourning and standing guard over his tomb
The Apotheosis of Washington by David Edwin David Edwin's Apotheosis engraving implies a religious transformation as Washington ascends from his earthly home to be welcomed by heroes on high.

The Origin of Paul Bunyan's Ax One of the most iconic tools of any being or hero of folklore is the ax of Paul Bunyan. Now there are many tales told of how Paul came by his signature ax, the most common is that he made it himself pulling a whole towering pine tree up out of the ground to form the handle, yet perhaps my favorite has much more of that mythic nature to it that exists in many American myths but is so often buried by what sells at roadside attractions or Kids films. That he was given it by the spirits of the earth. Now see just like the Ax Paul himself has many origins from flocks of storks, to arriving washed up by the sea to being born of old trees and becoming a sort of forest god, but this one seems to follow the vein of Paul's origins that has him akin to Joe Magarac in that he was born of the mountains themselves. Molten ore flows through Paul's veins as much as steel forms the flesh of Joe. Born of the Earth it stands to reason he would pal around with spirits of the earth. Sometimes its dwarves, others gnomes, and some others are more generic in their earth spirits. But this story holds that Paul received his Ax as a gift from the Spirits of the Earth (Dwarves) and it was because he chose to leave his mountain home and go amongst man to show them how to live with nature. This was Paul's noble goal and his gift to his camp followers. It also shows why when people put profits before nature he fled North away from those who broke his heart. Either way Paul's Ax is an iconic image and is even a Trophy between two rival football teams.

To mimic the fierce mane of the Hyperborean they must impose a shaving ban as they require decades to reach what we can grow in less than a year. They have disguised these traits of our race as theirs by selectively presenting those who more fit the desired stereotype while convincing our males they are full grown by 18 while all historical customs of the Old Ways point to late 20's to early 30's for true physical maturity for the Male Hyperborean. Confederados After the American Civil War not all Confederates stayed in the United States. Many ended up fleeing to Latin American countries such as Mexico, Belize and especially Brazil. These expats were often enticed with offers of cheap land by countries hoping to gain their expertise in various fields such as Cotton Farming. Nowadays there are around 250K descendants of these Confederate Expats. In Southern Brazil the land is not too dissimilar to their homeland of Dixie and it was there they founded the City of Americana. To this day various celebrations and continuations of their Southern American cultural heritage are proudly practiced. With their traditional dress being that of the South before and during the Civil War. These "Confederados" as they are called are not only fascinating as a sort of continued parallel time capsule of what was but also an interesting example of Americans as a distinct group. When all the Groups of Americans are often told we have no culture for an entire group of Expats to have such a clear cultural heritage from this country and be proud of it is a sight to behold.

My first exposure to "The Oregon Trail" . . . But in all seriousness looking forward to this series. Go check out American Folklore Preservation if you haven't already. üá∫üá∏ü¶Öü¶ùüèà

Crossing 2,170 miles of land connecting the Missouri River to the Oregon valleys, the Oregon Trail was laid down by trappers and fur traders around 1811, and until 1836, the it was only possible to travel the route by foot or on horseback. It was in that year, that a wagon trail was cleared to Fort Hall, Idaho from Independence, Missouri, and the first migrant wagon train, destined for Oregon, was organized. Around 400,000 settlers made the arduous journey in the pursuit of abundant farmlands, a fresh start, a manifestation of destiny West of the Rockies. While in modern times, many of us would make such a trip with little difficulty, that was far from the case for our forebears. The number of deaths is a subject of speculation, as those who died were often buried in unmarked graves that were made to blend in with the landscape as to not be disturbed by animals or native tribes. Most does of disease, with cholera killing up to 3% of travelers from 1849 to 1855. Encounters with Indians also played a major role in the deaths of the pioneers. These attacks became such a problem that more routes had to be made to avoid savage territory. Other deaths came as a result of hypothermia, drowning while crossing rivers, wagon fatalities, snake bites, homicides, stampedes, flash floods, and even lightening strikes. Completion of the first transcontinental railroad in 1869, resulted in the decline of the trail's use. The train was cheaper, safer, and people lost their sense of adventure (I'm half joking). The Oregon Trail helped to expand our country. Many fascinating tales were born from the experience of those who braved this path, and I have decided to make a short series to keep their struggles, horrors, and triumphs from fading anymore than they all ready have. Stay tuned!

It commemorates the adoption of the flag of the United States on June 14, 1777, by resolution of the Second Continental Congress.[1] The Flag Resolution, passed on June 14, 1777, stated: "Resolved, That the flag of the thirteen United States be thirteen stripes, alternate red and white; that the union be thirteen stars, white in a blue field, representing a new constellation."

Pets Help Us Be More Human How many of us have had a pet? For many of us these animals are a close family member, some even hold the opinion we are only still alive thanks to a pet. Whether as an emotional comfort or the animal literally saved our life. This is nothing new, thousands of years ago animals like domestic foxes and dogs were buried with messages of deep love for the animal: "I am in tears, while carrying you to your last resting place as much as I rejoiced when bringing you home in my own hands fifteen years ago" -Ancient Greek Writing on a Dogs Grave While many will claim animals "Only do it for the food" reality does not lend itself to this belief. Dogs have willingly given up their lives to defend their human friends even starving themselves to death to protect the humans corpse, cities report packs of dogs traveling on the bus to richer parts of town begging for food and bringing it back to their humans who are homeless. Affection goes both ways, individuals from certain groups such as PETA have viciously torn dogs from their humans who proclaim "Anything else please! Kill Me! Anything but don't take my DOG!" the dog will often escape but it is too late their human has passing on of a broken heart. This is not unique to dogs, horses have carried their unconscious riders off battlefields even dragging them with their teeth. Magpies, crows and many other birds will visit and protect their humans. Animals have long been companions of our people bears have been best men at weddings, opossums and raccoons have shown up to share a beer with people, whether rich or poor it is the true connection of the heart between two living things. Mutual friendship and understanding. Pets teach us to be truly human, to experience a connection with another living being without the cumbersome burden of social norms. Pin Ups and Bombshells While nowadays understandably the concept of a "Pin-Up Girl" is often thought of as Lurid, the Pin-Up and Bombshells of WW2 were an integral part of the morale of the men. Many of which were surrounded exclusively by their wartime brothers, the Pin-ups reminded them of home, many were of famous women, painted by famous artists, or women who volunteered to be depicted as such for the purposes of art and morale. The Pin-Up was so popular it was used in recruitment posters and Men even painted "Nose Art" of Pin-ups on their fighter planes reminding them of home and personalizing their own planes. These two mediums of Nose Art and Pin-Ups fed into each other, and the association gave birth to the term "Bombshell" for beautiful woman. Reminding the men that back home were "Women worth fighting for".

Did you know that the east coast and Appalachia contain distinct ethnic populations of the Irish, Scottish, and Scots-Irish? If you were born and raised in this area then chances are that your admixture is Celtic and Germanic. As a result, these regions are hotbeds for cultural celebration and enrichment! I spent the morning compiling a list of some of the most popular events and also a few directory links to help fill in the gaps. I included a few because the directories overlap with each other. Many from my list are included in one or more of the directories, but several are not. This list includes the states that I am familiar with but if you are in NY, NC, SC, TN, or KT, you have a ton of these Celtic celebrations around you. I really encourage you to do some research because I guarantee that there are plenty not in these directories that you can find with an intensive Google session. I‚Äôve been to a good handful of the ones on this list and they are amazing experiences every time. These events are some of the best ways to connect with your roots and teach your children about their heritage. There are also loads of networking opportunities with different vendors, artisans, and historic/genealogical societies. I promise that your heart will swell when you experience this tiny taste of who you are, it‚Äôs like your blood remembers the sounds and tastes of your ancestral home. You will absolutely experience ethnic homogeneity and racial pride so please check them out! cleaned_message: The Old Reuse of Items Did you know? That Flour Companies used to print their bags in patterns and special colors so the easily deconstructed bags could then be used for sewing? A rare gesture these days though it was likely a marketing move as upcycling the fabric would be a valuable way to both stretch money and income during the Great Depression and WW2 when times were lean. Nowadays I don't think our sacks of flour would be very useful for clothing. Something most items no longer have is the ability to be upcycled, however whether marketing or simply being kind in a time when kindness was at a premium due to scarcity the flour bags would often be printed in patterns and some would even include doll cloth patterns to cut out. With the talents of the Wives of the time allowing for the upcycled items to actually be better than much of what's available nowadays. With many people having long lasting "Flour Sack Dresses" as family heirlooms. Might be a good idea to start thinking of the Upcycling or Reuse of products with the way the world is going.

Folklore of Wisconsin: Hodag The Hodag was a ferocious and terrible creature that allegedly terrorized the town of Rhinelander, Wisconsin during the 1800s. It was believed this monstrosity was born from the ashes of a cremated ox, and was the personification of the cruelty that all oxen had endured through the centuries. The creature made regular appearances in the early tales of Paul Bunyan. In 1893, newspapers printed articles telling of alleged sightings of the Hodag. These articles described the beast as having "the head of a frog, the grinning face of a giant elephant, thick short legs set off by huge claws, the back of a dinosaur, and a long tail with spears at the end." The Hodag has since become Rhinelander's mascot, and giant fiberglass sculpture of the creature, stands outside of the Rhinelander Area Chamber of Commerce.

cleaned_message: Moll (Mary Diamond) Pitcher Stories tell of a woman by the name of Moll Pitcher, who lived during the 1700s, in Massachusetts Though no birth records exist for a woman by that name during this period, it is speculated that she was born in the year, 1738. There ARE records of a man named Aholiab Diamond, believed to be Moll's father, living in Lynn. Aholiab built a home and farm on "140 square rods of land." We don't know for sure when Moll Diamond was born, or where. What we DO know, is that after Aholiab Diamond and his wife died, their sons inherited their property. After the brothers died, their sister Mary (Moll) Diamond, was the only remaining heir. Somewhere along the way, she married, and her surname became Pitcher. Sometime after marrying, she gained a reputation as the town fortune teller. She thrived in her profession, making "successful predictions," for the poor and rich, alike. Many women sought her out, to learn who they were destined to marry, while others went to reveal the fidelity of their spouses. Treasure hunters came to her for guidance of the location of their desire, but she would often turn them away, stating that if she knew such a location, she would keep that information for herself. It seems that this wasn't so much because she was a greedy woman, but rather, had a very keen judgement of people. She had little patience for those who only wished to make themselves richer. Moll's main method of divination, was reading tea leaves. She frequently read for noblemen, with whom placed the utmost confidence in her prophecies. The table in which she conducted her talents remains in her home, which is now a historical landmark. Moll Pitcher died in 1813, at the age of 75. She was buried on an old burial ground, located on the western side of Lynn.

Guardians of Traffic by Henry Hering and Frank Walker 1930's The Guardians of Traffic in Cleveland Ohio are massive outdoor Art Deco Sculptures designed by Frank Walker and carved by Henry Hering and a large team of artists. All of the massive over 40 foot figures are crowned in either Laurel Wreathes of Winged Helmets. They also hold a different means of transportation meant to indicate the progression of transport. These include a Hay Wagon, Covered Wagon, Stagecoach, 1930's Automobile, and several construction vehicles. Half of them face east and the other half face west and all of them are a part of Hope Memorial Bridge in Cleveland, Ohio.

Molly Pitcher There are many heroines of American History and Folklore. While the likes of Amelia Earhart, Betsy Ross and Annie Oakley dominate the popular consciousness there are still many others that entered into legend. Such was the tragic tale of Molly Pitcher who fought in the American Revolution. There are many women who have been thought to be Molly: Mary L. Hays McCauley, Margaret Corbin, etc. While she is likely a composite figure this is largely irrelevant for folklore. The general story is that Molly Pitcher would take buckets of water out to the battlefield earning her nickname of "Pitcher"until her husband was killed in battle and she threw down her pitcher and took his spot at the cannon for the duration of the battle. At some point her legs were shot off by an enemy cannon sending her petticoat flying. Though for her heroics she gained other epithets including "Captain Molly" as well as "Sgt. Molly" which was said to be given to her by Washington himself. Issuing a warrant as a noncommissioned officer in honor of her heroics.

Helvetia Is this Switzerland? Well... Yes and No. This is Helvetia, West Virginia. Settled in 1869 by Swiss Immigrants mostly artisans. Helvetia is a little taste of Alpine culture in Appalachia. The area like most had their German heritage downplayed in WW2 but has persevered regardless. Named after the Helvetii Celtic Tribes that settled in the Swiss Alps the area continues the culinary, linguistic, and artistic traditions of Switzerland. Especially notable is their celebration of Fasnacht (Swiss Carnival) which is combined with another Swiss Pagan rite of Spring Sechsel√§uten which burns the B√∂√∂gg an effigy of Winter. In Helvetia the B√∂√∂gg has been replaced with Old Man Winter but Green Men, Animal and Plant Spirits as well as ghosts and various traditional costumes such as Mountaineers predominate. Other elements of Appalachian Culture have bled into Helvetia including Appalachian folk music and Square Dancing. When Old Man Winter is burnt one is likely to hear Country Roads Take Me Home rather than a traditional Swiss song. The culture may be rich and the Cell Service may be nonexistent but Helvetia's population has sadly fallen to 59 and like many similar towns that preserved and perpetuated traditions in the USA such as the Amana Colonies in Iowa the town is dying. We need to do what we can to preserve these towns and their cultures.

Meshach Browning 1781-1859 Backwoodsman, hunter, and explorer. He is considered Maryland's most famous hunter of the frontier. Browning's father had been an English soldier, but turned deserter, when he fled the Braddock Massacre in 1755. Meshach was raised in a secluded community, in the highlands of western Maryland. This community was fairly self- sufficient, wearing skins from the animals they hunted themselves. The women spun their own flax and wool. It seems the only thing this community relied on from outsiders, was gunpowder. Browning grew to be an expert on wild animal behavior. He was a professional gamekeeper, and has gone down in Allegheny Mountain history, as a legend in his tracking capabilities of white tailed deer, black bear, panthers, and wolves. Browning recounted his adventures of his "expeditions and life-threatening encounters," in his book: "Forty-four Years of the Life of a Hunter." The book was revised and illustrated in 1859 by E. Stabler. The man thought very highly of himself, but his mastery of surviving frontier life, has given him notable folk-figure status, possibly a folk-hero to some. A Historical Marker in Maryland claims that Browning"killed 2,000 dear and 500 bear, in 40 years." He died in Pennsylvania on November 19, 1859. He was 78 years old.

Meant to include this in the Snallygaster story. These are the hexsigns that were placed on the barns, to keep the creature away

The Snallygaster Something was terrorizing the early German settlers in Frederick County, Maryland. The settlers called it, schneller geist, which translates to "quick ghost." This creature was said to be a reptilian bird-like behemoth, with enormous wings, a single eye in the center of its ghoulish face, and a metallic beak, with jagged sharp teeth. Over time, the name changed to "Snallygaster." The Snallygaster was reported to swoop down from the sky, and snatch up people and livestock, carrying them away forever. The settlers painted seven-pointed stars on their barns, in the hopes to keep the beast away. These can still be seen today. I Suppose it worked, as stories abruptly stopped until the early 1900s, when sightings of abnormally large birds were reported throughout the state. The stories caused such a stir that the Smithsonian Institute offered a reward, to anyone could bring them the creature (dead, I'm assuming). There was a rumor that at one point, President Theodore Roosevelt, actually put off an African Safari to hunt down the Snallygaster, himself. No such creature has ever been captured, but some believe that Snallygaster dwells somewhere within South Mountain (an extension of the Appalachias, between Maryland and Pennsylvania.)

url_description: Few people today recognize the name Joseph Christian Leyendecker and yet he was arguably this nation‚Äôs most popular commercial artist during the first four decades of the 20th century. His paintings helped sell everything from men‚Äôs clothing to breakfast cereal and he helped define the modern magazine cover. Haggin Museum houses the largest public collection of original art works by the ‚ÄúGolden Age‚Äù illustrator, Joseph Christian Leyendecker. The Leyendecker Gallery displays more than 40 pieces of original works including sketches, studies, and finished paintings. In addition, a collection of photographs, letters and other personal items provide a rare, intimate look into his life. To learn more about J.C. Leyendecker and the Haggin Museum, visit hagginmuseum.org. This project is supported in part by the National Endowment for the Arts. Raccoons are one of the most cunnin' of animals in all of North America. Able to open house doors, steal what they want and leave closing the door on their way out as if they were never there. Their young are incredibly curious even though the chubby adults can go a bit murder hobo on people. They are able to handle objects much like people such as riding bikes or using a knife to cut strawberries. They were once a common game meat and are still eaten in many parts of the USA. Their fur is rather important and has been used as currency among European settlers in the past. Their appearance, cleverness and curious nature has resulted in them almost always being a Trickster or Thief in folklore or Pop Culture. Such as Rocket Raccoon, Sly Cooper and Rascal. Raccoons are social animals living in colonies or villages within forests and nesting in trees with their young.

With the help of Virginia Lieutenant Governor, Alexander Spotswood, she gained her land back. There, she lived out the rest of her life, seemingly undisturbed. Legend says, on the day Grace died, her sons placed her corpse by the fireplace, and a gust of wind came through the house and carried her away up the chimney. A cloven hoofprint was said to appear in the spot where her body previously lay. After her death in 1740, stories were told of how the devil claimed her body. Supernatural storms were said to brew up over the bay in which she had been ducked, and strange black cats were seen hanging around Grace's property. The cats seemed to provoke fear the most, for the locals started killing every cat they came across. This is what likely led to a major rat infestation in 1793. Grace's home once stood at Muddy Creek, but over recent years, vandals attempted to burn it down so many times that eventually, nothing remained but the chimney, which was bulldozed in 2002. The land is now owned by the federal government and is part of the Back Bay National Wildlife Refuge. Grace Sherwood was the last person to be formally accused of witchcraft, in the State of Virginia. In 2007, a statue was erected of Sherwood. She was depicted carrying a basket of rosemary to signify her knowledge of herbal medicine, and a raccoon at her feet, symbolizing her love of animals. Some say that all of the rosemary that grows in Virginia, is the result of a sprig of the plant that Grace carried with her from England to the colony, in an eggshell. The bay in which her trial by ducking took place, was renamed: Witch Duck Bay. Locals of the present day claim that every July, a ghostly light, can be seen, floating over Witch Duck Bay. This mysterious light is believed to be the restless spirit of Grace Sherwood. *I claim no rights to these or any photos I use with my stories, unless otherwise specified. I try to include the photographers and artists when their names are accessible to me*

The Witch of Pungo Grace White was 20 years old, in 1680, when she married James Sherwood, a poor farmer in the Colony of Virginia, town of Pungo. The couple had 3 sons. James died in 1701, leaving Grace, all 145 acres of his land. Grace used her knowledge of herbs and childbirth to make ends meet as a healer and midwife. Grace was said to be very beautiful, and her beauty only seemed to flourish as she aged. Some of the married local men fawned over her, which understandably, upset many of their wives, though it is said, Grace never showed interest in these men. So, with the stirring frustration of the men which manifested from constant rejection, and the hysterics a married woman may experience, knowing her husband lusted after other women, Grace became extraordinarily unpopular. The first accusations of witchcraft against Grace Sherwood, took place in 1697, when a neighboring farmer made the claim that Grace had cast a spell on his bull, causing it to waste away. The very next year, another farmer accused her of enchanting his pig and cotton crop. That same year, a woman claimed that Grace transformed herself into a giant black cat, entered the woman's home, and slashed her across the face before escaping through the keyhole. The courts in colonial Virginia, took no actions with these three cases, as the witch hysteria was never as severe here, as it was in say...Salem, Massachusetts. Even though nothing came of these incidents in a legal sense, Grace and her husband still had to pay court costs. In 1705, a few years after James Sherwood passed away, Elizabeth Hill, whose husband owned a farm down the road from Grace, accused Sherwood of bewitching her, and causing her to suffer a miscarriage, after the two women had gotten into a physical altercation. This time, Grace refused to appear in court. She was arrested. 2 juries were present, both entirely made up of women. Over half of these women feeling personally victimized by Grace Sherwood. Things weren't looking well for the accused. During this time, Virginia courts often dismissed claims of witchcraft, preferring not to stir up social unrest, but if enough people believed someone to be a witch, a trial would be held, however, the jury would have to provide proof in order to prosecute. (At this time, Virginia did not involve the clergy in judging legal matters, as Salem had.) 2 of the most common methods used in the identifying of a witch were used in Grace's trial: The women in the jury inspected Grace's body for "witch marks." These types of marks were usually just moles or birthmarks, but it was an easy way to "prove" one was in league with the devil, for it was believed these marks were given to witches when they made a pact with the devil. Four of these marks were found on the flesh of the Grace Sherwood. Though they were fairly certain that they had their proof by now, they decided to try one more test. The method of "ducking" a witch was one of the most widely practiced, during the witch hysterias of both Europe and the Colonies. This process involved submerging the accused in a body of water. Usually a weight of some kind would be attached to her feet. If she survived, she was guilty of witchcraft. If she drowned, she was innocent. Either way, in most cases, death would be her fate. And one early morning, Grace was rowed out onto the bay. She looked back at the crowd, a fiery hatred in her eyes. "Before this day be through," she said to them, "you will all get a worse ducking than I!" A 13 pound Bible was tied around her neck, before she was dropped into the water. Grace was underwater for no more than 30 seconds before she managed to untie herself and reach the surface. After this, Grace was thrown in jail to await sentencing, but not much is known of what happened to her between 1705 and 1714. Many court documents were lost in that time frame. Records state that Grace Sherwood was released in 1714.

The Star-Spangled Banner John Stafford Smith O say can you see, by the dawn's early light, What so proudly we hailed at the twilight's last gleaming, Whose broad stripes and bright stars through the perilous fight, O'er the ramparts we watched, were so gallantly streaming? And the rocket's red glare, the bombs bursting in air, Gave proof through the night that our flag was still there; O say does that star-spangled banner yet wave O'er the land of the free and the home of the brave? On the shore dimly seen through the mists of the deep, Where the foe's haughty host in dread silence reposes, What is that which the breeze, o'er the towering steep, As it fitfully blows, half conceals, half discloses? Now it catches the gleam of the morning's first beam, In full glory reflected now shines in the stream: 'Tis the star-spangled banner, O long may it wave O'er the land of the free and the home of the brave. And where is that band who so vauntingly swore That the havoc of war and the battle's confusion, A home and a country, should leave us no more? Their blood has washed out their foul footsteps' pollution. No refuge could save the hireling and slave From the terror of flight, or the gloom of the grave: And the star-spangled banner in triumph doth wave, O'er the land of the free and the home of the brave. O thus be it ever, when freemen shall stand Between their loved homes and the war's desolation. Blest with vict'ry and peace, may the Heav'n rescued land Praise the Power that hath made and preserved us a nation! Then conquer we must, when our cause it is just, And this be our motto: 'In God is our trust.' And the star-spangled banner in triumph shall wave O'er the land of the free and the home of the brave! The Official Anthem of the United States the Star-Spangled Banner is based on a poem describing the defense of America by a Siege performed by the British in the War of 1812. The poem was written by Francis Scott Key and was one of the most recognizable songs in the United States it was actually written in 1814 after Key witnessed the battle/siege and saw that by the end "Our Flag was Still There" or that despite the battle and bombardment the American Flag Still Stood. The original poem was called "Defence of Fort McHenry".

On this day‚Ä¶ On June 10, 1752, Benjamin Franklin was reported to have flown a kite in a thunderstorm hoping to capture an ambient electrical charge in a Leyden jar. Success would allow him to demonstrate the connection between lightning and electricity. He created a number of terms still used today, such as: battery, conductor and electrician. He also invented the lightning rod, used to protect buildings and ships from lightning strikes.

Paul's father stated his son had lately taken to standing at the edge of the tree line and staring into the dark forest, a few days prior to his disappearance. Paul was never found. 1943: Carl Herrick went hunting with his cousin, Henry. About 2 hours into the hunt, the men were somehow separated. Henry went back to their camp, as the two of them had agreed to do so should one of them become lost. When several hours passed and Carl had not returned, Henry went to the authorities. A three day search ensued. As the sun was setting on the third day, Carl's body was found. He was naked except for his socks and boots. His rifle was found 70ft away, loaded, and propped up against a tree. A chewing tobacco canister containing methamphetamine was found near Carl's body. Even more perplexing, the autopsy revealed that Carl had been squeezed to death. His lungs punctured by his rib cage. Three hunters all disappeared in that very same area, in 1981. Unlike Carl, they were never found. What is interesting about all these cases, as expressed by investigator and writer David Paulides (who has several books based on mysterious missing person cases within America's national parks), are the similarities they share: All happened between October and January. Many were last seen between 3-4pm. There have been an equally divided number of women and men who go missing in this area. There are many theories as to what is happening in the Bennington Triangle. Everything from bigfoot to faeries to inter-dimensional doorways have been suggested ....and the government totally knows...read David Paulides books for more info on that.

Folklore of Vermont: The Bennington Triangle The area surrounding Glastenbury Mountain is considered one of the most haunted and mysterious places in the state of Vermont. The land was dubbed "The Bennington Triangle" by folklorist, Joseph Citro, in 1992. Fearing the land to be cursed, Native tribes refused to set foot anywhere near Glastenbury Mountain. Colonial settlers had their own experiences in the area, which included strange smells and sounds Whatever energy that dwells there, it is said to have a disastrous impaction the human psyche. In 1867, there were reports of a feral man living in a cave on the mountain. His stories are quite benign compared to others, as his only objective seemed to be intimidation with a pistol and sometimes exposing himself to women. In 1892, a millworker named Henry McDowell, killed a co-worker by bashing in the man's head with a rock. Henry blamed the incident on the voices he heard in his head. He was tried and committed to an insane asylum. He escaped the asylum, and was never seen again, but some said he went back to Glastenbury Mountain, living out the rest of his life, hiding out in the slopes. Some say his ghost still dwells there. In the early 19th century, a stagecoach carrying several people, was passing through the mountains near Glastenbury. A terrible storm was wreaking havoc, flooding the road. They had no choice but to stop. As the passengers huddled together for warmth, something spooked the horses, which threw the animals into a frenzy. The passengers could not make anything out in the darkness, but suddenly, a great force came down on the stagecoach. Whatever was out there had to have been enormous, for it shook the coach back and forth until it fell on its side. One passenger claimed he could, infact, make out the image of a large, hairy beast with glowing eyes. He estimated it to be 8ft tall. The press got wind of the story, and named this creature, The Bennington Monster. In more recent years, the Bennington Triangle holds some of Vermont's most disturbing cases of missing people. 1945: a 74 year old local man named Middie Rivers, a hunting guide, led a group of 5 men up Glastenbury Mountain. It was an ordinary day. But on their hike back to camp, Rivers, being very well acquainted with the land, went a little further ahead of the others. The other hunters figured they would find him back at camp, but when they arrived, they grew weary when they did not find him there. The next day, when there was still no sign of Middie, a search party was called. The search lasted for a little over a month, and no trace of the man was ever found. 1946: On the first of December, one of the most well known cases of those disappearing in the Bennington Triangle unfolded. 18 year old, Paula Welden went for a walk in those woods that lined her school's (Bennington College) campus. Multiple people saw her on the walking trail and even recalled that she wore a bright red sweater. When Paula didn't show up to her classes for a day or two, the sheriff's department was called. Surely Paula and her bright red sweater would be found sooner or later. 400 volunteers, including students and faculty helped search for the girl. The search expanded when the news spread. Soon the search party consisted of 1,000 people, 20-some bloodhounds, helicopters, even a psychic was brought in. The search went on for nearly 3 weeks, but a few days before Christmas, many people lost hope. Paula was never found. The case of Paula Welden inspired a superstition that one should never go into the woods wearing red. Columbus Day, 1950: 8 year old Paul Jepson had been playing outside at his family's junkyard. When his mother came to check on him, it was as if he had completely vanished. The junkyard was located within Bennington Triangle territory. Paul had been wearing a red jacket when he disappeared. Hundreds of people searched for the boy. It is said that the bloodhounds lost Paul's scent right around the area that Paula Welden was last seen, 4 years before.

Bighorn Sheep Bighorn Sheep are a popular animal of the American West. While they are called "sheep" they are much bigger than most domestic sheep being nearly 6 feet tall, combined with their honeycomb style horns that absorb impact during their mating duels and their sharp hooves designed for walking on the edge of cliffs they are no slouch. They are prized as hunting trophies and have rivers, mountain ranges, and canyons all named after them. They are even the official state animal of Nevada and of the Province Alberta.

The Bald Eagle The Bald Eagle is the emblem of the United States, our official animal and the companion of Columbia goddess of America, the emissary of Washington from the realm of heroes. But did you know we almost had a very different animal as our official emblem? Benjamin Franklin actually recommended the Turkey, as he considered (rightly so) the Eagle to be a scavenger and too reminiscent of the Old World. Whereas the at the time nearly 4 feet tall Turkey was a uniquely American bird that populated the forests a tiny velociraptor of the Eastern Woodlands. Regardless the Fishing Bald Eagle became the emblem of the United States from across the North nesting in flocks of occasionally hundreds by rivers. Then of course there is the wonderful "Horny Death Spiral" that Eagles do when they mate. So all in all at least the Bald Eagle looks rather impressive especially in the Old Moss Covered Branches of the Northwoods.

American Bison American Bison also known as the Buffalo is one of the most iconic animals of North America, being the official Mammal of the USA. Much more widespread than the European Bison or Wisent the Bison once roamed the entirety of North America north of the Deserts but was extirpated from the Eastern woodlands. They are typically 1000-3000 pounds and are around 9 Feet tall. In the modern day controlled breeding programs are done to continue increasing the population. There are also many Bison ranches which tend to focus on leaving the animal mostly wild with just enough interaction to keep them healthy and within reach, including several groups who focus on regenerative ranching. Despite common claims that European settlers nearly drove them to extinction. It was actually the Plain's Indians hunting method of leading entire herds over a cliff exacerbated with horses that nearly killed the Buffalo, with it being the US government and conservationists who saved it from the brink of extinction.

Old Man River Besides the Great Lakes the Other Major Water Source is what divides the Country into East and West, The Mighty Mississippi AKA Old Man River himself, in his Ferry pulled by Mules down America's River. Not only is the mighty Mississippi so large that at many parts one cannot see the other side of the River but it is also home to abundant wildlife. Including enormous fish such as the Mighty Alligator Gar with its Armor grade scales, The Snapping Turtle with the bite force to take a mans hand clean off, Catfish the size of boats, as well as many birds like the Fishing Bird the Bald Eagle, or the living Spear known as the Great Blue Heron, many mammals also live and hunt near it such as the Studious Beaver, Powerful Black Bear, Crafty Cougar, and playful River Otter. It has been a major food and water source for much of the USA though in recent years it has undergone massive destruction via invasive species such as Zebra Mussels and Asian Carp as well as the Farm Run Off from the Corn Belt.

Ecoregions of the USA America is rather complex, for one the very nature the environments of North America ties the three major powers of the Continent together. Canada, The United States of America and The United States of Mexico all have a complex history together and our environments blend together. The Great Plains in particular goes from Central Canada, essentially cuts the American Forest in Half between East and West and goes down into North Mexico. Then You have the Rocky Mountains which form the Spine of North America from the Arctic to the Tropics. There are the Great Lakes which are shared by both the USA and Canada, the Great Bear Rainforest which is shared by the two countries as well, The Colorado River goes across the Southwest and into Mexico, and many animals from Pronghorn to Monarch Butterflies migrate across all three countries. Due to the sheer complexity and diversity of these Bioregions America is a rather complex area with in reality a myriad of cultures just among Hyperboreans.
