cleaned_message: The Roots of Modern Animation When animation first began as a form of media and artistic expression it was based mostly off the comic styles of American Newspaper & Political Comics. Your Little Orphan Annie's and Little Nemo's. As most early animators were former comic strip artists. The early Rubber Hose style of American animation was a simplified form of this comic style with the movements being very "rubbery". When Walt Disney wanted to make a feature length film he drew directly from European Fairy Tales with Snow White. With aid from artists like Gustaf Tenggren whose style was inspired by the works of Dulac, Rackham, Nielsen and Bauer. Animated Films were meant to be Fairy Tales Come to life! These beautiful pieces of art would eventually inspire Post-WW2 Japan in a boy named Osamu Tezuka who would combine Disney's Early Fairy Tale Style with traditional Japanese block print styles and create the modern art forms of Manga and Anime. Which now inspires American Animation coming full circle.

When Japan Demanded American Mythology After Commodore Perry forced Japan to open its doors to the wider world and stop its centuries old policy of isolationism Edo Period Japan was hungry for American culture and Mythology, as they were in awe of this powerful country. They received it in the form of some simultaneously fascinating and hilarious depictions of the Founding Fathers including George Washington Punching a Tiger, fighting Asura (A Dharmic God) and being presided over by the goddess of America (Columbia). While Ben Franklin is depicted as a stoic warrior capable of holding and firing a cannon with his bare hands. While John Addams is a super human warrior whose mother is eaten by a snake, Addams than seeks out a Mountain Fairy and with the aid of the Fairy's giant Eagle defeats the giant Snake and avenges his mother. In a strange turn of events many in Japan actually still take these depictions as historic fact. With Washington even a "Kami" at the Hawaiian Shinto Temple.

The Chuck Wagon Quintessentially American, The Chuck Wagon was used on Cattle Drives (mostly in Texas) as a means of keeping up morale with good food and as a means to attract the best of the Cowboys to run the cattle drive. The Chuck Wagon often used easy to preserve items such as Beans, Salted Meats (Especially Beef), Coffee, Onions, Potatoes, Lard and Flour. The Chuck Wagon was often manned by a talented cook who was typically ill tempered due to lack of sleep and long hours. He was second only to the trail boss and had many nicknames including Cookie, Coosie, Sourdough, Puncher, Greasy Belly, Dough Boxer, Old Lady, etc. While the Chuck Wagon fell out of fashion after the 1880's it eventually gave way to both the American Diner and the Modern Food Truck. It's culinary mainstays and adaptable nature of its cooks fed into much of modern American cuisine. It's Name of the "Chuck" wagon can be traced to either a slang word for food or its supposed inventor Charles "Chuck" Goodnight.

Northern Cardinals The Cardinal is one of the most popular birds of North America named after the Cardinals of the Catholic Church due to their red coloration, which also leads to their other less common name of "Redbird". Northern Cardinals are also often used as Yuletide decorations and symbols likely due to their overwintering and red coloration upon white snow. They have a distinct Whistling Song that is hard to mistake for another birds and have beautiful woven nests with speckled eggs. They are the State Bird of: Illinois, Indiana, Kentucky, North Carolina, Ohio, Virginia and West Virginia. They are also the namesake of several sports teams including the St. Louis Cardinals (MLB) and the Arizona Cardinals (NFL) The Cardinal was once prized as a pet bird but it was rendered illegal to keep them as pets in 1918. The Northern Cardinal carries the nickname of America's Favorite Backyard Bird and enjoy Sunflower and Safflower Seeds in bird feeders.

The Impact of The Shadow One of the most important characters in all of Pop Culture is a relatively forgotten but vastly influential figure. The Product of Pulp Novels which alongside elements of Myth and Folklore spawned the Superhero Genre in the early 20th Century. The Shadow was by far the most popular of all the Pulp Characters. A Household name with movies, books, comics, and an incredibly popular radio play staring Orson Welles. The Shadow is the predecessor to Batman, a dark and mysterious master of disguise, combat, and a great detective the Shadow would often find a way to entrap his quarry. In Many ways the Shadow originated the modern idea of the "Supervillain" with The Shadow's enemies serving as the template for such great antagonists as the Joker. His catchphrase "Who Knows what Evil Lurks in the Hearts of Men? The Shadow Knows." has been quoted time and again over the years appearing in cartoons of the time and video games of the modern day. I recommend checking his stories out.

Scrimshaw, A Whalers Art Form Upon the often monotonous and crowded days aboard a whaling vessel a unique form of art was born Scrimshaw! Which involved the carving of images with ink into Whale Bones, often it was the teeth, this unique past time has become incredibly valuable in recent years and is often incredibly detailed. The sailors would make them often as gifts for those back home, sometimes making puzzles or sewing baskets for their families and loved ones among other things. However with how dangerous the job of Whaling was many young men with massive talents for the artform died at a young age, dragged overboard and down to Davy Jones locker by their quarry.

Before the Court of King Neptune In Naval Tradition there is the "Line Crossing Ceremony" in which slimy Pollywogs (those who haven't crossed the equator) become trusty Shellbacks (Those who have) AKA; Sons and Daughters of Neptune. The tradition often involves some form of "humbling" act as well as a dip in sea water. What definitely occurs is that the Court of King Neptune appears, the Ship's captain and other shellbacks appear dressed as King Neptune, Triton, Davy Jones, Neptune's Queen, The Royal Baby (Typically the fattest man aboard), Bears, Mermaids, etc and then judge the Pollywogs before King Neptune's court. If they pass they become full fledged Shellbacks complete with certificate. The tradition is said to be 400 years old AT LEAST. It is likely far far older. As it's name implies it is done when people cross the equator... interestingly it is at the equator that many ships priests have "gone missing" over the centuries go figure.-TLK Hyperborean Radio (Uncensored)

Groundhog Day One of the most famous of all Animal Cults is the "Cult of Groundhogism" practiced by the Pennsylvania Dutch in honor of their totem animal The Groundhog, The Seer of Seers the Prognosticator of Prognosticators! Centered around an eternal Groundhog spirit and originally honored with a Groundhog hunt and feast. Nowadays that weather predicting groundhog is much more popular with the world famous Punxsutawney Phil as the focal point of the Holy Day. He has an inner circle of sacred caretakers, a brotherhood of venerators, and year round care with people who love him and care for him. While much of the holy day is tongue-in-cheek, the Groundhog Lodges where PA Dutch men go is much less so, swearing themselves in as "Baby Groundhogs" and swearing before an Idol of the King Groundhog to always protect and even lay down their lives for the Groundhog.-TLK Hyperborean Radio (Uncensored)

Maine Lobstermen In Maine and parts of the Northeastern States Lobster Fishing is a traditional and incredibly important industry. Due to the nature of Lobsters though there are incredibly important rules and traditions followed. These require an understanding of the Lobsters life cycle, habits and behavior on a deep level to be able to properly trap for Lobsters. Unlike other fishing industries, Lobster Fishing has remained largely small scale and family oriented with the various fisherman enforcing their own code of conduct such as limiting the number of Lobsters one can take or as seen in the above video marking breeding females to be unable to be kept. Lobsters can live over a hundred years being effectively immortal, only dying when they become too big to molt. As such a properly tended environment and population of Lobsters can feed people indefinitely but it requires understanding, genuine care and respect for these delicious buttery crustaceans. Gustaf Tenggren & Early Disney One of the most beautiful parts of American Media and Culture were the early films of Disney which drew heavily from European Fairy Tales and Literature. The style was even based largely off these older illustrations. While Walt Disney himself was a talented animator it was a Swedish Immigrant turned American that can be thanked for much of the beauty of the art style. Gustaf Tenggren was a phenomenal and largely unknown artist inspired by the likes of John Bauer, Arthur Rackham, Edmund Dulac, Kay Nielsen, and Howard Pyle his Fairy Tale Illustrations serve as Concept Art that far outclasses even the finished product from Disney. It is he who can be thanked for the beautiful and whimsical designs of early Disney films like Pinocchio, Snow White, and Bambi. He deserves far more credit than he gets.

Pin Ups and Bombshells While nowadays understandably the concept of a "Pin-Up Girl" is often thought of as Lurid, the Pin-Up and Bombshells of WW2 were an integral part of the morale of the men. Many of which were surrounded exclusively by their wartime brothers, the Pin-ups reminded them of home, many were of famous women, painted by famous artists, or women who volunteered to be depicted as such for the purposes of art and morale. The Pin-Up was so popular it was used in recruitment posters and Men even painted "Nose Art" of Pin-ups on their fighter planes reminding them of home and personalizing their own planes. These two mediums of Nose Art and Pin-Ups fed into each other, and the association gave birth to the term "Bombshell" for beautiful woman. Remind the men that back home were "Women worth fighting for".

Donut Dollies Dating back to WWI and coming to prominence in WW2 the "Donut Dollies" as they came to be called, were Female Red Cross Volunteers whose job was to bring a bit of home to the men fighting in foreign wars. Most famous for their bringing of free Coffee and Donuts to the men, as The American Donut was such a quintessential pastry that combined with the often charming women would lift the spirits of the men and ease their homesickness. The Point of the Donut Dollies was to keep the morale up, and they also served gum, cigarettes', and ran recreational activities to keep the men's spirits up, they continued to serve donuts for decades through Korea and then in Vietnam the emphasis was placed on the recreational activities while the Donut's faded into the background. This was no easy job as they served millions of donuts and cups of coffee while dodging bombs and bullets. The ladies were also chosen through a rigorous selection process which included picking them based on their amicable personality.

Which leads to the real question... Was it ever a good idea to head towards these futuristic Utopias or was it always merely an overly optimistic view of the future, ignoring our own natures?

The Puritan by Augustus Saint-Gaudens 1887 Springfield, Massachusetts The Puritan is one of the most famous and influential statues in America and is said to depict Samuel Chapin one of the original settlers of Springfield. Commisioned by said Chapin's descendent Chester W. Chapin. Originally set up in Stearns Square, it now stands near the Quadrangle in Springfield. It is so popular it was reproduced in 20 other cities and has been used for Municipal Flags, Railroad Companies, and even made into Stained Glass.

Giles Corey of Salem While often depicted as a hallmark of a super Christian America, Salem's ultra puritanical approach is noteworthy due to how odd and severe it was in comparison to much of the rest of America regarding its religious zeal. Being famous for the Salem Witch Trials, among the many who were executed or tried as a witch was one man named Giles Corey. He was charged with being a witch and after refusing to plead guilty was pressed to death under a pile of rocks, when asked if he would confess Corey simply replied "More Rocks" and subsequently died. While often touted by feminists as an example of Woman hating, most of the accusations were levied by other women and many men were also put to death during these witch trials, often much like in the Old Country by petty neighbors taking advantage of the hysteria.

cleaned_message: John James Audobon John James Audobon was a prominent American naturalist and artist, he was born in the French Caribbean as "Jean-Jacques" and anglicized his name upon immigration to the united states at age 18 to avoid getting involved in the Napoleonic wars. He would go to become one of the most important naturalists in American history and produced many writings and works of arts of the fauna across North America, most notably with his work "The Birds of America" where he depicted many iconic American Species and is considered one of the most important Ornithological works of all time. The Audobon society is named after him and was started by George Bird Grinnell. Pictured Audobons depictions of iconic species: Great Blue Heron, Turkey, Sandhill Crane, Mourning Dove, California Condor, Blue Jay, Bald Eagle, and American Robin.

Alexander Hamilton, Truth as Defense One of the most overlooked Founding Fathers save for his visage on the $10 Bill and a rather overplayed Musical written by a Puerto Rican Hamilton is one of the most famous men in American history and one of the most important of the Founding Fathers, sure he isn't in the "Big 3" but he had many important accomplishments in his short lifetime. One of the most important oddly, had less to do with his political career and more to do with his career in law. Where he argued for Truth as Defense against Libel, before this Libel only needed to be proved to be defamatory, not false. Protecting public officials from unfortunate facts that the public had a right to know about if they were unflattering. While Hamilton lost the case of People v. Croswell (N.Y. 1804), his argument that Truth was a defense against Libel eventually changed the laws, and if something was True it could not be Libel, remember that. ‚ÄúThe gist of Hamilton‚Äôs argument was that the truth of the claims made by an author should be admissible evidence for the defense in a libel case. The standard heretofore had been that plaintiffs in libel cases needed to prove only that statements made against them were defamatory, not that they were false.‚Äù -Ron Chernow, Alexander Hamilton

Slue Foot Sue Slue Foot Sue is a folk heroine and lover of Pecos Bill in American folklore. She was a prostitute and a talented and untamable cowgirl. She first meets The Wildman Pecos Bill when she is riding atop the Fur Bearing Catfish (The Spirit of the River) the two fall in love as neither are able to be tamed, but Ol' Sue always had to be contrarian often getting into situations where Pecos would have to fight off bands of Indians or giant monsters to defend her, in some stories the two lived happily ever after but far more commonly Sue tried to ride Bill's Horse Widow-Maker and was thrown clear to the Moon where she lives to this day, perhaps having whiskey and shootouts with the Man in the Moon. While Bill drank his sorrows away with nitroglycerin and either became one with the air or went off to live in the wilderness again as a wildman king of the Coyote's howling at the moon for the woman he lost.

Urglaawe, Pennsylvania Dutch Heathenry In America we have our own branches of Heathenry such as Urglaawe, which spawns from the blatantly Pagan folkloric traditions of the Pennsylvania Dutch, while there is some bleed over with the Eddic tradition the main focus is on German gods such as Perchta, Ewicher Yeeger, Eckhart, Lollus, Zisa, King Frost, and especially Mother Holle who is the patron deity of all Pennsylvania Dutch, and is credited with guiding them to America to escape oppression and watching over them from the Hexenkopf mountain nearby. She is directly tied into many holy days such as Grundsaudag and Allelieweziel and many folktales, many of her and the other gods stories are tied to the American land and incorporate many German and American customs including Steins, Hex Signs, Distlefinks, and more. As Holle is the leader and divine patron of this German-American tribe, her sickle is the symbol they wear in contrast to the Mjolnir typically worn by modern Norse & Germanic Heathens.

Paul Bunyan & The North Pole Paul Bunyan has many tales of what became of him after the large trees he cut were gone, some tales hold that he retired to the Arctic where he and Babe roughhouse creating the Northern Lights. In other tales Paul lives in the Arctic in a cabin enjoying his retirement, aside from the occasional visitor. In one such case the US government looking for a weapon to end WW2 came to Paul who jumped to the sun and asked her for a bit of her flame, when he discovered what it would be used for Paul decided against it and gave it back to the Sun. While even before he "retired" Paul would make trips to the arctic, once in his fight with the Whistling river herding a blizzard from the Arctic to create a chain to defeat the River god, while doing this he also made many of the icebergs in the Arctic. He also once cut the North Pole down for firewood during the year of two winters. Paul never did have a problem with the cold of the Arctic, and is happy being Santa's next door neighbor.

The Spanish Settlement of The American Southwest was an undertaking fraught with setback. The first establishment of Europeans in the area came in the form of Spanish colonists founding Santa Fe in 1598, The Spanish Crown did not think the area warranted its own governor until 1610, at which point Governor Pedro de Peralta received an order from Philip IV of Spain to move to and establish Santa Fe as the capital city of a new Royal Province, New Mexico. Peralta's voyage was one in a series of Spanish expansions in and around the Western regions of America. The founding of Santa Fe would further European settlement out of Mexico and into the Southwest of what is now the United States. üìçSanta Fe, New Mexico

Having spent quite some time overseas, I observed several noticeable cultural differences in the countries I visited in comparison to our own in the US. 1. People live to 90+, ride bicycles, and run marathons in some countries. (Staying active prolongs life expectancy.) 2. Fruit and vegetables going bad after several days, not weeks. (Homegrown and natural grown should be our model for health and wellness.) 3. Families living together, with the elderly staying until passing from this life, children not leaving in search of greener pastures and/or being kicked out at 18. (We Hyperboreans used to have large households (7+ children) up until the prohibition era. It is only in the modern era that they are seen as a hindrance and burden.)

Australian Shepherds are also incredibly adorable and loving, speaking from experience as my family has had two of them, their name Aussies, is a reference to the sheep imported from Oceania (New Zealand & Australia) that they were employed to herd in the American West. The breeds genetic stock is actually from Basque & Iberian (Spanish and Portuguese) breeds.

American Breeds: Australian Shepherd Australian shepherds despite their name are actually an American breed, they were bred by Basque Americans in California and were an exceptional herding breed for a long time. Being used to herd Sheep, Geese, and children. They were a relatively obscure breed until they were popularized in the Rodeo, by performer Jay Lister who would perform numerous tricks with his Aussies. From there they became incredibly popular and have become one of the most popular breeds in America. They are highly intelligent and agile, they are extremely affectionate and typically calm, they require stimulation similar to all highly intelligent breeds and can act out if they don't get it. Under no circumstances should one breed two "Merles" together as despite the beauty of their coats the two together will result in many genetic defects in their offspring. Like all breeds Aussie's have their quirks, notably they love to have their rear end scratched, as odd as that seems.

The Devil at the Crossroads? A common trope in American folklore is the deal with the devil at the crossroads, selling ones soul for money, fame, but most well known a gift of Musical Talent. So prolific is this tale that it is even a prevailing theory as to the deaths of Buddy Holly, Richie Valens and the Big Bopper! That they had tried to break their deal and lost their lives as a result. However, there is a prevailing theory regarding these music deals, as the Black Americans and White Americans have a radically different way of dealing with the agreements. That the "Devil" at the crossroads is actually various ethnic gods much as the tradition of Hecate or Perchta would show. That they make a deal with gods of music and song and in exchange as the musicians have said they can never stop giving music to the world, because if they do they will die, so they play on. No souls in exchange only music, music until death.

The Jersey Devil The Jersey Devil, also known as the Leed's Devil is one of the most famous creatures of American myth, the monster that haunts the New Jersey Pine Barrens. It is said a woman named Jane Leeds had 12 children and on finding out she was pregnant with a 13th cursed the child to be "The Devil" and after the child was born as a normal babe it quickly turned into a chimeric monster and fled up the chimney, though others claim he was the son of the Devil. The Jersey Devil is also the calm companion of the Golden Haired Girl spirit that lives in the Pine Barrens, and is actually intelligent capable of speech and talking with some of the soldiers who once came to hunt it. While its appearance is standardized now it was once much more amorphous in description. The Jersey Devil has had immense impact on folklore and culture and has appeared in popular media such as the X-Files and is the namesake of the New Jersey Devils Hockey Team.

Devil's Tower National Monument Devil's Tower was America's first National monument as named by Teddy Roosevelt himself and is located in the Black Hills of Wyoming. It's name is supposedly a result of translating the name of the tower as "Bad God's Tower" which was made into Devil's Tower. It supposedly originally meant something along the lines of "Bear Lodge Bluff" though it had many names and the Bear is often seen as Demonic in Amerindian spirituality. Many legends have sprouted up about the Tower and the most prolific and my personal favorite is that it is the remaining stump of a giant fossilized tree.

The Birth of Paul Bunyan There are many tales of the birth of Paul Bunyan and how he came to be. One story says he was brought by a flock of storks to his family, others claim he washed ashore in a giant basket, some say he was born a normal boy and was blessed by the Man in the Moon with his size and abilities. But my favorite story is that he was born of the forest itself. Immortalized in folk songs as "Son of a Great White Oak was He! His Father was a Redwood Tree!" Paul was born as a tree seed, usually an Acorn and from there he grew into a tree and decided he wanted to know what was over yonder hill and pulled up his roots and began to walk becoming the first and only "Paul Bunyan Tree", others have it closer to old Fairy Tales where he may have been born of an acorn but he grew into a man all the same, a large giant of a man the God of the Northwoods for the American People.

If anyone has wondered why we've focused on pop culture the last few days, I want to say it's ok to like stuff. Every bit of our culture can be traced back as part of a line of ideas, creations, beliefs, and traditions that are ancient, follow any line long enough and it'll lead you to something extraordinary. Everything is a result of the culmination of choices and creations that were made over time, the good and the bad, enjoy the good, love what has been created out of love, joy, creativity, and in some cases sorrow and pain. To toss it away because it is new, or because it is not hundreds or thousands of years old in its current state is to not see the forest for the trees. I repeat it's ok to like stuff, it's ok to live to laugh and love, to cry and sing, and everything in between. I hope you have a wondrous day and may our Forefathers and The Goddess Columbia smile upon you. The Folks at The American Spirit

Comic Strips, Animation, and Early Franchises Most earlier animators came from Comic Strip illustrators, this eventually gave rise to rubberhose animation, many of these early comic strips such as Little Orphan Annie, Popeye The Sailor Man, Flash Gordon, Dick Tracy, and Tarzan are still well known properties to this day and many were some of the first animated tv shows.
The Interior & Exterior of the Charles M. Schulz Museum in Santa Rosa, California.

Snoopy & NASA Snoopy the Beagle is most likely the most recognizable Comic Strip character in the history of comic strips, even the likes of Garfield and Marmaduke are not even close in terms of popularity and recognizability. The imaginative Peanut's Character, Best Friend of Woodstock and Charlie Brown is beloved across the globe, the Star of Specials where he is often in at least one scene fighting his imaginary arch-nemesis "The Red Baron" Snoopy can be seen as far away as Japan and more than likely everyone has held or owned at least one thing with Snoopy the Beagle's face on it, he was even the unofficial Mascot for the Apollo 11 Mission, and NASA even gives out the "Silver Snoopy Award" for outstanding achievements.

Popeye Trail The Popeye Trail in Chester, Illinois is a tribute to both the extremely popular character of Popeye and the town hero of Elzie Segar who created Popeye. It is planned to include 21 different statues honoring different characters from the comic strip most of which from Popeye and Olive Oyl to even the burger loving Wimpy were based on real people from Segar's hometown. So far they have 18/21 the most recent one was Harold Hamgravy in 2021. Along with the hero veneration aspect, there are also the names of the dead placed on the statues to honor them, it is fitting that the person who spearheaded this project is the town undertaker. Effectively these are memorials and/or Wayside Shrines. To remember and to inspire the people of Chester.

Little Nemo Little Nemo was a comic strip written by Michigander Winsor McCay from 1905-1927, back when the comics could be longer and often had more dramatic storylines, it's easy to see how the graphic novel spawned from these comics that began to be released in American newspapers, the comic featured Little Nemo sleeping and going to Slumberland (Land of the Gods) where he would have fantastical adventures with King Morpheus (God of Dreams), Santa Claus, Jack Frost, and a number of other fantasy and mythical characters. The comic was noted for its beautiful artwork with immense detail from the characters to the architecture and is considered McCay's masterpiece. Each comic typically ended with Nemo waking up.

Why the Underwear on the Outside? If you've ever seen the original designs for Superheroes especially those like Superman you have had the urge to or made the joke about him wearing his underwear on the outside. While this is a head scratcher in the modern day it actually makes total sense when the comics first appeared. As the strongmen acts of the time that populated boardwalks and carnivals often featured scantily clad Adonis' with nothing but boots and a pair of "Trunks" or as we would call them today "Speedos" the incorporation of this imagery into the costumes of Superheroes was meant to show their massive strength and power. As the culture shifted we lost context and it became point of mockery for the Superhero Genre.
Aviator By J.C. Leyendecker 1927

Elvis Presley & Captain Marvel Jr. It may seem odd but there was a time When Captain Marvel (Shazam! Not the Marvel Mary Sue) was one of the most popular characters in Pop Culture, so much so that the Fantastic figure gained a whole family of characters including Captain Marvel Jr. The whole "Marvel Family" included the abilities of Solomon (Wisdom), Hercules (Strength), Atlas (Stamina), Zeus (Power), Achilles (Courage), and Mercury (Speed) as well as some basic magical fantasy abilities. While the comics were stalled out due to being sued, the imagery of Captain Marvel Jr. kept going as Elvis Presley was a massive fan of the character and based his iconic look of blue suit, lightning symbolism, cape, and large collar and even the iconic Presley haircut off of Captain Marvel Jr. Making this obscure character one of the most prolific images of American Popular culture and music.
Buffalo Bill By James Bama

The Lore Continues Our gods have remained with us to this day, though we have been taught not to see them. While modern media has caused the Folklore to begin to fade, the stories always find a way on the dynamic color illustrations of Newspaper strips the beginnings of the "Superman" or Superhero craze started to germinate, and over the years intentionally by many authors and artists the gods of old were brought to the modern day. Some are obvious, such as Thor in Marvel or Green Arrow being based off Robin Hood. Others less so such as Wonder Woman continuing Columbia, Hermes appearing as both the Flash and SHAZAM! The Green Man finding his roots again in Swamp Thing complete with constant rebirth as the Lore depicts, even some seem the god made Mortal, for example Aquaman being an obvious play off Greek sea deities like Poseidon and Triton. Filling the absence of modern myth.
Cuchulain By J.C. Leyendecker 1906

A Memory of the Sun and the Moon Across most cultures the Sun and the Moon have an intimate relationship, and Hyperborean cultures are no different. The cultural and psychological archetypes of these various deities remain with us regardless of choice or reason. In America we have them as well, they go by the names Superman and Wonder Woman. These are fictional figures that is true, but they embody much older archetypes. Superman blends Sun god symbolism present in Sol Invictus and Apollo, mixed with the American Heroes such as Paul Bunyan and elements of Americana, he sits at the top of a fictional pantheon like a Modern Zeus or Dajbog. While Wonder Woman as Diana Prince, is the Moon Goddess her name a call back to the Roman goddess herself, she stands as Greco-American demigod, with the armor of the American Columbia the Lasso of Truth and a love for fighting-men and the strength of femininity. She does not pretend to be male but like Artemis, Athena, & Columbia her femininity is both armor and weapon.

Columbia, American Goddess of War Along with representing the country itself and it's ideals Columbia is also a war goddess. While Columbia does find antecedents and contemporaries in Lady Liberty and the Roman Libertas, she also succeeds Minerva as a war goddess, with shield, sword, and Eagle companion she will mercilessly fight America's enemies and valiantly support the men in the war effort, often being used as a promotional image to call men to war, to both honor and protect our goddess.

Folklore of Pennsylvania: Loop Hill Ike and the Haunted Fiddle If you lived in Pennsylvania during the 1800s, and had a problem of the paranormal sort, there was a man who could take care of that for you. Loop Hill Ike was just that man. Ike was considered a "Supernatural Bounty Hunter." Ike had other talents aside from casting out ghouls and witches....he was also an astounding fiddle player. One night, Ike and his friend, Bud, attended a dance at an abandoned house in Elk Country. Ike brought his fiddle along. When they got to the house, Bud offered to play the fiddle while Ike danced with a woman he had been courting. About an hour into the festivities, a loud bang was heard from upstairs, as though a door has been slammed shut. This was followed by heavy footsteps coming down the stairs. No one could see anything, even when the being should have been right there in front of them. But then Bud yelled out that HE could see the ghost of a man. Bud was the seventh son of a seventh son. Superstition states, that the seventh son born of a seventh son would have the second sight. All the party goers fled from the house, except for Bud and Ike. Ike knew just what to do. He would play the fiddle for the ghost and make him dance. But Ike couldn't play for something he couldn't see. So, he went down to the lake nearby, and picked a bit of monkshood, and put it in his hat. Now he could see the ghost. Ike began to play, slowly at first. The Ghost began to dance. Everyone knows that ghosts can't resist a good tune. Then Ike began to play faster and faster. The Ghost clomped his feet, dancing away until he stepped in a hole and fell through the wooden floor. As the ghost was falling, he slapped the monkshood out of Ike's hat. After that the ghost disappeared. Something peculiar happened then, that even Ike couldn't explain. His fiddle would never play again. No matter if he ran the bow across the strings, the instrument would make no sound. Ike was buried with his fiddle on a hill in Clinton County. He was actually a real person whose birth name was Isaac Gaines. He is considered a folk hero in Pennsylvania.

Invention of Basketball Basketball was invented in the early 1890's by Physical Education Graduate Student James Naismith at the YMCA Training School now called Springfield College in Massachusetts. It was invented in order to fill the Winter Months when Lacrosse and Football were unable to be played due to the cold weather, so that the young men could burn off the excess energy they accumulated without the other games. It combined elements of Rugby, Football, Duck on a Rock, and Soccer while toning down the physical interaction in order to avoid injuries that would increase without an open field to play in. Originally the basket was made of Peach Baskets (Originally meant to be crates, the circular shape was an accident). The game was an immediate hit and the 13 rules were published in the college magazine and basketball spread like wildfire. Today it one of the most popular games in the United States especially in March when "March Madness" is prevalent for the game.

Folklore of New Jersey: The Pine Barrens Once ranging North Carolina to Nova Scotia, the Pine Barrens are now a "rare temperate coniferous forest ecoregion." The ecosystem has been so badly damaged by urban development through the last few centuries, only about 10% of the original habitat remains. Other Sections of the Northeast United States that still contain the original Pine Barrens are: the New Jersey Pine Barrens; Long Island Central Pine Barrens in New York; and the Massachusetts Coastal Pine Barrens with concentrations in Myles Standish State Forest, Manuel F. Correllus State Forest on Martha's Vineyard, Cape Cod National Seashore and Joint Base Cape Cod and the Mashpee Wampanoag Indian Reservation in Massachusetts. Thankfully, these areas are well conserved. Before the Dutch and Swedes settled there, the Pine Barrens were inhabited by Lenape tribes. Today, much of the areas that underwent urban development have been abandoned. This seems to be the reason why the Pine Barrens of New Jersey has a quiet eeriness lingering over it. The ruins of old buildings and derelict houses can make you feel quite small and vulnerable. The legends don't help anything. The Pine Barrens have had much folklore attached to them for many years Jersey Devil: Probably the most well known legend of the ecoregion, is that of the Jersey Devil. According to the story, the creature was the 13th child of a 1700s woman, who could barely take care of her other 12 children. When she found out she was pregnant again, she declared: "Let it be the Devil!" The thing she bore was twisted and ugly, with large black wings, the body of a horse, and the head of a goat. The creature jumped out of the window and flew into the Pine Barrens, where people claim to see it even today. Captain Kidd: According to locals, the notorious pirate, Captain Kidd hid his treasure on Barnegat Bay, at the edge of the Pinelands, sometime in the late 1600s. Kidd's headless ghost is said have been seen over the centuries, walking along the beach with the Jersey Devil by his side. The Black Dog: We are used to hearing stories of spectral back hounds to be omens of death, but the black dog that haunts the Pine Barrens is said to be harmless. As the story goes, the ghost was the dog of a cabin boy on a ship. The ship was attacked by pirates, many of the crew were killed. Among the dead were this boy and his dog. The bodies were thrown into the water. A Pine Barrens island called Absecon Island was just half a mile away. It is believed the spirits of the boy and his dog did not know they were dead and made their way to the island. The boy's ghost has never been reported, but sightings of the black dog have been accompanied by human-like whistling. The Golden Haired Girl: A ghost said to sit on the rocks that line the beach at the edge of the forest, searching for her betrothed who was lost at sea. Some claim to have seen the Jersey Devil sitting beside her. The White Stag: A phantom white deer that is said to aid lost travelers. The deer has also been credited with preventing disasters. One story tells how it stopped a stagecoach from crashing into the Batsto River. Many believe that seeing this animal brings good luck.

America's National Cherry Blossom Festival On America's National Mall near the Jefferson Monument are a forest of Cherry Trees, these were a gift from Japan as a gesture of Goodwill in 1912. Every year there is a Cherry Blossom Festival from March 20th-April 17th, for four weeks in Washington DC, which symbolizes hope, renewal and new beginnings. They are constantly tended to and about 90 of the trees need to be replaced every year as they grow old and die, but new ones are planted to continue the forest of goodwill and the beauty of Spring.

While often seen as a Feminist Icon, the idea behind these paintings has more to do with the idea of making a sacrifice of ones family and comfort in order to help the war effort and their country, as their men did their part the Women did as well. Then they were misled into staying in the workforce driving wages down and tearing families apart. Women could always enter the workforce, it wasn't until after WW2 that it quickly became a necessity just to make ends meet. Families suffered, and businesses got cheaper labor. Pikes Peak, America's Mountain Pike's Peak has largely faded from the larger consciousness of America, but it was once a central part of our folklore and legends. It is said that it was built by Paul Bunyan after a day full of rather lengthy exploits. While a story of Pecos Bill's Horse Widowmaker says that one of Bill's friends tried to ride Widowmaker and the horse sent them flying all the way to the top of Pike's Peak, Bill then used his Rattlesnake Lasso to get his friend down, for his lasso was as long as the equator. After Columbia was given Uncle Sam as a "Brother" Uncle Sam was said to use Pike's Peak as his throne through which he could look out across America. Today Pike's Peak is largely forgotten, but it still is rife with lore of Cryptids, Wildmen, Miracles, Aliens, and Giant Man Eating rats. A strange "Byway of the Bizarre" of the American West.

Maple Syrup & America Our people have been making Tree syrup for a very long time, but the most quintessential Tree Syrup of North America is Maple Syrup, it went on Paul Bunyan's Flapjacks, its the pride of Vermont and much of the Northeastern United States. We began tapping American Sugar Maple Trees way back in the 1500's and the rest is history. Each region thinks it has the best Maple Syrup, with Vermont and Canada being the most fervent in their Maple Syrup adoration. Syrup producing areas will often use Maple Syrup as their only sweetener, with the production, Maple Forests, and use of the syrup taking on near spiritual components. Personally I think the Maple Syrup from my Home State of Iowa is the best. The Syrup can be further processed into an amber like substance that can be made into "Maple Sugar". P.S.- The Amerindians did not have Syrup they had the Sap, but the making of it into Syrup was a Hyperborean addition much like we already did with other trees such as Birch.

Bestiary Entry #49- Leprechaun Territory & Habitat: Ireland, North America, Wheel Wells of Commercial Airliners, and the dreams and ramblings of drunkards and fools. The Leprechaun is one of the most well known creatures of Irish myth, and as requested by L.O.R.E. I have proceeded to look into them and discover if they can be of some use especially in regards to an extra/paranormal source of funding. However, much of the lore involving Leprechauns is quite odd, and not the typical way but in the way one might find the ramblings of a drunkard or a fool to be. This seems to have been perpetuated by foreigners and the average person unaware of the broader lore of the Fey. As many old Irish people are rather adamant that Leprechaun's are a bastardization of the gods and fey, some specifically pointing to Lugh, though this seems to be based on little more than the start of their name. The Leprechaun sounds more akin to the story of the ‚ÄúWild Haggis‚Äù or ‚ÄúBlarney Stone‚Äù a sort of practical joke that has gone on to the point of being a near tourist attraction. The Leprechaun is also very different in the Lore attributed to it in Ireland where it is a rather obvious Brownie or Pooka corruption, being a short man with a beard, red suit, and hat. One you may pass on the street without even noticing, almost a way of making fun of the Irish. However, in America from the Boston Celtics to the imagery surrounding Saint Patrick's Day and numerous poorly made films, the Leprechaun is almost always seen in a stereotypical Green costume with a Shamrock. In America the idea of Leprechauns having a pot'o gold at the end of a rainbow or granting wishes is most prevalent to the point that an obscure American custom is the making of ‚ÄúLeprechaun Traps‚Äù where one baits them with ‚ÄúLucky Charms‚Äù or other colorful candies in the attempt to trap the Leprechaun on the eve of Saint Patrick's Day (Feast of the Smith) and have it in the morning and force it to grant wishes. As the Leprechaun and Saint Patrick's Day both served as a means to help the broader American populace accept the Irish, as they had been attacked and discriminated against for refusing to go along with the Church since days of old, and had been in America since day one. By and large the Leprechaun should not be taken seriously as it is more a modern bastardization that seems to mock the fey and gods of old Ireland. Then any real creature and even when not used in mocking is more of a Brownie than a separate class of creature. Eyewitness Accounts 1) Numerous accounts from Drunkards at Inns have been recorded but whether they can be taken seriously is up for debate. 2) L.O.R.E. Has attempted to inquire with many Elders of Irish clans and have been met with the resounding instance of enraged old Irish men raging and throwing things while declaring ‚ÄúThere ain't no such thing as FEKKING LEPRECHAUNS, and there NEVER WERE! They are the invention of the Church perpetuated by liars, drunkards and fools!‚Äù 3) According to a common quote in America Leprechauns are often afraid of the many people who are ‚ÄúAlways after me Lucky Charms‚Äù the exact Nature of these Lucky Charms varies one mister A. Powers says they are taken from the victims of the Irish assassins, while others claim they are a sugary snack food. Still others claim they are ‚Äúpart of a balanced breakfast‚Äù 4) According to a Mr. A. Szyslak they are native to Ireland but ‚Äúthey Come over 'ere in the wheel wells of Aer Lingus Jets‚Äù. Conclusion: Leprechaun's are more than likely just the inventions of drunkards and thieves and there will be no deals made for pots of gold for extra funding for L.O.R.E. Rip Van Winkle Rip Van Winkle is a popular tale by Washington Irving but similar to his other famous work Sleepy Hollow, Ol' Rip is based on Western European Folklore. The American version of the tale speaks of small fey or dwarves giving Rip a drink of some unknown liquor which puts him to sleep until he is old, upon waking this loyalist to the Crown is surprised to find that he no longer lives in English Colonies but American States! However, older European versions of the story depict the Fey as much kinder and mostly misunderstanding the situation, Rip being incredibly lazy and often avoiding work and taking naps, the Fey worry that he is unable to get enough rest and make him magically comfortable so that he can sleep as long as he needs, feeding him and combing his hair and beard. Quilts and Marriage Quilts are a quintessentially American craft. Numerous styles have been done across the years and it was once a rite of passage for young girls as they matured into womanhood. So much so that to this day some parts of the United States still expect a woman to have made at least one quilt before she is recognized as ready to marry. As it not only showed patience, skill, and resourcefulness. But also gave her a head start. The importance of Quilts is mostly lost today as aside from a few crafters or the Amish one does not find True Quilts very often. Yet they were a matter of survival once, fabric was scarce and the Winters of North America are cold and brutal thick blankets were needed and their creation requires creative solutions and the modern Quilt was born from the resourcefulness, skill, and creativity of our women, even with limited resources.

Joseph Palmer, Bearded Heretic It may seem odd to think of today but once having a beard was so culturally unacceptable that people were berated, ostracized and insulted for wearing a beard. Such was the story of Joseph Palmer, an American farmer who grew a beard and was not only accused of being a heretic who emulated Satan with his mane, but was attacked with scissors in an attempt to remove his beard and then thrown in prison when the burly American proceeded to defend himself with a knife and stab some Christian Zealots in the leg. Serving a 15 month prison term for "assault" Palmer would eventually leave after his mother pleaded him to pay the fine, which he had refused as it would be akin to admitting he was at fault. He then joined the ill fated Utopian group the Fruitlands and after it fell apart bought the land and farmed it. His grave contains the Quote "Persecuted for Wearing the Beard" By the time of his death beards had gone from hirsute heresy to the norm once more.

In death he became so much more, a spirit or arguably deity of both the pioneer spirit and of the orchard. He was a strong hairy wildman, who communed with spirits, healed Babe the Big Blue Ox, and planted Orchards in the sky. But most notably he became "The American Dionysus" just as Paul fulfilled a Heracles/Thor style role, Appleseed John fulfilled a Wildman role, nearly naked with a fierce beard and piercing eyes he was known to scare the unknowing preacher with his wild appearance, and most of the trees he planted were cider apples, he even became intricately connected with the Winter Solstice and has two holy days, one in the Spring (Which is today March 11th) and one in the fall. The planting and growing seasons, becoming effectively a god of not only Hard Cider but also vegetation and a sort of wild wisdom or madness, American Dionysus indeed.

Courir de Mardis Gras The Courir (Running) of Mardi Gras is a Cajun tradition, not dissimilar to Wassailing but far far more debauched and riotous. It involves homemade costumes in a French Style that has changed little in the last few hundred years, Horse Back Riding capitaines, A group of "Villains" who physically beat any offenders who break the rules, singing, live folk music, chasing a chicken in an attempt to catch it, scaling a greased up pole, dancing and plenty of drunken merry making ending in a massive Cajun Feast involving communal gumbo and much much more. A unique cultural experience of Lousiana's Cajun tribes.

While the settlers of Vinland brought the old gods notably Thor In one tale of Thor in Vinland, a devote of Thor appealed to Thor to help with the hunger of the men and was thus delivered a whale carcass. Other figures like Finn McCool, Easter, and The Wild Huntsman were also brought over along with many other Old Gods, as well as homegrown deities like Paul Bunyan and Joe Magarac.-TLK

Gun decking In the old days of American maritime service, under certain circumstances, drunkenness was not a crime. Shore liberty was granted very infrequently and it was expected that many of the men would return to the ship drunk, with torn clothes and bearing the marks of a fight. Officers of the deck recorded the return of each man in the ship‚Äôs logbook. A man returning in a normal condition was logged as "CS," meaning clean and sober. A drunk was logged as "DD," which stood for drunk and dirty. A drunken crew member had one objective that had came up with the practice of granting shore leave. He was expected to conduct himself properly in the presence of the gangway watch; but upon reaching the gun deck, he was allowed to curse the officers, the ship, the navy, or any other institution with the vilest language he was capable of speaking with impunity. This practice was called "gundecking" and constituted one of the few ways which the men of the Old Navy had for releasing pent-up anger and emotions.

cleaned_message: Folklore of Maine: Paul Bunyan On the day he was born, Paul Bunyan gave his parents quite the shock. He was the largest baby they had ever seen. He was far to heavy to carry, so 5 large birds had to pick him up to move him from place to place. By the time he was only a few weeks old, he weighed over 100 pounds. Growing up, Paul was ALWAYS hungry. He ate 50 eggs and 10 bushels of potatoes a day. By the time he was 13, he was so big, his parents had no idea what to do with him. One time, Paul rolled over when he was sleeping and this caused an earthquake. The earthquake brought a mob of angry townsfolk to the Bunyan's home. They demanded that Paul must go live elsewhere. His parents took him deep into the woods. This is where he would stay. In the woods, he helped his father cut down trees. This was easy work for Paul, as he had the strength of 20 men and he was very very fast. One day Paul came upon an unusual sight. I found a blue baby ox and decided to keep him. At night he put the ox in the barn with the other animals. In the morning the barn was gone and so was the ox. Paul found him grazing in a field. But the ox was no longer small. He had grown into a giant ox over night. So tall, his back (which now had the barn stuck on top of it) came up to Paul's waist Paul named the ox Babe. Paul and Babe left Maine and headed west to search for more work in the forests. On the way, Paul dug out the Great Lakes so that babe could have plenty of water to drink. They settled at a camp in Minnesota. Paul gathered other lumberjacks to help with the work. His crew became known as the Seven Axemen. All of these men were well over 6 feet tall and weighed over 300 pounds. Every Sunday, Paul and his crew ate pancakes. Each cake was so large, it took 5 men just to eat one. Paul always gave Babe a giant sugar cube as a treat after a hard day's work. It is said that Paul cleared many forests throughout the northern united states and parts of Canada. Babe died in South Dakota. It is believed he ate too many pancakes. Paul buried his companion there and this created the Black Hills. There are different versions of Paul's Fate. Some say that he was last seen in Alaska, or even the Arctic Circle. Other stories say that he returns to Minnesota or Maine every summer but that he moves in and out of the forest so many never know where he is.

Folklore of Louisiana: Lutin Stories of these hobgoblin-like creatures, were brought over to Louisiana with the French settlers The Lutin can take many different shapes, including cats (commonly white ones). Cajuns claimed that these pranksters were very active in their new homes on the bayou. Usually their shenanigans are more annoying than malicious. French Catholics believed these beings to be the spirits of babies, who died before being baptized.

Bestiary Entry #45- The Nain Rouge Territory & Habitat; The Area around Detroit, Michigan. The Nain Rouge (Red Dwarf) AKA The ‚ÄúHell Goat‚Äù is a kind of imp or dwarf from Detroit Folklore. It is said to plague Detroit and be an omen of misfortune. It is said that the founder of Detroit Antoine de la Mothe, sieur de Cadillac was told to appease the Nain Rouge but refused to and instead beat it resulting in Cadillac being cursed with misfortune. While his name implies he is a dwarf the Nain Rouge is often depicted closer to a stereotypical Christian Demon or European horned god. Possessing Red skin, pointed ears, horns, claws, and a beard. With many calling him a ‚ÄúLutin‚Äù or hobgoblin. The Nain Rouge is also the focus not only of being the harbinger of Detroit's Doom, but also being the figure at the head of the March of the Nain Rouge. Which is held every spring since 2010, the Nain Rouge as ‚ÄúThe Harbinger of Doom‚Äù and ‚ÄúThe Embodiment of Everything that Holds Detroit back‚Äù. At the end of the procession of floats, fire dancers, and people embodying the Nain Rouge an effigy of the Nain Rouge is burned to ward off the dwarf's supposed malevolence for a time. While this tradition is intended to keep the Nain Rouge at bay, a second part of the procession involving ‚ÄúPro-Nain‚Äù protesters exists encouraging people to not shoo away the dwarf, though this seems primarily to be a tongue-in-cheek protest. While the tradition itself is fairly new, it is based on a shared cultural heritage of Detroit and New Orleans, as both were founded by French settlers hundreds of years ago, and is intended to unite Detroit. With the Nain Rouge becoming more a symbol of Detroit then a malevolent force in the modern day. With the aforementioned protesters saying things like ‚ÄúThe Real Nain Rouge is Nice‚Äù. Eyewitness Accounts 1) The most famous account I have heard is from that of Cadillac himself, as he was warned of the Nain Rouge and told to appease it, but instead when it arrived he beat it with his cane, resulting in a curse of misfortune being placed upon Detroit's founder. 2) Other eyewitness accounts point to the times the Dwarf has appeared before catastrophe including: The Battle of Bloody Run (1763), The Fire of 1805, the 12th Street Riot (1967), among other events the city has faced. Conclusion: The people of Detroit seem to have it handled in terms of mitigating any curse, but even without the curse that Cadillac incurred, the city faces many issues of a more mundane and less magical variety, while the Nain Rouge may have caused some of it, there is no way to know how much one can blame on the dwarf and how much one must lay at the feet of man, but as is usually the case of history it is man who will bear the brunt of the blame and the consequences.

The Unseen Bear Cult Holidays The Bear Cult is one of many enduring aspects of European ethnic faith, and most people don't see the elements of culture that have been drawn from it, changed as they are after centuries of cultural shift and Church influence. But there are two big ones in February alone, Groundhog Day & Valentine's Day. Both spawn from different regional traditions involving the bear as incarnation of the gods. The Groundhog Day tradition arose from a combination of Imbolc and the awakening of the Bear which was transplanted onto the "Bear Rodent" (Groundhog), while from a slightly different regional tradition that blended with Lupercalia, Medieval Romance sensibilities and bird mating rituals observed around the same time spawned Valentine's day, the name of the saint connected with the day is no accident, many "Bear Saints" arose to cover up the Bear Cult, Valentine was one such saint, and its association with the Bear Cult can be seen in the Medieval Romance "Valentine & Orson".-TLK
Happy Valentine's Day Folks

Records state that Blackbeard was very tall and enormous trademark black beard ‚Äî long enough to reach his waist. A warrior through and through, on his final battle he sustained around 25 wounds in a skirmish with Lieutenant Robert Maynard in a bloody fight at the mouth of the Okracoke Inlet, North Carolina.

While they live primarily in European mountain ranges, they have apparently followed the people to America and set up a colony of their own in Northwest Minnesota where a Mountain Range fits them like their nonexistent snowshoes. Eyewitness Accounts 1) While scant, several eyewitness accounts point to them spreading across the Atlantic, if they have arrive in Minnesota it is doubtful the Barbegazi hasn't spread to other snow capped mountains in America, with a high percentage of Hyperborean population. 2) The whistling sound and helpful nature of the spirits marks them as generally kind and numerous eyewitness accounts mark them as a helpful Wild Spirit, akin to Basajaun. Though like any spirit, creature, or being of Faerie or Elphame the Barbegazi will have inevitable variation in personality and in reaction to various individuals. Conclusion: The Barbegazi is a wild spirit, ebbing and flowing with the seasons, it shows little sign of domestication unlike many helpful spirits I have reviewed, and instead has retained its wildness. While classified as Fey by many, it is closer in appearance to either a dwarf or Woodwose, neither of which is really a creature of Faerie. The latter of which tends to live in the wilds of the Mortal realm and at times is even a Hyperborean Human in its raw primal state, the former however would match both aspects of the physical description and living traditions of mountain caves. Indicating a possible demigod creature, as Dwarves are far more than Tolkien may have written about. No expert crafting beyond tunnel creation has been mentioned. It is by far a generally helpful spirit, as such I see no reason to worry about it atm, even with the Winter Olympics going on, it is more likely the Barbegazi will not set foot in China, as there is not enough Hyperborean blood to draw them there, nor are there any indications of an extant population in Oriental Territory. Unlike the Dogmen Barbegazi have not shown habits of bonding to individuals, and even if they did, its helpful nature would make it a boon to the athletes, and not a bane. L.O.R.E. Has no need to try to contain or be concerned with the Barbegazi.

Bestiary Entry #40-Barbegazi Territory & Habitat: The European Alps, primarily the French Alps, they have also spread across other mountain ranges, and have traveled to America with the people. Creating an extant population in Northwest Minnesota. The Barbegazi ‚ÄúFrozen Beard‚Äù are Alpine spirits, primarily a kind of Faerie Folk, or perhaps Dwarf. They dwell in mountain tops primarily in the French Alps, though they are found in other regions as well. They are extremely hairy being covered neck down in thick white hair and possessing a massive white beard, which due to their cold environment is almost always covered in icicles, hence their moniker. They are most likely physical beings that can take advantage of the altitude, shadows, and underground passages that they live in, in order to cross between the realms. Though most likely they are also physically here, as they occupy land rarely seen by mortals. The Barbegazi are a variation on either a Woodwose or Dwarf style spirit in terms of both appearance and action. As the Barbegazi enjoy the cold, hibernating underground in their caverns during Summer Months, while coming out during the colder Winter months. They are also built rather like dwarves being stocky and powerfully built, with enormous feet that they use to slide down snow like skis or to walk atop massive snowfall akin to snowshoes. They are expert tunnelers far exceeding any burrowing animal of the mortal plane. Able to quickly burrow into snow and mountain rock, creating complex tunnel systems that they live in. They are helpful beings often whistling to warn of storms, or helping shepherds collect their sheep, they do this by letting out a whistling sound, and their tunneling ability has allowed them to dig people out of deep snow, saving lives. Their helpfulness to shepherds and their whistling to warn of storms reminds one of the Wildmen spirits or deities of the Basque Pyrenees Basajaun. One wonders if the two are connected given the interconnectedness or at least parallel evolution of the Lore of the Alps and the Pyrenees. All in all a fairly helpful spirit, they seem to enjoy riding atop avalanches, though whether they are able to cause them beyond the level of say, a very loud human I am unsure.

‚ÄúThe curse of every ancient civilization was that its men in the end became unable to fight. Materialism, luxury, safety, even sometimes an almost modern sentimentality, weakened the fibre of each civilized race in turn; each became in the end a nation of pacifists, and then each was trodden under foot by some ruder people that had kept that virile fighting power the lack of which makes all other virtues useless and sometimes even harmful.‚Äù Theodore Roosevelt

There is some evidence that the Dogmen or a subset of them may in fact be humans made into Woodwose by casting off society. However, not enough evidence exists to confirm or deny this hypothesis. Eyewitness Accounts 1) Several Hyperborean Soldiers from Michigan have reported seeing them in battle while in Afghanistan, these individual Dogmen or tribes (packs?) of Dogmen traveled alongside the bonded individual(s) either in ammunition crates or Wheel Wells of the planes (speculation?). They take part in the battles and in some cases wipe out enemy encampments with ‚ÄúDog Tracks‚Äù found all over, after the events. 2) Several sightings in the North-Western Lower Peninsula of Michigan including Gladwyn and nearby cities. The sightings are varied but consistent, with the Dogmen being credited with killing their ‚Äúvictims‚Äù and strewing their mangled corpses across multiple trees, from which the rotting flesh doth hang. 3) In the Upper Peninsula (from approx. St. Ignace to Escanaba) there are many sightings of the Dogmen, similar to in the LP. The people disappear but their bodies are never found, unlike in the LP. Bloodied clothing has been found but never the bodies. One wonders if this ties into their possible lycanthropic tendencies. 4) As the Dogmen serve as guardians and protectors they are often left gifts of clothing and food. Close to Omar, Michigan. People would often take food and clothing to an abandoned cabin as thank you for the protection the Dogmen had given them. Conclusion: The Dogmen are mysterious, it is unclear if they are Wild Men, Werewolves, Guardian Spirits, or something else entirely. Among the Hyperborean's of the Upper Midwest, especially Michigan, they are seen as benevolent and well liked. Despite their unpredictable actions and violent tendencies. I see no true harm they can do, no more damage than one can find in a Gargoyle's territory or that of a Grimhound. Similar to the latter, I see no way to possibly contain the beings. As even if they are physical, as the locals say ‚ÄúThey are very good at hiding‚Äù and more than good at killing.

Bestiary Entry #38- The Dogmen Territory & Habitat: The Dogmen are a group of woodwose and werewolf style beings that predominate in the area of the Upper Midwest Great Lakes Area. Mostly in Michigan and Wisconsin. Typically in wooded areas though they can extend into rural areas at times. It is unclear if this is the same species known as the Cynocephalus from Medieval texts, such as that which the Orthodox Church draws their Saint Christopher. While this species or subspecies of spirits are mostly in the Upper Midwest, they are known to travel and have traveled across the United States and abroad in order to follow and/or protect those they attach themselves to. The Dogmen are beings that live in America and may or may not have come over from Europe (It is unclear if they emigrated with people, or if they are some kind of cryptid.) They appear in multiple forms sometimes appearing as a Werewolf style beings, while others depict them as Woodwoses or Bigfoot-like beings. The Dogmen are in the popular consciousness merely monsters, cryptids or beasts of physical form either as Lycanthropes or as Bigfeet. However, after further study I think this is but a popular fallacy not dissimilar to the equivalency of the Fey and Elves in many peoples mind. The actual lore and animistic practices of the Hyperborean Michiganders does not suggest a mere beast. They live in the wilds of Michigan and the nearby States, where they are said to protect the good and punish the wicked. With people often leaving gifts to them, such as food or clothes. With certain campgrounds and old cabins being hot spots of the Dogmen. They are said to be dog headed, fur covered men. Being man shaped in all but their head. The Dogmen have been said to have followed the individuals they have bonded with (Unclear as to the process or reasoning behind this) to Afghanistan, and there are even stories of them fighting in the USA Civil War. They are not spirits in the sense that most would see them, rather they are physical beings though in what way is unclear. Not dissimilar to Saint Christopher, the Wulver, or the Cynocephalus of Medieval travel logs they are said to be real physical beings similar to the Trolls of Northern Europe. They are said to simply be good at hiding.

Bestiary Entry #35- Butzemann Territory & Habitat: Farms and Fields of Pennsylvania, Germany and nearby areas (As well as other areas where summoned), though to what extent is unknown. Among the Pennsylvania Dutch AKA Deitsch there is a tradition of the ‚ÄúButzemann‚Äù the Butzemann is a scarecrow and protective totem, that around Groundhog day is activated (Often by a witch) embodying a kind of nature spirit, neither the scarecrow nor the spirit alone is necessarily the Butzemann, occasionally a female version of this spirit a ‚ÄúButzefrau‚Äù also exists but is less common. The Butzemann will take care of a farmers land, performing many chores and protecting against spirits of cold and rot, and receiving gifts of Molasses and Milk as thanks. Around Halloween the Butzemann's body will be burned and its spirit released to the Parade of the Dead led by Holle. There is a risk if the body is not burned that the Wild Hunt will claim the spirit, but leave the body open to more hostile or misanthropic spirits. Each generation of Butzemann receives the names of the previous creations with the first one being known as (Name) + der nei (Or ‚ÄúThe new‚Äù) before becoming the surname or clan name of this specific series of Butzemann/Butzefrau (Name)+sen/docha. The spirits themselves are benevolent and typically more than a little friendly to those they serve as caretakers to, though their left over scarecrow bodies serve as easy physical manifestation for any number of spirits, akin to spiritual hermit crabs in a way.... Eyewitness Accounts 1) One well known account among the heathens of Urglaawe tribal tradition tells of ‚ÄúDelbel the Butzemann‚Äù who was built with a rickety leg, unclear if historical instance or if used as a warning against not following traditions regarding the physical body. The creator of Delbel died and the resulting chaos wrought carnage across the town, as his spirit was taken by ‚ÄúThe White Lady‚Äù but his body was left unburnt, resulting in a Boogeyman who was more than happy to set fires, let loose numerous animals, and just cause general issues before a local Braucheri (Good Witch) aided Delbel in completing the latter half of his release. 2) Several instances of Butzemann burnings being described as ‚Äúoddly beautiful‚Äù or dancing. I have yet to observe any moving scarecrows, though am not one to doubt regarding the Wild Hunt or Goblin like nature spirits. Conclusion: The Butzemann is a generally helpful borderline domesticated spirit, far more congenial than the more temperamental Brownie or Kobold. Requiring little more than physical upkeep and some minor gifts as thank you, it is unclear given its state of being a clothed scarecrow if it dislikes gifts of clothes similar to many domestic spirits. I am forced to conclude the Butzemann is a helpful spirit, though its form should be burned to avoid rampant arson from scarecrows, we get enough of that from the humans on Halloween.

Bestiary Entry #34-The Groundhog Territory & Habitat: Pennsylvania and its various Groundhog Burrows primarily, actively venerated at versammlinge gatherings, power centers during the ancient holiday now known as ‚ÄúGroundhog Day‚Äù making Punxsutawney the focal point of the figures energy. Can be found across the USA and parts of Canada. The Groundhog is a spirit and totemic animal of the American tribe known commonly as the Pennsylvania Dutch or Deitsch. The traditions surrounding it and its related Holiday are old, and can be traced back to the Bear Cult of the Old Ones, and the festival of the little lights and rising flames. The Groundhog or ‚ÄúKing Groundhog‚Äù is an odd spirit as by accounts we have uncovered he is an ancient being born in the Chaos of the Long Long Ago. Despite his legend being fairly new in many ways. Able to control the weather or at the least predict it. ‚ÄúThe One True Prophet‚Äù as they call him. With even the world famous Punxsutawney Phil being but a pretender, his ‚ÄúOracle of Delphi‚Äù if you will, the Groundhog fulfilling a role akin to Gaia Apollo. Mother Earth (Hertha? Gaia?) is described as bound in her chains and proclaiming that those in need of prophecy must ‚ÄúSeek the Groundhogs Hole‚Äù. It is said the Groundhog is embodied in all the Groundhogs, with all of them being both The Groundhog and not The Groundhog. The ‚ÄúCult of Groundhogism‚Äù as it is called is practiced among the Deitsch. Some practice it as Tongue-in-Cheek, while others with far more seriousness. The various Inner Circles and their ‚Äúpriests‚Äù of The Groundhog Prophets are of high import in regards to this spirit. Eyewitness Accounts 1) The Groundhog is honored at various gatherings, in one instance an effigy of Punxsutawney Phil was hung for daring to be a pretender to the throne of The Groundhog. Implying some level of awareness that Phil is not the primary figure of this pagan cult. The men also tend to show their hands in front of them like paws when swearing oaths to a statue (often crowned in the same ceremony) of The Groundhog, as ‚ÄúBaby Groundhogs‚Äù. 2) A story told concerning the Groundhog and Mother Earth involves Mother Earth swearing that The Groundhog is the one true prophet, his association with an Elder God of the Old Ones, testifies to this figures age. 3) Groundhog Day is said to be the day that Butzemann (Protective rural spirits in Scarecrows) are built and blessed by witches, and is directly associated with the Goddess Holle. It is unclear the relationship between The Groundhog and Holle, but both have found ties to the Holiday. 4) Groundhogs Groundhog Day celebrations are powerful instances of tradition taking form, with the focal point around the various Groundhog Prophets, most notable figures such as General Beauregard in the South, as well as Punxsutawney Phil. Complete with numerous rituals and traditions, as well as an honor guard and keepers of his secrets. The speaking of Groundhogese has yet to be deciphered, though we are forced to conclude the scroll read off is pre-prepared if still powerful. Gobblers Knob possesses more power than it wishes to recognize, culminating in the Holiday's celebration. Much fun was had by all, and the Hot Cocoa was excellent. Conclusion: The Groundhog is an important and powerful spirit, related primarily to its core tribe the Deitsch. Most likely harmless, but stronger then first perceived, may require consideration as a deity rather than a spirit. The Cult of Groundhogism including tertiary members, numbers easily in the millions. Though as of yet has remained a non-threat and been allowed to stand despite clear cut heresy to the Church.

Buckwheat Honey Buckwheat Honey is an all-American form of honey. Most popular in northern states like New York and Ohio. It is one of the best varieties for making mead, and is excellent for wound treatment. It has a very strong flavor similar to Molasses. As its name implies it is made by bees with a lot of access to Buckwheat flowers.
Various photos of Bee Species Native to the Americas

Telling the Bees Telling the Bees, is an old Rural Custom of Europe that was carried over to America by settlers. It involved telling the bees about important happenings in day to day life, including births, marriages and deaths. At weddings cake and other offerings might be left for the bees, while with a death black cloth would be draped over the hive and a mournful tune may be hummed or sang. These various customs were said to be done to avoid the Hive leaving especially in regards to the death of their beekeeper, but it also may be a leftover tradition involving bees as messengers of the gods and of/to the dead. It also may be a way of insuring the bonding of the beekeeper to the collective consciousness of the hive, so as to retain the trust of the bees and continue the symbiotic relationship between man and insect.-TLK
The pedigree of honey Does not concern the bee; A clover, any time, to him Is aristocracy. -Emily Dickinson

Spirit of the Day #31 Agropelter The Agropelter is a spirit of American folklore, often portrayed as a monkey with long arms it is actually supposed to be closer to a goblin. The Agropelter is native to the Northwoods from Maine to Oregon, and is a member of the Fearsome Critters of Lumberjack Folklore. The Agropelter lives in trees and picks up dead branches and stones and hurls them at people, when a treetop or branch (or as Lumberjacks call them Widowmakers) comes out of nowhere in a forest and seems to head directly towards you that is the Agropelter. It supposedly likes to eat Hoot Owls and Woodpeckers. The items it throws can be thrown with the force of a Canon or handgun, making its aim rather deadly.

Spirit of the Day #28 Johnny Appleseed Johhny Appleseed AKA Appleseed John AKA John Chapman AKA The American Dionysus. Is a Historic Figure, American Folk Saint, and Spirit of the American Frontier and its many orchards. While in life he was a forest Hermit who communed with spirits, and planted forests worth of apple orchards, Johhny Appleseed passed into legend being spoken of as a Wildman and spirit, even said to have met Paul Bunyan and Babe the Big Blue Ox and healed the sick Ox with his medical abilities. He has a thick bushy beard, bearish build, ragged clothes if any, and wears a tin pot hat from which peers two piercing eyes, he is often depicted with children who he would often amuse by piercing his feet with red hot pokers, or with animals that live around and on his rather Wild build and bushy beard. He gained his epithet the American Dionysus due to most of his apples being Cider Apples, it is said when the Sky looks like Apple Blossoms that is Johnny planting trees across the sky.

Dark Watchers of the Santa Lucia Mountains (Folklore of California) Phantom-like shadow figures have been reported in the Santa Lucia Mountains since the European settlers were told the stories by the Indians. They are called Dark Watchers. Cave paintings exist depicting these beings. They are said to only appear at Twilight and disappear when the sun has completely vanished in the darkness of night overwhelms the Earth. To this day no one knows why the Dark Watchers appear, but still they remain...watching

Spirit of the Day #22 Tommyknocker Tommyknocker or originally known as Knockers, are Cornish, Welsh, and American mining spirits. It is described as a tiny man in mining clothes with bushy white whiskers. Some tales say the Knockers were malevolent and would cause knocking noises to cause a cave-in. However, other folklore implies they are the spirits or ghosts of dead miners who make the knocking noises to warn people of imminent cave ins. Resulting in some people giving them offerings and gifts as thanks for their protection. The "Knocking" was said to be the spirits mining, in America the name became Tommyknocker and the legend spread with the influx of Cornish Miners across the Western USA and Appalachia.

"For my own part I wish the bald eagle had not been chosen as the representative of our country. He is a bird of bad moral character. He does not get his living honestly. You may have seen him perched on some dead tree, where, too lazy to fish for himself, he watches the labour of the fishing hawk; and when that diligent bird has at length taken a fish, and is bearing it to his nest for the support of his mate and young ones, the bald eagle pursues him, and takes it from him. . . . the turkey is in comparison a much more respectable bird, and withal a true original native of America." -Benjamin Franklin

The Moon-Eyed People (Folklore of North Carolina) The remnants of ancient stone structures can be found in North Carolina's mountains (some in Georgia and Alabama as well). These structures are mostly man-made. It is unclear, to some, who built these structures, but according to the Cherokee, it was the Moon-eyed people. The moon-eyed people were said to be a race of people who lived in the southern Appalachians. They are very different in appearance from the Cherokee. The men had big bushy beards. Their skin was pure white and their hair was blonde or for some, almost as wide as their skin. It is believed they were unable to see during the day and they only came out at night. Their eyes were pale blue and glowed in the darkness. The most well known of the instructors is just near the NC border in Georgia. Fort Mountain, now a state park. Fort Mountain (pictured in the last slide) is a 850 ft long stone wall thought to have been constructed by the moon-eyed people for a battle between them and the Creek Nation, who felt the moon eyed people had no right to the land (some say it was actually the Cherokee who drove them out). The moon eyed people lost this battle and went to live in caves and underground. It is believed by many archaeologists that the moon-eyed people were actually European settlers who made contact with the Cherokee long before any others discovered this country. Their story has also matched up with the Welsh legend of Prince Madoc
