A pioneer and frontiersman, Daniel Boone's escapades made him one of the first folk heroes of America. 250 years ago, Boone led his scouting party through feral wilderness, uncrossable rivers, and treacherous mountainsides. It was a long and hard journey, but because of his determination, the land they treaded on, would soon become settled, and become what we now know as the state of Kentucky. Boone and his party, were the first frontiersman to settle beyond the borders of the 13 colonies. Today, you can walk through the Daniel Boone National Forest, and take the same paths that Boone, himself cleared. You can even find his initials on some of the trees. A fascinating and wonderful aspect of this land, is that the vast majority of the wilderness has been left untamed and unspoiled...just as Daniel Boone found it. Boone lived a long life (uncommon back then), and died peacefully in his sleep at the age of 85. I highly recommend reading more about him. Watch the movies, read the books. He was absolutely fascinating.

Father Time & Baby New Year Father Time is a folkloric deity and the personification of Time itself. He founds much of his origin in the deity Cronos and the Roman god Saturn who heavily synchronized with him in classical aristocratic Roman myth. Despite this Father Time is an entity within himself and often appears alongside other folkloric deities. Being depicted as a friend of the Grim Reaper and often using his scythe if he so chooses. He is also at times depicted with Santa Claus, implying a possible agreement regarding the Time Santa Claus uses to make his nighttime ride. The most notable however is the figure of Baby New Year (Identified by some as the Frankish god Lollus) who he often hands the dominion of the New Year over to when the year ends and he dies or retires. He is often depicted with a Scythe, Holly Wreathe, book, hourglass, and sometimes even wings. At the end of 2021 it is time for him to pass his Sash to Baby New Year and maybe go have drinks with Santa and Grim. Happy New Year.-TLK

Santa Claus Impersonators In America it is a common sight around Christmas to see Santa Claus around the town. Promoting charities, visiting children in the hospital, leading parades, and more. Santa is not only a symbol of the Holiday he is a symbol of the goodwill, kindness, and hope embodied in the Yuletide. Those who portray him often grow their beards out specifically to do so, dyeing their beards white and wearing the common red suit. Many take their role more seriously and pick up tailoring and leatherworking to make a more authentic Santa outfit. Oftentimes comforting children on their deathbed, or helping the children who come to them with their list (including several instances of beating up abusive parents after the child revealed their secret to Santa). Many of them have even stated they understand they are embodying a deity, much as Wild Man mumming customs like Krampus runs and the Mari Lwyd embody deities, so do those portraying Santa. Much as predecessors Father Christmas or Sinterklaas.-TLK

Popular American Yule Gifts Part 2: Action Figures Human shaped toys are among the oldest toys created from dolls to action figures. Yet this oft sought after toy has ancient origins and ties to the Christmas season. The creation of small toys in the shape of gods or heroes were a popular custom gift among Romans during Saturnalia. Many people claim that this was a replacement of Human Sacrifice... well I'm a little concerned if every power ranger or superhero I got as a little kid was my parents fighting back the urge to cut out my heart and give it to the sun... it was a toy that every boy and girl probably wanted of Hercules, Milo, Zeus or whoever their favorite mythical figure was, just the same as us with Marvel, Star Wars, and all other franchises tapping into this primal childhood interaction. Next time you give an action figure, remember we've been doing it for millennia. üòâ

Papa No√´l, The Cajun Santa Claus In Louisiana the Cajun's have a Santa Claus all their own, descended of the French-Acadian traditions of the settlers of the region, they have developed a figure known as Papa Noel. A Cajun Santa often dressed in traditional Cajun clothes or as a fur trapper. He rides in a traditional Cajun Canoe led by 8 alligators, one of which is female known as Nicolette, who is albino with growing green eyes to light the way. A tradition calls to light bonfire on Christmas eve to light the way for Papa Noel to find the houses of people, as he leaves his swamp to deliver presents to all the boys and girls. While Papa Noel still enjoys a kind of Cajun Sugar Cookies, he enjoys shellfish far more and had received a rather boisterous girth from his love of crawdads and other Louisiana seafood.

The Grinch's Ancient Origins? The Grinch is a famous Christmas character created by Dr. Seuss. Yet where did the lovable misanthropic Furry Green Man come from? While the Green color was merely a movie choice with the Grinch originally being black and white the idea of a "Hairy man" living on a mountain and being associated with Yuletide is actually an ancient tradition. Wildmen AKA Woodwose's are often seen living on Mountains (Rubezahl, Pan, The Orc) and are also associated with the end of the year and the fertile rebirth of the earth. Traditions involving the death of a bear or Wildman only to be symbolically reborn at the end of the mock battle or the next year is older than history. This is often done during the Yuletide. Sometimes the Wildman is a bear, but the Black and White Grinch is even inspired by European Wildman folklore, and when combined with Christmas fulfills an ancient archetype of the Hyperborean Consciousness.

Belsnickel, Santa, and American Mumming Belsnickel AKA Pelsnickel is a Wildman gift giver from German folklore. He arrived to America with the PA Dutch. They and other German immigrants from Eastern Canada to the mid-Atlantic US began to celebrate "Belsnickeling" a kind of American Mumming. The tradition largely died out in the area. mostly due to attacks by the NAACP and the East Coast upper class. Decrying the noisy celebrations and accusing the Belsnickel of being Blackface. The tradition of Belsnickeling continues to this day in both the PA Dutch and in the Eastern provinces of Canada. Belsnickel is considered one of if not the original origin of American Santa Claus, with the Name "Kris Kringle" being derived from Belsnickels gifts known as "Grisht-kindle". While Belsnickel is often translated as Nicholas in Furs, an obscure German word for elf may lead to his name being "Hairy Elf" which befits this rather burly origin of the "Jolly Old Elf".-TLK

‚ÄúThe Apotheosis of George Washington‚Äù, an etching from 1800-1802 by John James Barralet, part of the rising mythology of Washington's remembrance in early America. After his death in 1799 Mason Locke Weems sought to contribute to his legacy through writing a biography of the first president from 1800-1802. Corresponding to print man Matthew Carey in January 1800, Weems exclaimed, "Washington you know is gone! Millions are gaping to read something about him.... My plan! I give his history, sufficiently minute.... I then go on to show that his unparalleled rise and elevation were due to his Great Virtues."

Santa & The Hearth Out on his nighttime ride on Christmas Eve Santa is said to come down the Chimney and out the fire place, bringing gifts and treats to boys and girls all across the land. But why the Fireplace? Well the Fireplace or Hearth has always been a liminal space. A place where spirits and ancestors can communicate with us (Due to the flame and it being the heart of the home). As seen in the tale of Cinderella or when Corn Spirits are released in the flames. Santa may for the sake of storytelling come through the Chimney, he is actually calling back to this ancient tradition and travelling through the fireplace as a portal to the other realms "North Pole". Though he still finds himself covered in ash with a "blackened face" akin to the Cinderbiters and Wild Men of European customs. So need to worry if the fire is lit you do not risk burning him, he's coming through the flame not atop it.-TLK

Popular American Yule Gifts Part 1: Puppies A popular gift in America and across many of our lands for Yule is that of the dog, typically a puppy. This finds its origins oddly in myth, as The Wild Hunt would often leave a dog especially a black one in its puppy form with a family for a year. The Dog had to be treated well, and cared for, and probably taught to hunt. The family may be rewarded or punished accordingly, the dog will typically leave with the Wild Hunt next year. This also functions as a rite of passage. As a young child must train the dog, taking responsibility for it often teaching it to hunt. Learning many life lessons. If you choose to get a dog for your family this Yule, please do so responsibly as too many of them are abandoned soon after. If you receive one unexpectedly especially a black unknown breed. Best treat it well perhaps it was Uncle Frank, perhaps it was the Old Gods and they are watching. Either way it is a living thing and a friend to us for its entire life.

The Origins of Christmas Cookies One of the most well known and nostalgic holiday traditions is that of leaving out milk and cookies for Santa. This humble tradition is millennia old and has appeared in some form during Yuletide for as long as can be recorded. Many areas would leave out feasts for the dead, who would come to visit during Yuletide and consume the spirit of the food. Families would leave food out as offerings for a day sometimes a few and then consume it, as the spirits had had their fill at this point they would feast. Why Cookies? well this combines another common element of Yuletide traditions the creation of baked goods as offerings for deities and spirits. Such as the Sinterklaas Speculaas reminiscent of Fro or Wodan, or the Hot Cross buns made for Ostara. The combination of these two traditions resulted in the modern tradition of the leaving out of the offerings of both the special baked good and the food for the spirits (ancestors) in milk and cookies for a Jolly Old Elf.-TLK

The Origin of Santa's Elves Santa has numerous constant companions, Reindeer, Mrs. Claus, but most notable is his legion of elves. They make the toys, prep his sleigh, and live and work in the North pole. These Christmas Elves in much the same vein as Tomte are in fact the memory of the Ancestral spirits of the dead. Appearing around Yuletide to deliver gifts to their living relatives. In Sardinia this is most blatant as in some areas the tradition of the dead collecting and delivering gifts is stated plainly. Unlike the workshop elves of Santa's North Pole, the ghosts of the Sardinian people rise from the dead and simply steal (borrow forever without asking) the gifts from stores and bring them to their descendants. In this vein Santa behaves much the same as Wotan, Harlequin, Holda, and King Arthur in leading a host of the dead. But instead of the ancient Battle Hosts and Hunts, instead they work in the North Pole a land of mystery where souls may wander. Our ancestors do like to leave gifts for us.-TLK

‚ÄúWe have met the enemy and they are ours‚Ä¶‚Äù Oliver Hazard Perry's immortal words to Major General William Henry Harrison after the Battle of Lake Erie, 10 September 1813, "We have met the enemy and they are ours-- two ships, two brigs, one schooner and one sloop." The victory secured the Great Lakes region for the United States and ended the threat of invasion during the war of 1812.

Captain John Paul Jones, during the famous battle between Bonhomme Richard and Serapis on 23 September 1779 had the odds greatly against his favor, and it would seem that he was fated to be destined to Davy Jones‚Äô locker. It was apparent that some of Jones' men cried for surrender, but not Jones. Captain Richard Pearson of Serapis asked Jones if he had surrendered. Jones uttered the immortal words: "I have not yet begun to fight!" Further cementing his legendary command over US naval forces during the Revolutionary war, he went where no other desired to go, and led decisive victories in support of America‚Äôs quest for freedom. ‚ÄúI wish to have no Connection with any Ship that does not Sail fast for I intend to go in harm's way.‚Äù
Happy Thanksgiving Everyone have a good day and enjoy time with family, and remember what you are grateful for.

American Football American Football, also known as Gridiron or just Football is the most popular sport in America and is quintessentially American to the point the Superbowl is nearly a national holiday and Thanksgiving is often celebrated with the watching of a game or tossing around of the 'Pigskin'. Football diverged from the traditional Soccer Games of Europe in the late 1800's and the father of Football Walter Camp a Yale Coach is often credited with fleshing out the differences between the two sports. College football became increasingly popular spreading from the Midwest out. With Professional Football finding its origins in 1892. Football is slightly older than Thanksgiving as a national holiday and when Thanksgiving was chosen as the date for the College Football Championships the All-American Sport and the American Harvest/Hunting Festival were joined at the hip from then on.
Coin Toss by Norman Rockwell 1950

Thanksgiving Thanksgiving is an American Holiday, descended of traditional harvest and hunting festivals of Europe. As well as arguably some Bear cult ones as well. The First thanksgiving as it is often called was by no means the first merely being used as a way of trying to unite the country as the myth of the Pilgrims and the Indians came about during the Civil War, and it was around this time that Lincoln declared it a National Holiday. Though the harvest feast had been performed for centuries beforehand. Various foods have been added to the table over the years, the Turkey is referenced in New England Thanksgiving Cookbooks, Pumpkin Pie was much the same, Macy's Parade started in the 1920's and Football and Thanksgiving have been joined at the hip for over a hundred years. This Holiday is about Family and Gratitude and should we treasured regardless of the nonsense spread about it by certain people in the modern day.

Ragamuffin Day Ragamuffin day was a nickname given to Thanksgiving as many Irish-Americans would dress up as devils, hobos, homeless, Indians, Blacks, and even cross dress and go door to door as amateur beggars. They would also perform traditional Irish Music while they did so. This was a continuation of ancient Mumming traditions from Europe. This version of the Holiday has since faded and been replaced with an annual Ragamuffin Parade in New York. It is one of the many examples of Mumming traditions that were in America but faded and became boiled down to Trick or Treating and Caroling in the modern day but was once far more widespread. The tradition was also celebrated with bonfires, mince pies, and many other traditions that have fed into modern Holidays.

This video brings up some interesting points, personally I believe that the true "American Mythology" are the stories of our heroes, gods, and ancestors that built this new nation. Yet, I cannot deny that in the modern day Superheroes are probably the closest analogue to ancient Greek mythology in America, with Pulp heroes preceding and often "Inspiring" them they would fit as the "Titans" the Superheroes are even ageless and their powers defy mortal understanding, and like our gods they die in tales but return fulfilling a similar psychological need that we have stemming from our collective unconcious. We do have tales of Thor, Finn McCool, and many other European gods that are unique to America, as our gods followed us where we went. But we also have our legends of Johnny Appleseed, Paul Bunyan, Davy Crockett, and many more. Regardless this was an interesting video on American mythic outlooks and their modern day origins. https://youtu.be/0d45i_PjUbU

‚ÄúIf you‚Äôre going to wear a cowboy hat, you‚Äôre going to have to go all the way. You should have livestock around you, settle all of your disputes with a pistol, and ride a horse absolutely everywhere.‚Äù -Tom Segura.

With the threat of troubling cattle rustlers and Indian war parties, working days and nights of eighteen hours in the saddle was expected and this is where the lore of the trail is born. Old Wild West legends develop into sharper focus, as the trail-weary cowhands plunge into the excitement of the towns along the drive‚Ä¶ Dodge, Ogallala, French Ford, Tombstone, with their monte games, saloons, clothing stores, parlors, and sudden shootouts. Legendary men such as Billy the Kid (Henry McCarty), Pat Garrett, Butch Cassidy (Robert Leroy Parker), Jesse James, Wild Bill (James Butler Hickok), Buffalo Bill (William Frederick Cody), and John Henry ‚ÄúDoc‚Äù Holliday, were trail blazers in establishing the iconic tough men of the West. In ballads, songs, poems and in cinema, the cowboy becomes mythical, encapsulated in legendary tales contained in the folklore stories that lift them up in an indomitable light.

The legend of the Cowboy The cowboy as a figure in the American folklore scene comes into view directly after and as a result of the Civil War. While Texas ranchers were off fighting for the Confederacy from 1861 to 1865, the wives and children looked after the cattle, branded the calves, raised the crops and tended the farm. When the Texans returned home, they found their homesteads filled with cattle sleek, and robust from grazing on pastures where buffalo no longer roamed, but additionally no local market for the beef. The cowboys had tended cattle and continued to ride the range, achieving great renown for difficult and challenging migrations of livestock. There were difficult fords to cross where steer got bogged down in quicksand, dry areas to test man and beast to their limits, and blind stampedes that threaten to dissolve the herd, scattering them to the four winds.

‚ÄúWell, I walk tall into varmint and Indian, it‚Äôs a way I‚Äôve got, and it comes as natural as grinning to a hyena. I‚Äôm a regular tornado, tough as a hickory withe, long winded as a nor‚Äô-wester. I can strike a blow like a falling tree, and every lick makes a gap in the crowd that lets in an acre of sunshine. Whew boys!‚Äù Mike Fink ‚ÄúThe Big Bear of Arkansas‚Äù to his fellow keelboatmen of The half-horse, half-alligator breed

Mike Fink, the Keelboatman Not as well known as Paul Bunyan, Pecos Bill, or Joe Magarac, Mike Fink is a hard man who embodied the salty, seaworthy mariner folk hero in such a way that has not been seen since Old Stormalong. He was born of Scotch-Irish descent, although claims have been made him belonging to the stock of the Pennsylvania Dutch. In his early youth he served as a scout and Indian fighter int the fiercely contested region around Fort Pitt, described as ‚Äúthe gateway to the west‚Äù, and a key British fortification during the French and Indian War in 1753. The hero of a hundred fights, and the leader in a thousand daring adventures. His name is still remembered among the whole of Ohio as a man who excelled his fellows in every thing‚Äîparticularly in his skill with a rifle, which was acknowledged to be unsurpassed. He was the tallest, strongest, longest winded fellow around, and carried his rifle which made him legendary as the William Tell of marksmen on land.

The same is true for beliefs concerning health, from folk medicine to childbirth/pregnancy folklore. Efforts such as dowsing, divination, clairvoyance, and fortune-telling, all rely on folk beliefs as a method of incorporating lessons of conduct and consequence. Beloved figures of holiday lore, like Santa Claus, and the Easter Bunny, have roots in an older belief system carried over by European immigrants seeking a new opportunity, yet holding onto tradition and their own unique culture. From the Scots, Slavs, Irish, Germans, Italians, and other descendants of men and women that traversed the savage seas in search of opportunity we find that our similarities are too great to ignore as diasporan descendants of Europa.

Folkloric Americana Folk beliefs are convictions that are held and passed on by ordinary people like you and me, which encompass every aspect of American life. Most folk narratives are predicated on some ideas that are held in common between the listeners, and these beliefs generally concern what is true, right, natural, honorable, fortunate, beautiful, or ideal. It is in this belief structure that contribution to the creation of culture is found. The many characteristics of popular folk beliefs include: Animals, birth, infancy, childhood, cosmic pheomena, seasons, death and funeral customs, economic and social interaction, fishing and hunting, home and hearth, folk medicine, love, courtship and marriage, horticulture, travel, weather, witchcraft, and the supernatural.

Atlas by Lee Lawrie 1937 The Atlas Statue in Rockefeller Center, New York City is 45 feet tall though only 15 is Atlas himself. The statue is done in the Art Deco Style and has become something of a pop culture icon appearing in the TV show 30 Rock, and is directly associated with Ayn Rand's novel Atlas Shrugged.

Mt. Horeb, Wisconsin is nicknamed "The Troll Capitol of the World" the town takes pride in its Norwegian heritage with its famous "Trollway". The town is covered in statues of trolls in various situations from watering flowers to backpacking to giving away the key to the city. Many of the businesses in the town take their name from the Scandinavian spirits and there is even a traditional Troll costume that is often paraded around town as the mascot Jorgen.

"The legend lives on from the Chippewa on down Of the big lake they called Gitche Gumee The lake, it is said, never gives up her dead When the skies of November turn gloomy‚Äù T'was the witch of November come stealin'" (Gordon Lightfoot)

Joe Magarac Joe Magarac is an American folk hero and arguably deity of manufacturing and metalworking. He was born of mountain ore during a storm. He was known for being tireless and hard working to the point his home was his station in the steel mill and his name "Magarac" translated to Jackass and referred to his extreme stubbornness and endless work ethic, molding steel beams with his bare hands. When he was made of flesh molten steel poured across him but instead of killing him the metal loved him so that it replaced his flesh making him a man of metal, though others hold him as made of metal from the start. He once fell in love with a woman with hair the color of fire and won her hand in a contest of strength but realizing her heart belonged to another Joe gave her up. When Joe's Mill was soon to shut down, Joe went into action. He ordered himself melted down into the steel they used. His spirit inundated the steel of America, blessing it and Joe became the Spirit of American Steel.

On this date in 1775, the United States Marine Corps was birthed in a Philadelphia bar called Tun Tavern. Sadly, all that remains of the historic birthplace is a marker where Tun Tavern once sat. Its original site near the waterfront is now occupied by Interstate 95. The Tavern had developed a reputation for fine beers in Philadelphia and held the reputation for over a century. Its name is derived from the old English word "Tun" meaning measured cask, barrel, or keg of beer. On November 10, 1775, Robert Mullan, the owner of the Tavern and son of Peggy Mullan, was commissioned by an act of Congress to raise the first two battalions of Marines, under the leadership of Samuel Nicholas, the first appointed Commandant of the Continental Marines. Each year on November 10th, Marines worldwide toast the Marine's birthplace on the most significant date in the history of the USMC.

Hobo Signs During the Great Depression millions were out of work and forced to travel as Nomads seeking work, these were the Hobos as opposed to Bums and tramps. Hundreds of Thousands of these workers were teenagers and the life was harsh, over time a language was constructed to help aid other Hobos who were new to an area, this Hobo Code would be carved to allow people to know what they were walking into, from kind folk who would help to areas where they might be killed, places with work, places without, dogs, cats, bread and even medical treatment. This language of Hieroglyphs and Pictographs was invaluable as it allowed even the completely illiterate to discover where they could go for what they needed as well as avoid potentially lethal situations.

url_description: Harry 'Haywire' McClintock wrote his first song, the story of "Big Rock Candy Mountain." around the turn of the last century which was based on fairy tales he had heard growing up, conjuring up images of houses built out of sweet cakes and candy. In this visual adaptation a scruffy old hobo brings us on a journey around this wonderfully lazy place where hand-outs grow on bushes and you can sleep out every night. With beautifully rendered backgrounds and silky smooth animation the Big Rock Candy Mountain is something anybody of any age will enjoy.

cleaned_message: Big Rock Candy Mountain The Big Rock Candy Mountain's is a Hobo Utopia from American Folklore, it was a land of ease, where power was inverted and the Hobo could harvest handouts from bushes and you could "Sleep out Every Night" the land is made of candy, lemonade, entire lakes of stew, and "little streams of alcohol come streaming down the rocks". This Hobo paradise inspired the popular song of the same name, and is part of the broader elements of American folklore fulfilling a similar role to the land of Cockaigne which was a Medieval Peasant Utopia.

In the Wild West, the lawmen tended to be former Union Army and the outlaws, former Confederates: James Gang, Doc Holiday. Although Doc dabbled in law enforcement. Lady Liberty Lady Liberty also known as Columbia is the goddess of America, and is the continuation or successor of Libertas who is depicted in the statue of Liberty. America is even known as the Land of Liberty and her people are known as the Sons and Daughters of Liberty. With America functionally being a nation devoted to this relatively minor Roman goddess. While she was eventually displaced by Uncle Sam several myths of her arose, including visiting a vision of the future of America upon Washington. She functioned as a goddess of War and protection and is depicted in the mural in the Capitol "The Apotheosis of Washington" as fighting off the enemies of Liberty and America. An example of the heathen origins of the American nation. -TLK

Teddy Roosevelt was an avid hunter but when he was given a chained bear to hunt he refused to do so. This story and the subsequent political cartoons spawned the now famous "Teddy" Bear simultaneously in America and Germany. While stuffed bears are fairly old, the name is a direct reference to TR.

The statue ‚ÄúWashington Enthroned‚Äù is modeled after Phidias‚Äô great statue of Zeus Olympios, one of the seven wonders of the ancient world. As a member of the Fearsome Critters folklore family of animals, the hoop snake is a creature from the folklore of lumberjacks and forest workers, especially in the woodland areas of Wisconsin and Minnesota. The Hoop Snake is described as a highly colorful snake that has the ability to move swiftly by taking its tail in its mouth and propel itself by rolling like a hoop! It is a highly poisonous, predatory reptile than can launch itself at its prey at great speed, but humans are able to outwit it and escape by jumping through the center of its hoop, confusing it long enough as it goes by, for it can‚Äôt turn around fast enough to give chase.
Have a Jolly Halloween!

Popular American Halloween Costumes Part 6: Clowns Clowns are a popular Halloween costume, often being joined with the tramp/hobo costume. Though Monster clowns have become increasingly popular with the show and film of Steven King's "It". Though Clowns have been scary before featuring in many horror movies, and a staple of Halloween masks for decades. There were also the 2016 Clown Incidents, where many creepy clowns seem to appear in the middle of the street at night and in forests, scaring the willies out of people. The Clown actually is a very old tradition in Europe and even ties back into the God Harlequin, as well as the traditions of the Comedia del Arte, and even Greek theatre. Harlequin became the spirit of the theatre and his visage and similar stock characters became used for many clowns, mimes, and other performers. The imagery also fed into Jesters who doubled as advisers to the king, their trademark hat actually featured horns similar to Ostara the Moon goddess, and many wildmen gods.

While the Pumpkin gets all the love, the Apple was also an important symbol of Halloween along with other Tubers and nuts that formed the Fall harvest. Apples reach back to ancient times and the Apple has been a symbol of fertility, love, and the sun for quite a while. Many of the traditions involving "Apple Bobbing" tie into traditions of scrying for ones spouse, some women would carve their initials on the apple and see if a suitor would bite theirs out of the tub. If it took too many tries the romance likely wouldn't work out. Others believe that as both Water and Apples are symbols of the faerie realm, bobbing for apples increases your chance of seeing a Faerie. Apples were so popular that parts of Canada did not always say "Trick or Treat" but instead would say "Halloween Apples" as they went door to door, and those candy apples, well they were a tasty treat invented at the turn of the 1900's. -TLK
The Beauty of Vermont in Fall
A Paul Bunyan Illustration by Renee Graef

Popular American Halloween Costumes Part 5: The Hobo While American Folklore is replete with hobo Folktales, especially from the Great Depression, and numerous people who wandered around much akin to a hobo. Tales of Big Rock Candy Mountain, or the Wise Old Hobo riding the rails. This costume is in fact a callback to two practices. One is the Wise Old Hermit of pagan times that existed in the woods living as bears, wolves, and other wild animals. Much like Johnny Appleseed. They also blacken their face from "Riding the rails" in so doing calling back to the darkened face of those who embody the dead, one could even argue a symbolic nature of trains coming and going along the road to the living and the dead much like the Carriages and Carts of the gods. Hobo's are also often shown to be storytellers, a potential call back to the bard. While the Hobo has largely fallen out of favor, and has gathered a bad name in the modern day, the role and individuals who lived it were an integral part of America.
Some of the Classic posters for the Universal Pictures Monster Movie Series From the 1930's-1940's

Freak Shows Freak shows arose in the Victorian Age though it is a much older tradition. With people who have physical oddities often being shown off to the amazement of those around them. Though this has resulted in abuse at times, it was actually often a way for them to pull themselves up and many were well spoken and educated. For our people it is actually a form of wonder, we are amazed that such people exist, often in real life fighting back the urge to ask them a myriad of questions, believing it to be rude. The Lion Faced man for instance spoke 5 languages and would often have conversations with his audience and retired in his 30's. In an odd way it reminds us of a physical manifestation of our spirits the Wildmen and Fey. A magical experience. With some interviews with modern members of freak shows realizing many people do not hate or feel disgust of them but are instead fascinated but worry they cannot approach, something they realized after joining. They are not hated but fascinating. -TLK
Big World By William Alther

The Addams Family are now Pop Culture Icons, but they began as a New Yorker Comic Strip written by Charles Addams, usually taking a Macabre spin on everyday American Family Life. The Addams family captures the feel of Halloween as they are all about Family the living and the dead, while also having quite a fascination with the Macabre. They were not named until the TV series from the 60's before then being generally known by their appearance.

Popular American Halloween Costumes Part 4: Vampires Vampires and similar creatures are a staple of European folklore. Though their name and core mythology comes from Eastern Europe, they have been influenced by many different creatures, legends, historical figures, and fiction writers. Originally the core legend of a vampire had it as a soul or astral projection of the vampire's corpse, while the body never left the grave. Others would have the ability to change size coming from a tiny opening in their place of burial and returning through the same small opening. Traditionally beheading, sticking a clove of garlic in its mouth, and staking the corpse to the coffin and maybe dismemberment and burning on top of it were used to kill a Vampire. Which was often thought to be the cause of illness and death upon the village making more and more people into vampires. The idea of sunlight as a weakness was introduced in Nosferatu. In America a brief Vampire craze was started due to the spread of Tuberculosis.
Drawing of Cthulu by H.P. Lovecraft
Illustration for Edgar Allen Poe's poem Lenore by Henry Sandham 1886

These Vampire Hunting kits were purchased by wealthy Americans headed to Eastern Europe (Transylvania which is now Romania) Travelers would bring back horror stories of Vampires with them from their trips.

His attacks on British ships were often sudden and sometimes bloody. The vision of a swarthy scalawag persisted even to the writings of Rudyard Kipling a century later. He was serious about his honor and his duties and was a harsh military leader, but was also surprisingly sociable. He was a prolific poem and letter writer, spoke some French, and though unmarried, was involved in many romances. Above all, no one questioned his daring.

Born John Paul on 6 July 1747, in Kirkcudbright, Scotland, John Paul Jones entered the British merchant marine at the young age of 12 and went to sea for the first time as a cabin boy. He had a name change after he was appointed ship‚Äôs master in of a slaver brigatine 1769. In 1773, he killed the leader of his mutinous crew in self-defense at Tobago, in the West Indies and to avoid trial, he fled to Virginia and was considered a fugitive by the British. According to some historians, Jones remained legendary as much for his actions as for his personality. British chapbooks, an early form of dime novels, pictured him as a ruthless marauding pirate similar to Blackbeard.

John Paul Jones The treasure ships carrying the wealth of the New World to Spain inspired an explosion in piracy in the so-called Spanish Main in the sixteenth century. This was the era of swashbuckling privateers, buccaneers and English sea dogs, whose adventures became the stuff of legend. American privateers such as John Paul Jones rose to fame around the time of the American Revolution and the War of 1812, with valorous exploits that cemented his name in the annals of history.

Popular American Halloween Costumes Part 3: Werewolves The Werewolf is one of the most famous and widespread creatures of European mythology. While some may argue King Lycaon is the first Werewolf given his transformation into a wolf by Zeus, other figures can lay claim to quite a bit of Werewolf mythology. For example a form of the Berserk known as Ulfhednar took the wolf as totem animal. A Berserk being a pre-Christian sort of battle trance. While others use the fear of the werewolf to cover up their own crimes saying the devil gave them a belt that allowed them to turn into a wolf and kill. Pagan examples exist such as the Celtic Werewolf Warriors that were supposedly paid in babies to eat (actually replenishing numbers with adoption). Or the importance of Werewolves among the Balts, where they are depicted facing off against crusaders and as "Hounds of heaven". Werewolves were conflated with "Lunacy" which is why the full moon and the Silver bullet is often traced to the Beast of Gevaudan.

From the listless repose of the place, and the peculiar character of its inhabitants, who are descendants from the original Dutch settlers, this sequestered glen has long been known by name of Sleepy Hollow ... A drowsy, dreamy influence seems to hang over the land, and to pervade the very atmosphere. Washington Irving, "The Legend of Sleepy Hollow"
An 18 Foot Tall statue in Sleepy Hollow, New York of The Headless Horseman pursuing Ichabod Crane by Artist Linda Perlmutter
The Headless Horseman Pursuing Ichabod Crane by John Quidor

Popular American Halloween Costumes Part 2: Witches Witches are simply but the sum total of the mythology and demonization of the wise women and men of Europe. Many good woman have lost their lives as a result of demonization of wise woman who kept pagan customs, though many men also died defending said women or were burned alongside them as werewolves or witches. They were herbalists, priestesses, healers, matriarchs who kept the old ways. With their murders much was lost of our old ways. Though that important note out of the way I am here to discuss the origin of the current incarnation of the witch. The Hat, it likely arose out of the conflation of the alewives hat with witches due to herbalism, many ‚Äúeye of newt‚Äù ingredients were actually plant nicknames. The cauldron likely had to do with brewing remedies, the broomsticks tree of life branches or distaffs. The black cat is likely due to the accusation of familiars taking the shape of pet The three witches motif seems to tie into the Norns.
Young Sammy Six Guns by John Phillip Falter 1957

The colossal statue of the Roman god Vulcan on Red Mountain, in Birmingham, Alabama is the largest cast iron statue in the world, and the city‚Äôs symbol. Cast from local iron in 1904, Vulcan has carefully watched over the state‚Äôs largest city for over 100 years atop Red Mountain. Why Vulcan? Because he represents, and is the god of fire, the steelworker, and the ore miner, which is very much in tune with the hard-working, industrious American spirit.

Popular American Halloween Costumes Part 1: Ghosts The common bedsheet ghost is a rather recent concept, originally ghosts were depicted as wearing the clothes they had when they died but over time artists began to depict ghosts as being covered in their ‚ÄúBurial shroud‚Äù creating the modern image of the white sheet ghost we all know and love/hate. The idea of spirits and ghosts coming to our aid or coming to harm is rather old this boon or bane of spirits is a very old and deeply important custom to Europeans. Especially in the coming season when the veil is thin, as Halloween approaches and our ancestors and all sorts of ghosts, ghouls, and goblins run amok. Oh and who can forget a good old haunted house, Recall your ancestors light a jack‚Äôo lantern as a totem of protection and a beacon to the spirits of the ancestors, wear a costume so they know they are welcome. There is not much to fear if your dearly departed know where to find you as the parade of spirits and wild hunt ride across the sky.

While largely fallen out of favor, the Halloween feast is a big part of the tradition. Mince meat pies, berries, nuts, meat, baked breads and sweets. The food involved is not only for the living but also the dead, with traditional sweets and treats given out on Halloween being homemade, though these have fallen out of fashion as time has gone on, and negative press has been made to keep people from keeping to tradition. The importance of the homemade warm food is key, as the spirits of the dead are meant to consume the spirit of the food, not the food itself. With the steam of fresh baked bread, meat, etc being what they primarily feast off. Though they are likely to show up to your door for Tricks or Treat hidden among Iron Man and the Hufflepuffs.-TLK

Mary Hays, most commonly associated with the legend of "Molly Pitcher" at the Battle of Monmouth, was born on this day in 1754. Hays served with her husband‚Äôs cannon crew and was awarded a pension for her service in 1822. Art: Molly Pitcher, Battle of Monmouth, 1778 by Don Troiani

Jack O' Lanterns Is a form of Spirit Lantern or Will-o-the-wisp. They use an old European word "jack" that means spirit. They are said to attract helpful spirits and repel malicious ones. The tradition of carving them with pumpkins rather than Turnips is uniquely American, with it likely originating in folk customs from Celtic immigrants bringing traditions of Samhain to a new country. In 1866 the tradition of Pumpkin carving was mentioned as being practiced Enmasse in the city of Ontario, since it spread North from America this indicates it was much older and the tradition may even predate the formation of the USA. "The old time custom of keeping up Hallowe'en was not forgotten last night by the youngsters of the city. They had their maskings and their merry-makings, and perambulated the streets after dark in a way which was no doubt amusing to themselves. There was a great sacrifice of pumpkins from which to make transparent heads and face, lighted up by the unfailing two inches of tallow candle."

The Jersey Devil The Jersey Devil is a famous monster from New Jersey Folklore that prowls the pine barrens. He serves as a boogeyman to the children of New Jersey, his most famous origin story is that he was the 13th Child of the Leed's Family and was cursed for being a burden, born human but quickly morphing into the chimera monster that haunts the woods today. The Jersey Devil emits blood curdling screams and can spit fire, for all intents and purposes he is a dragon, with similar beasts appearing in Medieval European illustrations. The Jersey Devil also possesses the ability to speak and is said to be able to shapeshift.

Hodag Hodags are one of if not the most fearsome critter of the Northwoods. Even going toe to toe with Paul Bunyan at times, being a large part of his early tales. The lore of the creature is most prominent in Rhinelander, Wisconsin. Where The Hodag lends its name to many businesses and appears as mascots and statues across the town. The Hodag is sometimes described as a relic of the Dinosaur age while others argue it is the transmogrified soul of oxen that became lost in the woods. While in a complete break from the typical Hodag, the creature is sometimes described as a giant killer chicken. A Hodag's tears are said to make the worlds best lemonade, sadly Hodags never cry.

Martha Jane Cannary-Burke, also known as "Calamity Jane" was well known for her extraordinary skills and aptitude for horse riding and handling a gun. Her escapades brought her in the company of the legendary WIld Bill Hickock. Her image was unconventional for the era, as she was one of a kind. Her nickname ‚Äúcalamity‚Äù comes from her contention of the promise of calamity for any suitors to come her way. Calamity Jane is an important figure in the American folklore of westward expansion, etching her name in national folklore.

Whenever he got an itch, Babe the Blue Ox had to find a cliff to rub against, 'cause whenever he tried to rub against a tree it fell over and begged for mercy. To whet his appetite, Babe would chew up thirty bales of hay, wire and all. It took six men with picaroons to get all the wire out of Babe's teeth after his morning snack. Right after that he'd eat a ton of grain for lunch and then come pestering around the cook - Sourdough Sam - begging for another snack. Paul also used Babe the Blue Ox to pull the heavy tank wagon which was used to coat the newly-straightened lumber roads with ice in the winter, until one day the tank sprang a leak that trickled south and became the Mississippi River. After that, Babe stuck to hauling logs. Only he hated working in the summertime, so Paul had to paint the logging roads white after the spring thaw so that Babe would keep working through the summer.

Paul Bunyan went out walking in the woods one day during that Winter of the Blue Snow. He was knee-deep in blue snow when he heard a funny sound between a bleat and a snort. Looking down, he saw a teeny-tiny baby blue ox jest a hopping about in the snow and snorting with rage on account of he was too short to see over the drifts. Paul Bunyan laughed when he saw the spunky little critter and took the little blue mite home with him. He warmed the little ox up by the fire and the little fellow fluffed up and dried out, but he remained as blue as the snow that had stained him in the first place. So Paul named him Babe the Blue Ox.
‚ÄúBlackbeard in smoke and flame‚Äù By Frank E. Schoonover

Beneath this fair tree, like the patriarchs of old, Their bread in contentment they ate, Unvexed with the troubles of silver or gold, The cares of the grand and the great. With timber and tar they Old England supplied, And supported her power on the sea: Her battles they fought, without getting a groat, For the honor of Liberty Tree. But hear, O ye swains ('tis a tale most profane), How all the tyrannical powers, Kings, Commons, and Lords, are uniting amain To cut down this guardian of ours. From the East to the West blow the trumpet to arms, Thro' the land let the sound of it flee : Let the far and the near all unite with a cheer, In defense of our Liberty Tree.

The Liberty Tree by Thomas Paine In a chariot of light, from the regions of day, The Goddess of Liberty came, Ten thousand celestials directed her way, And hither conducted the dame. A fair budding branch from the gardens above, Where millions with millions agree, She brought in her hand as a pledge of her love, And the plant she named Liberty Tree. The celestial exotic stuck deep in the ground, Like a native it flourished and bore; The fame of its fruit drew the nations around, To seek out this peaceable shore. Unmindful of names or distinctions they came, For freemen like brothers agree; With one spirit endued, they one friendship pursued, And their temple was Liberty Tree.
Yosemite Valley Albert Bierstadt (1830-1902), oil on canvas
Benjamin Franklin Drawing Electricity from the Sky by Benjamin West 1816
Cranberry Bog, Ocean County, New Jersey - Pickers at Work. 1877 Artist Unknown
Illustrations from the Wizard of Oz by William Wallace Denslow

"Who planted this old apple-tree?" The children of that distant day Thus to some aged man shall say; And, gazing on its mossy stem, The gray-haired man shall answer them: "A poet of the land was he, Born in the rude but good old times; 'T is said he made some quaint old rhymes On planting the apple-tree."

Each year shall give this apple-tree A broader flush of roseate bloom, A deeper maze of verdurous gloom, And loosen, when the frost-clouds lower, The crisp brown leaves in thicker shower; The years shall come and pass, but we Shall hear no longer, where we lie, The summer's songs, the autumn's sigh, In the boughs of the apple-tree. And time shall waste this apple-tree. Oh, when its aged branches throw Thin shadows on the ground below, Shall fraud and force and iron will Oppress the weak and helpless still? What shall the tasks of mercy be, Amid the toils, the strifes, the tears Of those who live when length of years Is wasting this little apple-tree?

And when, above this apple-tree, The winter stars are quivering bright, And winds go howling through the night, Girls, whose young eyes o'erflow with mirth, Shall peel its fruit by cottage-hearth, And guests in prouder homes shall see, Heaped with the grape of Cintra's vine And golden orange of the line, The fruit of the apple-tree. The fruitage of this apple-tree Winds and our flag of stripe and star Shall bear to coasts that lie afar, Where men shall wonder at the view, And ask in what fair groves they grew; And sojourners beyond the sea Shall think of childhood's careless day And long, long hours of summer play, In the shade of the apple-tree.

What plant we in this apple-tree? Sweets for a hundred flowery springs To load the May-wind's restless wings, When, from the orchard row, he pours Its fragrance through our open doors; A world of blossoms for the bee, Flowers for the sick girl's silent room, For the glad infant sprigs of bloom, We plant with the apple-tree. What plant we in this apple-tree! Fruits that shall swell in sunny June, And redden in the August noon, And drop, when gentle airs come by, That fan the blue September sky, While children come, with cries of glee, And seek them where the fragrant grass Betrays their bed to those who pass, At the foot of the apple-tree. (Cont.)

The Planting of the Apple-Tree by William Cullen Bryant Come, let us plant the apple-tree. Cleave the tough greensward with the spade; Wide let its hollow bed be made; There gently lay the roots, and there Sift the dark mould with kindly care, And press it o'er them tenderly, As, round the sleeping infant's feet, We softly fold the cradle sheet; So plant we the apple-tree. What plant we in this apple-tree? Buds, which the breath of summer days Shall lengthen into leafy sprays; Boughs where the thrush, with crimson breast, Shall haunt and sing and hide her nest; We plant, upon the sunny lea, A shadow for the noontide hour, A shelter from the summer shower, When we plant the apple-tree. (Cont.)

Johnny Appleseed is a hero of American Folklore. While often depicted in modern media as spindly and pacifistic, he was most certainly not. Described as being as strong as Paul Bunyan, and even interacting with the Legendary Lumberjack when he helped heal Babe when the Ox was ill. He roamed across the wilds planting Apple Trees (mostly Cider) earning him the nickname The American Dionysus. Johnny would've been fierce to behold, a shaggy beard and wooly body of immense strength, wise piercing eyes staring out from below his shaggy hair and tin pot hat. He communed with spirits and did superhuman feats such as walking across flame and ice barefoot. He was said to have a spirit bride and be a friend to the animals with a wolf as companion. His Holidays are around the two Equinoxes which coincide with his birth and death. He effectively fulfills a Hermit Wildman/Green Man Archetype within American Folklore. After his death he continued to plant trees both in spirit and in careful planting.-TLK

The Thomas Jefferson Gardens in Jefferson, IA are effectively a Shrine to Thomas Jefferson. Complete with a statue of the president holding the Declaration of Independence. An Outdoor Museum, Educational Garden, and a miniature library shaped like Monticello are all on the grounds. It is open to the public.

Few people know that the beloved cartoon Popeye actually existed in real life. The man‚Äôs name was Frank 'Rocky' Fiegel, born in Poland, he emigrated with his family to America where in 1887 he joined the US Navy. When Popeye's creator met him, he was a retired sailor contracted by Wiebusch‚Äôs tavern in Chester, Illinois, as security and a bouncer. He had a reputation as a brawler, from which he developed a deformed eye (‚ÄúPop-eye‚Äù). His feats of strength were in full display in so many fights that he became a local legend. He always smoked his pipe, so he spoke only with one side of his mouth. When children were around he positioned his pipe in the corner of his mouth and told of the antics of his youth, often boasting of his physical strength and loudly proclaiming that spinach is the food that makes him invincible.

The Mothman Mothman is a Cryptid or Spirit from Point Pleasant, West Virginia. He appeared during the time span of 1966-1967. He is described as having large wings and glowing red eyes. He is often thought to be a Sandhill crane or other bird. However, aside from the usual legends of flying over cars and scaring a passerby the Mothman is also connected to the deaths of 46 people as he was spotted and connected to the Silver Bridge Collapse in 1967. After this the Mothman became more associated with being an omen of destruction or misfortune, perhaps a spirit who feasts on fear?! In typical American Fashion the Mothman is often considered either a Nuclear Mutant or an Alien. As such the Men in Black ended up being mixed into the story somehow.

Ever Forward It was first a distant, restless hope that the future lay in a magic land off to the west that European dreamers set their sights. Once that land was found, it drew people to it like a magnet. There was an innate pull that literally drove a hopeful people westward, taking them across treacherous mountain passes, through dangerous plains and desert, facing both horrors known and unknown. It was, at times, relishing the challenge of perseverance over incredible obstacles that stood in their way. And we are the result of this relentless pursuance of a chance to be bold and live free. cleaned_message: Pecos Bill Pecos Bill is an American Folk Hero of the Old West and especially Texas. He was the inventor of the Rodeo, the digger of the Grand Canyon and Rio Grande, the bringer of rain, the rider of tornados, among many other feats. He was also the Original Cowboy, inventing the term and occupation. He had a rattlesnake for a lasso, a Mountain Lion and the Grizzly Bear for mounts on the former he fought a giant snake. Eventually he teamed up with his famous Horse "Widow-Maker" and fell in love with his tragic sweetheart "Slue Foot Sue".

EXPOSURE TO NATURE PURIFIES THE SPIRIT t.me/TheWotanNetwork - t.me/Stephen_A_McNallen - t.me/Wotan_Network_Activity - wotannetwork@gmail.com It happens literally every time. I'm stressed, or distracted, or bored...I drive down to the bottom of the hill on which I live, and park the car. I note the time, and get out of the vehicle. I start walking. Yes, these are paved roads, and homes are dotted here and there, but mostly what I see are trees - short ones, tall ones, oaks, pines. Some are mossy, some are not. Usually I see some deer, and of course the ubiquitous squirrels. Two horses are in a corral; sometimes they come over to see me but mostly they are just doing horse stuff. And then it hits me. My stress is gone. I am surrounded by beauty. I am filled with joy. I look at the blue sky and the puffy clouds, and it dawns on me: Within the field of my vision, there is (probably) more organic life than on all the other planets in our Solar System, combined. And then, unfailingly, I realize just how unspeakably beautiful it all is...and a sense of the holy, the transcendent, fills my consciousness. I am deeply, unspeakably, grateful. "Thank you for this day of life", I say aloud, and a line from a story written by Robert Heinlein ("The dean of science fiction writers") crosses my mind and escapes my lips, words set in a poem for a spacefaring future..."We pray for one last landing on the globe that gave us birth...Let us rest our eyes on the fleecy skies, and the cool green hills of Earth..." Nature. Beauty. Awareness and inspiration. Some who seek the higher realms of being - Jane Dixon, author of Biology of Kundalini: Exploring the Fire of Life, for example - points out that our environment, and especially nature, and beauty, and all which stirs the human soul, is an important factor in producing a deep and lasting spiritual experience. I think she is right....Hail Wotan, and hail our Awakening! P.S. I post to all my media outlets on Monday, Wednesday, and Friday. If there are schedule disruptions, I will still aim for three posts a week. P.P.S. The Spear - the "field manual" for Wotan Network - may be ordered from our store at wotannetwork.com. If that does not work for you, contact me at the wolfagemedia@gmail.com address. My earlier book, Asatru, A Native European Spirituality is also available along with other, smaller works.

IN THIS HOLY YULETIDE SEASON...BECOME MORE THAN YOU ARE! Yuletide is, and always has been, the holy season of the Scandinavians and their Germanic cousins everywhere. It is a time loaded with spiritual might, if only we have the insight and the understanding to penetrate the Christian overlay. As this season draws to a close, it behooves us to embrace again the wisdom and strength of our Teutonic forebears, and to carry this spiritual inheritance into the days and months beyond. Hopefully you have observed these holy days and nights, hailed the Holy Powers, embraced your Folk literally and metaphorically, and opened yourself to the Gods and Goddesses,making the holidays into, truly, "holy-days." (It's not too late!) We - all of us - need to become more than we are. We must grow wiser and stronger, braver and bolder, more in love with our Folk and in love with the high Destiny that is ours, if only we have the will to grasp it! How will you be stronger? What will you do to earn high repute and folk-fame in the year to come? These are not rhetorical questions. Sit down and make your personal list today. How will you, metaphorically, "throw the Spear" of Awakening and of Wisdom over our Folk? How will you serve Wotan and his Way? This goes beyond "New Year's resolutions" - it should be your steadfast determination in the year to come...Grasp your greatness! Let's get going! We have a world to change! May the coming year give you health, prosperity, and power. Stephen McNallen

TOUCH THE SPIRITUAL POWER OF YULETlDE! wotannetwork.com - stephenmcnallen.com - t.me/Stephen_A_McNallen Yuletide is a time for family and fun, for renewing old contacts, for gifting and for getting together with friends, for relaxing...All this is true - but there's more: Yule is an opportunity to take your spiritual understanding and power to a new level. Some of this is obvious: Remembering ancestors, strengthening family bonds, exercising the traits of generosity and love, all these are valuable. Taking the "bah, humbug" approach is a sure sign of spiritual regression - and what a waste of opportunities! You probably don't need to be lectured on that. But how about taking it to a new level this year? The deep nature of things is different around the solstice-tide; it's not as simple as space and time, or darkness and light, or snow and chill - though all of these are factors. We have responded on a deep level to this time of year throughout much of our evolution, especially in the northern climes. Open yourself to that deeper connection - the connection to all those ancestors who touch us still. Sense the love, the hope, the striving. Become more than you are...and our Folk, past and present and future, in our time-transcending essence. becomes more. Bask in the wonder of it all. Have a happy, wonderful, transcendent, holy Yuletide! Stephen and Sheila McNallen

cleaned_message: WOTAN NETWORK AND THE "CULTURE OF RESISTANCE"wotannetwork.com - stephenmcnallen.com - t.me/TheWotan/Network - t.me/Stephen_A_McNallen It's always good to steal an enemy's best ideas..and one such idea is the "culture of resistance," popularized by Italian Communist Antonio Gramsci. The leftists have been very effective in wielding this weapon...but anything they can do, we can do better! In this strategy, an "oppressed" tribal or ethnic groups can use the features of its culture as weapons - things like spirituality, history, art, songs, mythology, folkways, and customs. All these can bolster the morale and pride of the group, giving its members a sense of unity and the will to resist erosion and absorption. Our folk can use these methods as well as anyone else. The wisdom tales ("myths") of our Folk, our spirituality, our history, our food and music and language, our symbols - all these are means to resist absorption. Anyone reading this should have no problem listing such cultural items and aggressively promoting them. Consider one of my favorite sayings: "Spirituality shapes culture...Culture shapes politics." By creating our own "culture of resistance" against degeneracy, cancel culture, and the anti-White (concealed as "anti-racist") efforts of our foes, we can make changes. Difficult? Not at all. Folk songs, poems, movies, cultural events like Highland games and Oktoberfest celebrations, the use of runes either alone or as part of an inscription, the display of symbols such as Thor's hammer, monthly Odin World Prayer Day - the list is endless. And it's fun. But don't settle for this! This is just the beginning! There's a lot more you can and should do...For more ideas on resistance, see Chapter Four in The Spear. Until next time...Stephen McNallen

WOTAN NETWORK...AND YOU! wotannetwork.com - stephenmcnallen.com - t.me/Stephen_A_McNallen I've always defined Wotan Network as a "networked psychological and spiritual warfare project." That's true, as far as it goes. What it doesn't say is that YOU can be a vital member of it. You don't have to send us dues, or fill out a membership application. All you have to do is 1. share our material and 2. tell others to do likewise. No membership lists, no meetings, no dues. No public recognition. No doxxing. Just a devotion to Gods and Folk. Wotan Network has never been an official thing. But we DO want others out there - specifically, YOU - to identify with Wotan Network, to consider yourself a "member" in an informal sense...Brothers and sisters united in a common cause,even if they have never met. You are part of an underground, connected to others by an invisible and informal bond, a gathering of ghosts. The "field manual" of these ghost battalions is The Spear. In its pages you will find motivation...methods...and hope. You can order it on https://www.stephenmcnallen.com. "Throw the Spear of Wotan" in your daily life. "Throw the Spear, and rewrite the runes that shape the world!" Stephen McNallen

"WOTAN ON THE PEAKS" OVERLOOKING MELBOURNE, AUSTRALIA On Nov 9 after work I undertook to go and complete a 'Wotan on the Peaks" at a local lookout here in Melbourne's hills. I took mead, my Gungnir pendant and knotwork ring, and my unopened copy of The Spear I'd been saving for this occasion. I found a small spear-like grove of white trees up away from the tourists (I actually felt Odin had picked it out) and as twilight began to set I offered the mead. As the night descended I opened my new copy of The Spear with just enough light to see Stephen McNallen's signature, and as I took up my Gungnir pendant that was lying next to the book I noticed something - the good megen connected with Stephen's signature was uber-strong. I felt honoured to have been able to sense and experience this. SUBMIT YOUR WOTAN NETWORK ACTIVITY TO: wolfagemedia@gmail.com

Make a habit of joy and it will seldom desert you. The joy you will feel will lift all those around you. WOTAN...ON THE DROP ZONE! wotannetwork.com - stephenmcnallen.com - t.me/Stephen_A_McNallen "Wotan on the Peaks" - climbing a mountain or hill to offer our devotion and our mead to Wotan - has become a sacred ceremony among many of us in Wotan Network and, for that matter, countless other people around the world. It is one of our most vital acts of spiritual resistance against the Age of Ultimate Degeneracy. But for those who want to push the limits just a bit more, there is now a new challenge... Let me introduce..."Wotan on the Drop Zone." A drop zone - sometimes shortened to "DZ" - is a field where parachutists land after jumping out of planes. Yesterday, to celebrate my 75th birthday, I did what is perhaps the first-ever "Wotan on the Drop Zone". Sheila and I, by prior arrangement, drove to a nearby skydiving facility, got our briefing, and connected with the experienced parachutists with whom I was going to make my tandem jump. I got my training session with a no-nonsense expert wearing a "Five Finger Death Punch" tee shirt - I knew right away I was going to like this guy - who put me through the procedure. This jump was considerably more complicated than my previous tandems, where I was basically just strapped along for the ride. This instructor had higher expectations: Not only was I directed to go into the usual arch and assume a good position, I had to observe the altimeter on my wrist and deploy the chute at five thousand feet. Finding the rip cord - which was on the instructor, not me - had to be done by feel, reaching behind me - which made it a little more complicated, but I executed it perfectly. The ride down was ecstatic. The roar in my ears sounded like an explosion that never ended. The adrenaline was pumping like crazy. I spoke my words to Wotan, in English and in German, and just went with the high. The landing was easier than I expected. After dropping gear, Sheila and I took a horn and a growler of mead off to one side, and shared a horn of mead with the High One. I would have included my jumpmaster as well, but he was already gearing up for another jump. Hail Wotan, God of our Ancestors, God of our Folk! May our love and devotion awaken our sleeping brothers and sisters!

THE WAY OF WOTAN - THE NORDIC SOUL COMPLEX by Anders Nilsson stephenmcnallen.com - wotannetwork.com - t.me/Stephen_A_McNallen Anders Nilsson is perhaps best known as the man who founded Odin World Prayer Day, a long-distance monthly ritual with participants all around the world. But now he has added to his resume by writing a very useful book, titled The Way of Wotan - The Nordic Soul Complex. I had the honor of writing the foreword to this book, and now we all have the pleasure of reading it. While it does explain the multiple components of the Nordic soul, it includes much more than that! The reader also learns how and when to give blot to the deities of the North, how to begin working with runes, and, perhaps most intriguing of all, how to seek one's fylgja. It is published by Logik Forlag, at https://butik.logik.se/collections/english-books. Your collection won't be complete without it! It makes a very nice companion to my own recent book, The Spear!

cleaned_message: GOTHIC RUNES" BY FRITZ MAES: - PUT IT ON YOUR LIST! stephenmcnallen.com - wotannetwork.com - t.me/Stephen_A_McNallen I thought I had read most of the important books about runes - but here is one I missed! I have been familiar with the Elder Futhark, Younger Futhark, and Anglo-Saxon Futhorc for literally decades. What I had NOT run across was a text on the Gothic runes. Well, now I have, and it is amazing. It's available through Lulu. Ten chapters, 260 pages, on topics including the history of the Goths (and theories of their origin), a breakdown of each individual rune and its meaning in Gothic, an original rune-poem by the author for each of the twenty-four runes, plus commentary, maps, and photographs - the works. Maes finishes up with an extensive list of sources for those who want to know more. Gothic Runes is an electronic book (PDF), designed to print as an attractive paper volume for those who wish to do so. A visit to Fritz Maes' Lulu page reveals a fascinating list of other works by the author: Germanic Chivalry, which is mostly about fighting arts, Ringen, covering medieval German wrestling, and Princely Singers of Eros, about the composers of erotic love ballads during the Middle Ages. His works are listed at https://www.lulu.com/spotlight/fritzmaes. Stephen McNallen

MY EARLIEST EXPOSURE TO ODIN stephenmcnallen.com - t.me/Stephen_A_McNallen - wotannetwork.com I often cite the novel The Viking, by Edison Marshall, as the book that brought me to Odin. - and that's true. But I had an earlier exposure to Him, which I had all but forgotten for a very long time. You'll laugh, but here it is: My dad used to go down to a local store and buy his cigars - El Producto Favoritos. Sometimes he took me with him, and he would let me buy a comic book -even though they cost a whole dime back in those days. (We're talking my age being maybe eight to ten years old, so this was about 1956 or 1958.) Donald Duck was a favorite. Now, these comic books could actually be educational. In one episode, the Ducks set off to find the Philosopher's Stone. In another, they engaged the Minotaur. I am sure there were other such classic adventures, but another one, which I was to remember many years later, had the Duck family in Norway. Deep inside a cave, they encountered Odin and Thor, and perhaps others. But the Gods were mere shapes, mere shadows of themselves, ghostly. Why? When asked, they responded that it was because no one believed in them anymore. I don't remember anything else about the story. Did it make me interested in Norse mythology? No. Did it have any part in the Awakening? Not really. I pretty much forgot about it. It was not a cause of the Awakening... but somehow, it was a forerunner. Today, the story would have a happier ending!

RUNE OF THE SPEAR! stephenmcnallen.com - wotannetwork.com - t.me/Stephen_A_McNallen Each chapter of The Spear, opens with a particular rune, complete with stanzas from the rune poems, relevant to that chapter. The last chapter summarizes the symbolic "taking up Wotan's Spear" by personal transformation and cultural/political activity. The only problem - the common rune-rows do not have a rune meaning, specifically, "spear." I had to look beyond the runic "alphabets" with which I usually work...and finally, I found it! A later addition to the Anglo-Saxon rune row was, indeed, "Gar," or "spear." But unlike the earlier runes, it had no verse attached to it...So I wrote one, using the basic structure of the Anglo-Saxon verses. Here it is: The noble ones take up the spear Not iron and ash, but wit and will. Their folk to save, great fame to win. The athelings grips the gar, Fling it far over the foe And write the runes to reshape the world. - S. McNallen Wotan, Be With Us! Stephen McNallen

"Detatching from smart tech is a revolutionary act." So true - indeed, it is a "revolt against the modern world."
In The Spear, I address this issue. There are three imminent and existential threats we face: the surveillance state, central bank digital currency (CBDC), and firearms confiscation and/or tracking.

If you have a smartphone they can monitor your online interactions, who you text, call, email and the websites and social media you use. If you have a smart meter they can monitor your energy use, when you boil the kettle, turn the heating on and when you turn all the lights of at the end of the day. If you have a smart watch they can monitor your physical activity and health, even in your sleep. If you have a smart door bell they can monitor who comes to your door and when you leave the house. If you have a smart TV they can monitor what you watch and when you watch it. Data is the new oil and we have willingly yet unwittingly become an income stream for a parasitic entity. Detaching from smart tech is a revolutionary act.

THE GREAT DOWN-GOING stephenmcnallen.com - wotannetwork.com - t.me/Stephen_A_McNallen The Wall Street Journal recently released an article titled "Americans Pull Back from Values that Once Defined Us," released the results of a poll analyzing the changes in American culture over the last twenty years. Here are the results: Twenty years ago, 70 percent of Americans described themselves as patriots; today that has dropped to 38 percent.Those who thought religion was important fell from 62 percent to 39 percent.The percent of those to whom having children was important went from 59 percent to 30 percent.Americans who thought community involvement was important went from 62 percent to 27 percent.Those who thought having a lot of money was important increased from 31percent to 43 percent. I am somewhat ambivalent about some of these points - but it is clear that America has changed a lot, mostly for the worse. We are afflicted by a cultural malaise - Spengler's "decline of the West." Two things in particular stand out: (1) When it comes to valuing children, we know that White folks are indeed being replaced, not just in America, but worldwide. (2) The declining interest in community involvement is a clear sign of our inward-turnng, our preoccupation with the cell phone, social media, and the internet generally. I address both of these problems, and others, in my soon-to-be-published book, The Spear. We must create a new culture, a culture that favors our people, a culture of resistance against the Borg, against the media-mind, against cybernetic domination. A return to our spiritual roots is the answer...But our salvation does not lie in the faiths of the Middle East. We must take up the Spear of Wotan...the Spear of Awakening, of Wisdom, of Sovereignty, of Initiation. Wotan shows the way!

Humans are ritual-building beings. Anthropologists have defined us as "tool-using animals" and as "time-binding animals", and even as "symbol-using animals". I will pass over the question of whether or not we are animals, but surely the building of rituals encompasses all three of these-a sense of time and symbols, as well as the ability to construct tools (spiritual ones, in this case). Evidence for deliberate ritual can be found in Neanderthal burial customs, so it‚Äôs clear we‚Äôve been doing this sort of thing for a long time. For some reason, ritual innately appeals to us and it makes sense, then, that we ought to be doing it. S.McNallen

I was asked to give some words to be read at the memorial in Dresden today. Here is what I sent: A MESSAGE FROM AMERICA ON THIS DAY OF SADNESS From 1973 to 1976 I had the privilege of serving as a young American Infantry officer, stationed in Germany. During those years, I spent most of my weekends traveling around the country, walking literally hundreds of miles on back roads and in small towns. I also participated in programs with the German military, earning its paratrooper wings and taking part in other exercises with German soldiers. I stayed with German families for days at a time, and I came to love Germany and the German people. I remember the day our Infantry battalion made a reconnaissance of the front lines we would defend if the Soviet tanks ever came pouring through the Fulda Gap. I looked at the hills before me, and thought of the horrors of war - and I was determined to do my best, if war came, to defend Germany. The Russians never came, but now I must defend Germany in another way - by speaking of the needless horror inflicted on Dresden by those who hated Her. When I think of the many thousands of ordinary men, women, and children - ordinary, helpless civilians - incinerated and suffocated in the bombing raids we remember today, my heart breaks. I will remember them this day and light a candle...a flame of love and remembrance, not the fire of hatred and death. All soldiers understand that people die in war. We also understand that the innocent die, not just soldiers. But the bombing of Dresden was different; it was a war crime. I am not the only one who thinks so; a highly decorated British pilot named Victor Gregg, who was a prisoner of war in Dresden and witnessed the horror, calls it what it was - murder. You can find his testimony online. Were there valuable industrial targets in Dresden? Yes. Was it necessary to kill many thousands of innocent civilians to hit those targets? No. The decision to bomb civilian targets and ‚Äúdisplace‚Äù German industrial workers was made by the British Bomber Command, approved by Churchill in 1942. They were ‚Äúdisplaced‚Äù indeed - their ashes drifted on the winds. This was an act of pure hatred.. No more brother wars! Hail to the fallen! Let us honor their memory, and grieve. If we ever fight again, let us fight together!

url_title: Your mind is much older than you think | genetic memory & Carl Jung's collective unconscious
url_description: How old is your mind? And is there such a thing as genetic memory? These ideas have been explored in video games and films like Assassin‚Äôs Creed. But it‚Äôs not a new idea. It can be traced to psychologist Carl Jung‚Äôs concept of the collective unconscious. Our traditional understanding is that memories are formed through networks of neurons in the brain. But researchers are discovering a new kind of memory that‚Äôs stored within the nucleus of neurons, deep within our DNA. Carl Jung‚Äôs work builds on the work of his one-time friend, colleague, and fellow psychologist Sigmund Freud, who posited that we have a conscious mind (which is made up of all the things we‚Äôre aware of, including the ego) and an unconscious mind, with is a repository of repressed desires, thoughts and memories. Freud hoped that Jung would be his successor and carry on his work, but this would never come to pass. Their disagreements grew as Jung made this own development and took his own direction in psychology, which diverged sharply from Freud‚Äôs. One of their major disagreements, was Jung‚Äôs concept of the collective unconscious, a kind of universal human memory that‚Äôs imprinted in the psyche; a storehouse of symbols and imagery that‚Äôs independent of time and space. We can think of it as a kind of universal ancestral memory, and we inherit the collective unconscious from our ancient ancestors, and it‚Äôs common to every person and every culture in the world. It‚Äôs the part of the mind that we all have available to us, and we can all tap into. Jung maintained that the collective unconscious was made up of psychic structures that are universal, that form all the elements of human experience, and are expressed as reoccurring patterns that shape our lives. He called these patterns archetypes. Examples of archetypes include the great mother. The wise old man. And the trickster. We see versions of these archetypes in every culture in the world. Other archetypes include the persona, and the shadow. Perhaps the most powerful archetype in Jung‚Äôs approach are numbers. Jung came to believe that the numbers 1 to 9 were some of the potent archetypal symbols of the psyche, and were the most basic and universal symbols we have. Jung once wrote that ‚Äúnumber and synchronicity were always brought into connection with one another, both possess numinosity and mystery as their common characteristics, and all numbers from 1 to 9 are sacred.‚Äù Jung believed that everything is connected. That there‚Äôs an underlying unified reality from which everything emerges and to which everything returns. He called this idea Unus Mundus. This bears a striking similarity to the ancient Chinese concept of Qi, which is the vital energy that flows through all things.
