December, 1993 - Somewhere over the African continent‚Ä¶ The flight from Johannesburg to Amsterdam must be the longest one in the world. I sped through the thin air at thirty thousand feet, a drink in my hand and a pillow under my head. Far below me lay the sweltering heat and the human misery of the country I‚Äôd just spent three weeks trying to get into - Angola. My goal had been to link up with the rebel UNITA forces fighting for control of the country and interview their charismatic leader, Jonas Savimbi. At the least, the interview would have helped me pay off the credit card debt I had incurred by jaunting all over southern Africa. Better yet, I might have ended up on Savimbi‚Äôs payroll. Alas, it had all come to naught. I had flown to Katima Mulilo - scene of furious fighting between the South African army and Cubans years before. From there, I had ridden in the back of a truck to the tiny town of Bagani where I missed my UNITA contact by seconds. I spent the next three weeks trying to reestablish link-up, but luck was not with me. On the last possible day I could catch my plane back to the United States, I flew out of Johannesburg for Europe. Another day‚Äôs travel, and I would be arriving in San Francisco. But you know, the thought that I had not succeeded in getting into Angola really irked me. So I did the only reasonable thing‚Ä¶I got off the plane in Amsterdam, forfeited the rest of the ticket to San Francisco, and caught a train to Bosnia...

cleaned_message: WE ARE EVERYWHERE...EPISODE ONE Years ago, I was in the jungle HQ of the Karen National Liberation Army, in Myanmar (formerly Burma). I had come all the way from the USA to see if I could be of help, even if the only aid I could give was to write an article for SOF magazine. The monsoon was on full force and fighting had pretty well bogged down to zero, there was nowhere to go and not much to do. I was hanging out to see if any operations were pending, when in stumbled another White man - the first I had seen in weeks! - soaked, carrying his rifle. We introduced ourselves; it turned out he was from Germany, a physical therapist who on his vacations came to Myanmar to teach sniping. Small talk ensued. At one point i saw he was staring at my chest - I looked down, to see that my Thor's hammer had slipped out of my shirt. He looked at me and, wordless, reached into his shirt and pulled out his own. Two men, one blood, a common connection to the Gods of our greater Folk.

I had the bear back on my front porch again in the pre-dawn. I could see better this time; he looks like a yearling. This bear is the fourth one I have seen up close. Two times, they were in an obviously spiritual context, i.e., in direct connection with a ritual. "Going to visit your friends in person, rather than electronically, qualifies as a revolt against the modern world. So does speaking to strangers, and looking people in the eye. Break down the barriers that keep us isolated and helpless against the Borg...the Machine...the Hive." - from the chapter "Toward a Culture of Resistance" in The Spear.

From my upcoming book, "The Spear" - We need a "culture of resistance" in which spirituality, folk history, art, mythology, songs, folkways - in short, our traditional culture - becomes our weapon of choice...A culture of resistance uses meanings and symbols to contest and combat a dominant power,and constructing a different vision of the world in the process.
Hail the heartbeat of the wild...

I just had a bear on my front porch - about 0415, in the pre-dawn gloom....and I live in an area with houses only a couple of hundred yards apart...I hope he finds his way back home; it can't end well for him here. What a majestic animal...I don't believe in accidents when it comes to things like this...What is the spiritual and/or synchronistic message for me? May the bear be blessed,and find his way back to the wild. Raiding the cat's bowl is below him; sad.

We are all honored to be here, in this Age of Ultimate Degeneracy, this Wolf Age, to fight this battle! When we tire, when things look their darkest, we must remember that the light will come again...and that we helped to make it so! So smile, kameraden; the blows of our foes only make our glory greater. Let this coming year be a year of victory!

Well, I haven't got that article written yet...overwhelmed by Yuletide...Hail to all reading this; may your forefathers and foremothers whisper in your ear, may this season bless your life and give you inner peace, among the outer strife.

"Better to die than to be slaves! But better yet to thrive, rise up in greatness, become wise and empowered and sovereign, in the image of Wotan, Father of the Gods, Lord of Battle, Leader of Hosts!" - from, "The Spear"

Yesterday was the first day of Yuletide, when we lit a candle and reminded ourselves of Industriousness and our need to accomplish. Today is the second day of Yuletide, when we remember Justice as we light the candle...When we are just, we live up to that which is noblest within us.

"And how can man die better than facing fearful odds, For the ashes of his fathers, and the temples of his Gods..." - from "Horatius at the Bridge" by Thomas Babington McAulay, and still true after all these years. Hail our Ancestors! Hail our Folk!

From a friend of the Network: Today, I ventured into the beautiful Appalachian hills to honor the High One. It was medium level trails with ascending steps up the cliff face to the top. A nice bit of effort to offer him on his day. At the top of the cliff I blessed the mead and offered my wishes and the whole horn to Odin. As I made my descent, I had an epiphany that not only ritual, but this hiking effort were done in circuits. Just as in the laws of electricity. If the circuit is broken, it will not work. In a sea of camouflaged red, yellow, orange and brown leaves I spotted a sprig of green oak leaves. There were 5 leaves. Rit is the 5th rune in the Armanen Futhark and literally means ritual, order, and doing things correctly. Synchronicity at work. Hail Wotan! It's time to wake up. TWO AMAZING FINDS IN FIVE MINUTES! Sheila was going through some old boxes and guess what she found...First, a diary I carried with me on my first trip to Africa, in 1976. The opening entry was dated 17 May, from In Salah, Algeria..."My first meal here - lunch yesterday - was composed of rice and camel meat in a spicy sauce, and tasted better than anything I have eaten in days." I had a long trip before me, heading down through the Sahara via the central route. What a flood of memories! Minutes later, she produced photos of my mother, and aunt Shirley, and others when they were children. Brought tears to my eyes...blood and soul connected through the generations, and ultimately, forever. I'll try to produce photos later.

Speaking of diets...Here's a response I made to someone who was suggesting that being a carnivore should be necessary for AFA membership....I'm not dissing him, he has a right to his opinion...but here is my response: i get your point about meat, and personally I am definitely a carnivore. That said, it seems that to make something like that a requirement for membership would be over the top. Let's leave dietary requirements for the Abrahamic faiths. One of the toughest, most dedicated, most honorable men I ever knew was a vegetarian - and an AFA member and follower of Wotan up to the time of his death: Jost Turner. Many of you may be familiar with his writings; he founded a yoga path which he called Arya Kriya. For those who don't know his story: Jost was a Vietnam veteran...101 Airborne...Recondo...who had fought at Hamburger Hill - one of the bloodiest battles of that conflict. Politically...well, let's just say that he was as dialed on the racial issue as anyone you will ever meet. But as a practitioner of yoga, he was a vegetarian. And trust me, up to the day he died...if it had been Right Action (as the yogis call it) or the principle behind the rune Raido (as we would call it)...He would not have hesitated to have terminated someone and hidden the body in a mineshaft. I had the honor of helping to make his coffin. My Thor's hammer - which fell off my neck as I bent over the coffin lid - rests with him. So do a pair of my jump wings. Recommend carnivorism, maybe. Making it a matter of faith? Maybe not.
Or maybe it's because I am doing intermittent fasting today - hunger destroys my ability to spell.
Too bad I couldn't spell "culture" right - I got in a hhury, I gess.

"FREE MEN"....A couple of days ago I was re-reading a short story by Robert Heinlein titled "Free Men," in a hypothetical future in which America is an occupied nation and guerrilla forces are fighting the occupiers. The title comes from a statement in the story that "You can't enslave a free man. Only person who can do that is a man himself. No sir, you can't enslave a free man - the worst you can do is kill him." Powerful words in an age when we seem all to eager to put the chains on our own wrists.
This is us, up on the peak!

WOTAN ON THE PEAKS - RUSSIAN WILDERNESS, NORTHERN CALIFORNIA! stephenmcnallen.com - wotannetwork.com - t.me/Stephen_A_McNallen Upward we climbed - adults, children, a baby and a dog! - on a mountain overlooking the roughest terrain in northern California. The going was rocky, the trail sometimes clear, often questionable. By the time we got to the peak, tiny flakes of snow were falling on our shoulders and salting my beard. We ate a light trail meal, rested a bit, and gave blot to the Father of Our Folk; he who is Odin, and Wotan, and Woden to our forefathers. We each touched the horn to give our gifts, and after the giving of them, shared another horn filled with the gifts of the High One, the god of a hundred names. Five miles, in all...from Midgard to the edge of the God-Home, and down the trail again. Joy, and uplifting in every way. Wotan, God of our forefathers and foremothers, God of our Folk! Awaken us, that our Folk may always Be, and Become, and Overcome, down through the ages! "The existence of my people is not negotiable."

cleaned_message: There's a conversation over on Wotan Network Comment Board, on Telegram, about dying and going to Valhalla...That's all very well, and someday I hope to make the cut on that. People forget, though, that there is a path to Odin's hall aside from the warrior way, and that is the way of the wise...by which I mean the way of the mystic. Master yourself, master the mysteries of the runes, fight nobly whether with literal weapons or metaphorical ones, and I am pretty sure that you will be welcome to the Hall of the High One. No, I can't quote the Eddas to support that, but that's what I believe.

GLORIOUS DEATH, OR GLORIOUS LIFE? When I was an ROTC student back in the late Sixties, I dreamed of joining Special Forces, going to Vietnam, killing Cong, and dying gloriously. I was young, dumb, and full of...testosterone. I am now an old "former" soldier. "Former" because I am still imprinted with the military mindset; my jump wings and Ranger tab are tattooed on my arm not to be cool, but to remind ME every day of the standards to which I hold myself. I'm older and wiser than I was; death is seldom - some would say never - glorious. No man knows if he is "Einherjar quality" until he's tested. It's not about bravado, it's about duty. Until the crunch comes, I will not know if I meet that standard. In the meantime, I strive at the tasks before me. The famous expression is "Duty - Honor - Country," (or "Folk" as the case may be} - not "DEATH - Honor - Country." In the meantime, I do my best to lead a glorious LIFE. Stephen McNallen stephenmcnallen.com - wotannetwork.com - t.me/Stephen_A_McNallen

LIFE, STRUGGLE - AND JOY! Many years ago, someone - it may have been my Shorin-Ryu sensei - said that "Life is kumite" - that is, combat. In my mind, that conjures an image of someone blocking, striking, and kicking against multiple opponents from different directions - someone constantly alert, clear-headed, and responsive. That image has never left me - and as the years go by, it seems more and more relevant. "Kumite" sounds a lot like "multitasking." It sounds better in German - "Das Leben ist Kampf." Sometimes, for all of us fighting for the existence and well-being of our people, the odds seem to be stacked against us. We have not yet learned to love ourselves, to value that wondrous thing that we are, and to work for our high Destiny. But we are rousing from our slumber, albeit gradually. As we learn to love our ancestors, and to value the inheritance - cultural, biological, historical - that they left us, our Awakening will accelerate. Learn to love the struggle! If we do it right, it earns us satisfaction, even a sense of inner joy! And as Herr Nietsche noted in his famous quote, it makes us stronger. At the end of the road lies victory. ..Or as Jost Turner wrote in a song, "Fight your battles and dare the odds, drink your mead and praise the Gods..." What have you done for our Folk today? For the memory of our ancestors? For the honor of our Gods and Goddesses? For the future existence and well-being of our people? A few days ago we celebrated Winter Finding at Odinshof. It was, as always, an inspiring and motivating experience. Whatever the calendar might say, there is that moment when you realize that summer is fading, and that fall has arrived. Appropriately, the day we were to meet at the Hof I awoke to find that, indeed, the air had a chill to it! After the sweat and swelter of the recent weeks, it was a delight. Indeed, I had found the first hint of winter! It was, literally, ‚ÄúWinter Finding.‚Äù Read the rest at https://stephenmcnallen.com/winter-and-our-awakening/

TWO PHOTOS FROM WINTER FINDING As promised - One is at our "Greeting to the Gods," when we introduce ourselves and toast a deity of choice. Odin, of course, in my case. The other is taken during the Ullr blot. As I impart "my might, my main, and my troth" to the horn to be offered to Ullr. Sporting my kilt in both shots...

THE HERO OF STAMFORD BRIDGE This morning, it suddenly hit me that September 25th was, for some reason, a special date. A quick search revealed that this was the anniversary of the Battle of Stamford Bridge, fought on this day in 1066 between King Harold Godwinson of England, and Harald of Norway. I always remember this battle because of the bravery of one man, a Norwegian whose name has not come down to us but who, I am sure, was remembered by Odin and his valkyries. The unnamed hero was a man wielding a broad axe, standing atop a wooden bridge in northern England. He was the only fighter blocking the advance of the English troops as the Norwegians hastily assembled their shield wall. Ultimately it was to no avail; an Englishman managed to spear the axeman from below. The Norwegians lost the battle and their dreams of conquest died with the axe-wielding warrior. Whoever he was, he will be long remembered, and in some circles - like ours! - he will be toasted.

WINTER FINDING AT ODINSHOF - OUTSTANDING! "Winter Finding" lived up to its name. The day before we were to gather at the Hof, the sweltering heat that has weighed on us for weeks decided to break, with temperatures in the 70"s...Delightful! So yes, in a sense, we "found" winter! On a whim - which may become a habit - I wore my utilikilt (the one I wore to the Pleasanton Scottish Games a couple of weeks ago). I wore a dark red dress shirt and finished off my attire with a tie sporting the County Tyrone plaid. And yes, it was cool enough to wear something under the kilt! (This is now an unofficial definition of the first day of winter.) I gave a talk comparing the coming of winter with the decline of a society (ours) - the victory, at least temporary, of "Ice" over "Fire." I'll be posting an improved version of it on my website in the next couple of days, and I hope you find it of interest. Like I said in the title, "photos to come." I'd have posted a couple tonight, but other things got in the way so it will have to wait!

A BLAST FROM STEVE'S PAST! Zambezi Shell, in Katima Mulilo, Namibia...Just across the border from Angola. You can find it on Google Earth. I recall sitting there for hours, hitching a ride to Bagani to meet someone who would take me across the line....With that old song about "Here I am, on the road again..." running through my head. That was back in the day when Jonas Savimbi, in Angola, was fighting the Cubans. My contact never showed up, which probably was for the best, as I had been given some really poor intel by some people in Johannesburg, possibly on purpose. I still hate Commies, though.

cleaned_message: EVACUATION - So far Sheila and I have not had to head out the door to escape a fire, and odds are we won't have to, at least not today...but we're keeping an eye on things...last we heard the fire pictured in my post yesterday is zero percent contained. Ironically it's named the Mosquito Fire but it's one helluva big mosquito. A tip - If you are ever in a situation where you might need to bug out with little notice - for whatever reason; fire, tornado, pursuit by people who want to hurt you - It's good to have a list of what to grab, by priority. Take a sheet of paper, divide it into quarters and label each section with a time window: 15 minutes, 30 minutes, one hour. more than one hour. In each quarter note what you would take if you had that amount of time before shutting the door behind you.
